<FIRST>u w AM-Chantee-Bush     09-13 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chantee-Bush,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush-Drugs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirteen-year-old Chantee Charles thought she'd
made the wrong impression. But if she were to do it over again,
she'd still let President Bush have a piece of her mind.
   As it happened, Bush took it in stride when the Arlington, Va.
youngster delivered a surprise lecture against the death penalty
during an anti-drug ceremony at the White House on Wednesday.
   ``To me, killing someone that has committed a very serious crime
is wrong,'' Chantee told the Rose Garden crowd assembled to honor
the Drug Abuse Resistence Education project, DARE. ``It does not
solve anything. All it does is take someone else's life.''
   Bush, a longtime backer of capital punishment and an advocate of
extending the death penalty to drug kingpins, hardly seemed put off
by his youthful critic. Indeed, he complimented Chantee and two
other teenagers who also addressed the gathering for saying ``what's
on your heart'' without worrying ``if people agree with you or not.''
   Chantee said she had formulated her speech without really knowing
that Bush was such a staunch advocate of the death penalty, and,
when first questioned about her speech by reporters ``thought I had
made the wrong impression.'' But White House aides later assured
her, just as the president did himself, that no offense was taken,
she said.
   In any case, she wouldn't have done anything differently, she
added. ``In DARE classes, they teach you not to stoop down to
pressures, to be your own person and not let your friends take you
down,'' she said. ``It's important for me to know that other people
know how I really feel.''
   Her White House surprise was reminiscent of an episode nearly 20
years ago, when a young Madison, Wis., woman, Debra Jean Sweet,
admonished President Nixon for his conduct of the Vietnam war after
he had presented her with a medal for exceptional public service.
   Nixon had drawn her ire when he contrasted her with ``the very
small minority of young Americans who have lost faith in their
country.'' She retorted that ``I cannot believe in your sincerity
until you get us out of Vietnam.'' Later she explained that ``I saw
him using me as a symbol and I refused to become that symbol.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
