<FIRST>r a AM-DrugAgentSlain     09-13 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Agent Slain,0475</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Blocks Release of Mexican Millionaire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court Wednesday blocked a
judge's order setting $200,000 bail for the brother-in-law of
Mexico's former president after prosecutors sought time to appeal
the decision.
   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeal granted a stay on the order
issued Tuesday by U.S. District Court Judge Robert Takasugi. The
order would have resulted in freedom for Ruben Zuno Arce, 59, a
Mexican businessman linked by authorities to drug trafficking. He
has been in prison since Aug. 9.
   The appeals court gave prosecutors until Monday to appeal the
release order and gave the defense until Sept. 25 to file responses.
   ``We'll just have to abide by the court's order and wait for the
ruling,'' said Zuno's attorney, Edward Medvene.
   Zuno was charged with perjury before a federal grand jury last
week after spending nearly a month in custody without being charged
with any crime. He was held initially as a material witness in the
1985 torture murder of U.S. Drug Enforcement agent Enrique Camarena.
   Prosecutors contend that Zuno, a millionaire who has vast
business holdings in Mexico, would flee to his native country and
never return if he is freed.
   Zuno's sister is the wife of former Mexican President Luis
Echeverria.
   Takasugi, who ruled that Zuno could not be held without bail,
said that the defendant could sign a waiver of extradition and a
promise to return to federal court when he is summoned.
   The government wants Zuno to testify in the trial of a recently
charged defendant in the Camarena case, Juan Jose Bernabe-Ramirez, a
former member of the Jailisco State Judicial Police.
   Prosecutors have linked Zuno to the sale of a home in Guadalajara
that was subsequently bought by Mexican drug lord Rafael
Caro-Quintero. Authorities believe Camarena was murdered at the
house.
   Zuno's lawyers say the house was sold through an intermediary and
Zuno knew nothing about the murder.
   Caro, who is accused of orchestrating the murders, is in custody
awaiting trial in Mexico City. Seven more men are charged with
murder and conspiracy in the case.
   Zuno testified before a federal grand jury for two days, and
another judge ruled then that he had little information to offer and
should be released. At that point, immigration officials demanded
his return to San Antonio, Texas, for investigation of whether he
was a narcotics trafficker.
   While in Texas, he was charged with perjury in Los Angeles and
was returned again. He was accused of lying when he said he didn't
know Caro or Ernesto Fonseca Carillo, another key defendant in the
Camarena case.
   Prosecutors have said they consider Zuno ``significant'' in the
Camarena investigation, but have refused to say why.
</TEXT>
