<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--JewishVandalism     09-13 0152</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Jewish Vandalism,0155</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Jewish Student Leader Arrested for Spray-painting Swastikas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BINGHAMTON, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former president of a Jewish
students' group at the state University at Binghamton was charged
Wednesday with painting anti-Semitic slurs on the group's
headquarters last year.
   Broome County District Attorney Gerald Mollen said James
Oppenheim, 20, was charged with fourth-degree criminal mischief and
third-degree falsely reporting an incident.
   Oppenheim, a junior, was president of the Jewish Student Union
when slurs and swastikas _ a symbol used by Nazi Germany _ were
painted on the group's office and sanctuary on Nov. 10, 1988. It was
the eve of the 50th anniversary of Kristallnacht, the night Nazi
stormtroopers began their reign of terror against German Jews by
smashing up their stores and homes.
   Oppenheim was quoted at the time as condemning the act as
``horrible'' and ``hurtful.'' He also speculated the vandalism was a
calculated political act.
</TEXT>
