<FIRST>r a PM-Bush-Schools     09-13 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Schools,0497</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grandfatherly Advice: Students Supportive, But Not Optimistic</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Congress-Drugs, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Many of the kids listening to the president's grandfatherly
advice that ``Saying `no' won't make you a nerd,'' found it just one
more bit of well-meaning advice from an adult far from the front
lines in the drug war.
   ``I don't think it had that much effect because drug dealers are
going to still go out and deal and people are going to still go out
and buy drugs because it's addictive,'' said Jason McNally, a
seventh-grader in Elmhurst, Ill.
   ``It needs a lot more to stop it,'' said 10-year-old Amos Dunn, a
fifth-grader in Boston. The only answer is ``not making any more
drugs,'' he concluded.
   Like Amos, other pupils who watched Bush's televised speech
Tuesday demonstrated intimate awareness of the problem. And many
wondered if anything the president says is goingto make a difference.
   Tres Whitlow, a 12-year-old classmate of Jason's at Carl Sandburg
Junior High in the middle-class Chicago suburb, said warnings from
parents or politicians pale beside pressure teen-agers feel _ from
their peers and from dealers _ to try drugs.
   ``They see drug dealers tell them it's going to make them do
better,'' said Tres, 12.
   From Roosevelt Junior High School in Glendale, Calif., came
comments much like some heard in Congress.
   ``I think he should have been tougher,'' said Katherine Jo,
ninth-grade class president at the suburban Los Angeles school. ``He
doesn't know how bad it is.''
   Some supported the president.
   At Sandburg, 12-year-old Christine Gershak took heart in the
president's message that there are people willing to help youths
resist drugs. ``I think it will make a big impact because the kids
will, like, know what to do, to go for help,'' she said.
   But classmate Tania Durdevic, 12, noted Bush didn't address one
of the causes of drug abuse.
   ``Some kids might take drugs because they have family problems
and think nobody likes them,'' Tania said. ``But, like, my life is
really good, my family _ I know they care about me.''
   Amos and his classmates at Mattahunt Elementary School in
inner-city Boston were all too familiar with the dangers Bush warned
them about. They see it on the streets, and what they learn there
often is embellished with what they get from television.
   ``The white people are supplying it to black people, who are
selling it to black people. Like on TV,'' said Larry Bates, 11. ``It
makes me feel bad seeing black people are using it. I'm black. I'm
not going to be using it.''
   The teacher of the Boston class, Ouida Kalokoh, warns her
students about drugs. But she didn't know the ingredients in crack _
until her pupils filled her in.
   ``I was told everything, and they were fourth-graders,'' she
said, dismay in her voice. ``They knew all about it.''
</TEXT>
