<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 0103EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BlueBanjo     09-13 0973</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Blue Banjo,1002</SECOND>
<HEAD>Flashers, Drugs and Death: Business as Usual at Yakima Bar</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   There's a certain kind of bar in the tough part
of town, any town, where business goes on pretty much as usual no
matter what happens. If a couple regulars don't show up, no one pays
any attention. If it turns out they're lying in the alley out back,
nothing happens. And if they're dead?
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By LUIS CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YAKIMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Death dropped in at the Blue Banjo one
Sunday, and nobody even noticed.
   Richard O'Bennick and Frank Woodworth lay by the back steps for
more than six hours on a 90-degree day before anyone realized they
weren't asleep.
   Two nights later, the jukebox blared a Johnny Cash song about a
Dallas bordello. A haggard group of men lounged in the alley behind
the Blue Banjo, talking and sharing a jug. On the sidewalk out front
drug deals went down.
   Business as usual.
   Inside, a couple of Mexican farmworkers played pool on a ragged
blue-slate table. A half-dozen men sat at barstools, laughing once
in a while and trading jokes with the bartender.
   A blonde woman with a bandage wrapped around her hand and missing
a front tooth danced a little as she walked from the jukebox to her
table. A man strutted behind her, mimicking. She turned and swiped
him on the shoulder. They laughed.
   O'Bennick and Woodworth used to come in, when they had cash.
   ``They certainly take these fellows' money readily enough and
give them alcohol. They're friends as long as they have money,''
said Roger Phillips, who runs the 100-bed Union Gospel Mission.
   Robert MacLemore, a kitchen worker across town at the Blue Ox
restaurant and O'Bennick's sometime drinking buddy, took a seat at
the orange formica-topped bar. ``He would go up and try to bum for
money, and I got to know him. He would always be glad to see me
coming. He knew I always had money on me, you see.''
   MacLemore last saw O'Bennick the Wednesday before he died, and
gave him all of his bus fare so the transient could buy a quart of
beer. MacLemore walked to work. O'Bennick ``was a nice person, he
really was. But he was lonely. He had something down inside of him
that was eating him away,'' he said.
   O'Bennick ``had a lot of good in him,'' said Phillips, whose
mission was the dead men's last address. He ``always carried a
trombone around and talked about playing it,'' though Phillips never
actually saw him blow a note.
   MacLemore remembered Woodworth as a quiet, heavy-set man who
walked around on crutches and loved to drink wine. ``He was older.
Well, he looked old, but he wasn't as old as I am. He was in his
late 40s, maybe early 50s.''
   After two autopsies and tests for poison, the cause of
O'Bennick's and Woodworth's deaths on Aug. 6 remains a mystery. The
men's bodies sat in the late-summer heat, a jug of Almaden Blush
Chablis between them, long enough to start decomposing before
anybody knew they were dead.
   Yakima County Coroner Leonard Birkenbine wasn't surprised. ``You
go down there, there's always somebody lying down like that.''
   The tavern, with a blue neon sign that's read ``lue Banjo'' as
long as anyone could remember, is in the tough section of Yakima, a
central Washington town of 50,000 that is best known for apples,
cherries and vineyards but is fast developing a reputation as a
rural drug center.
   In a block wedged between a residential district and a restaurant
strip are the Blue Banjo, another tavern and a long-vacant building
with barred doors.
   ``We did have an extensive problem some time ago down there,''
said police Capt. Don Blesio. ``For the most part the problem has
been reduced considerably, but we're suffering from the cocaine and
heroin problems that exist.''
   ``It's tough there, it really is,'' MacLemore said. ``You can get
hurt there. You can get killed there.''
   Bob Briggs, who said he was released from the Washington state
penitentiary in Walla Walla that day after serving eight years for
burglary and auto theft, watched the Blue Banjo scene from the
corner barstool.
   ``I asked where the toughest place in town was, and they told me
the Blue Banjo. So I figured I'd better come try it out,'' he said.
``It couldn't be any tougher than Walla Walla.''
   The bar is a popular spot. Patrons wander in, some for draft beer
at 50 cents a glass, some for the two-for-a-quarter cigarettes. In a
cubbyhole behind the bar two shelves are filled with fortified wines
like Thunderbird, MD 20-20 and jugs of White Port, O'Bennick's
favorite.
   While MacLemore and others talked about O'Bennick and Woodworth,
a young woman walked in and ordered a beer. The bartender asked for
identification and instead of producing a driver's license, she
lifted her shirt and exposed her breasts. She was kicked out.
   ``We get that all the time,'' said the bartender, a burly man
with a gravelly voice who asked that his name not be used. ``I've
got to kick her out or the cops would bust me for promoting
prostitution.''
   Two men staggered in and tried to order beer. They were kicked
out, too.
   ``He was like that,'' the bartender said of O'Bennick as they
lurched out.
   The cash register rang almost constantly after the bartender gave
last call at 11:45 p.m. MacLemore downed one for the road and walked
out through the shifting crowd outside.
   ``Coke? Coca?'' two men asked, making little sniffing motions.
   MacLemore ignored them and walked to the back of the building,
where a lone man rummaged through a trash bin. The homeless
jug-sharers had left. The spot where O'Bennick and Woodworth died
was empty.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890913-0016 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 0107EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Canada-Tax     09-13 0783</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Canada-Tax,0807</SECOND>
<HEAD>Canadians Protest Planned 9 Percent Sales Tax</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government's plan for a 9-percent
sales tax is bringing more than the usual number of protests from
the Canadian grassroots. Some analysts say the tax could cause
tremendous upheaval in the economy.
   ``There has to be a better solution,'' said Gus Karagianis, who
has a placard outside his Fruit King produce stand inviting
passersby to sign a tax-revolt petition.
   He showed off about 3,200 signatures he said he had gathered in
three weeks.
   ``Being a storeowner I'm capable of voicing my opinion,'' he
said. ``Regardless of whether it does any good or not, just voice
your opinion.''
   Petitions, some of them sponsored by newspapers, telephone hot
lines, the inevitable slogan T-shirts and buttons and even a tax
protest song have sprung up since Finance Minister Michael Wilson
announced the details in August of the proposed goods and services
tax that would take effect in 1991.
   The tax would replace an existing, hidden 13.5-percent
manufacturers sales tax that the government says damages the
Canadian economy's ability to compete. The current tax, for example,
applies only to goods manufactured domestically and not to imports.
   Wilson said the new tax would be ``revenue neutral'' for the
government as compared to the current system but would raise the
consumer price index by 2.25 percent in 1991.
   The new tax would be felt by consumers for many goods and
services not now covered, from new houses to restaurant meals and
even postage stamps.
   Basic groceries, virtually all of the items sold in Karagianis'
store, would not be affected, but the 33-year-old shopkeeper said he
believes that any measure that cuts into consumers' spending power
ultimately hurts his business.
   ``You can only tighten the belt so much,'' he said.
   Basic groceries, prescription drugs, health and dental care,
educational services, day care and legal aid would be among the few
categories left untouched by the new tax.
   The Edmonton Sun newspaper in the Western province of Alberta
said it has gathered from readers more than 15,000 tax-protest
coupons addressed to Wilson. ``There are a number of individuals and
organizations who started petitions,'' Managing Editor Randy
McDonald said. ``It's been more of a grassroots thing.''
   Taxes traditionally have been higher in Canada than in the United
States.
   McDonald said tax freedom day, when citizens can stop thinking
that their money is going to the government, already is calculated
for Albertans as July 15 or 16. It was May 4 this year in the United
States.
   ``I think it's just a matter of enough's enough,'' McDonald said.
   The Toronto Sun, the Edmonton's Sun's sister newspaper in
Canada's largest city, said it has taken in 138,000 tax-protest
coupons so far.
   No central place has tabulated the number of Canadians signing
petitions or expressing opposition to the tax plan in other ways.
   But critics of the plan say they hope that evidence of
widespread, visible discontent will persuade the government to alter
or scrap the plan. They note that it won't take effect until 1991,
when the next national election will be on the horizon and unpopular
measures might be harder to take.
   Prime Minister Brian Mulroney's Progressive Conservative Party is
in the first year of its second consecutive majority term. Another
election will not have to be called for at least three years.
   ``We are bringing in the new goods and services tax not because
it is easy but because it is right,'' Mulroney told his party's
recent convention.
   Wood Gundy Inc., a prominent investments firm, said in its highly
publicized analysis of the tax plan that the inflationary impact
would lead to higher interest rates and add to the federal budget
deficit.
   It said the Bank of Canada probably would use tight money policy
to control price pressures and that unemployment would rise as a
result, possibly to 10 percent from its current level of 7.5 percent.
   Burns Fry Ltd. said the government should call the proposed tax
``deficit neutral'' rather than ``revenue neutral,'' as Wilson
characterized it.
   The new tax would take in $4.7 billion ($5.5 billion Canadian)
more than is currently received, but the funds would go out for
refundable tax credits for those with income less than $25,500
($30,000 Canadian), which would lower the middle-income tax rate
from 26 percent to 25 percent and pay for administrative costs.
   The Globe and Mail newspaper in Toronto said in an editorial:
``Both on the visibility and the impact of the tax, the federal
government's projections and hopes appear unrealistic and naive,
asking retailers, consumers and workers to let the system work by
being reasonable.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890913-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 0135EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-CocaineandCoffee     09-13 0525</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cocaine and Coffee,0543</SECOND>
<HEAD>Another Battle Colombia Faces: The Coffee War</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HAROLD OLMOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Colombia's cocaine war has called
attention to another battle _ the coffee war.
   Colombia blames the United States for a nosedive in the price of
coffee, which brought Colombia almost $1.5 billion last year and is
the South American nation's top foreign exchange earner.
   Government officials here complain that what Washington giveth
with one hand _ such as military aid to fight drug traffickers _ the
other hand taketh away, in coffee revenue.
   That is money that could be used for fighting drugs.
   Specifically, Colombia says the United States is to blame for the
collapse of a 74-nation agreement between coffee exporters and
importers that set export quotas and assured Colombians of decent
earnings.
   In July, talks broke down after months of debate among the
members of the International Coffee Accord to renew the agreement.
   The member countries, including suppliers and purchasers,
negotiate prices for one year. The trouble was that some coffee
producers in the pact were selling at cheap prices to non-members,
U.S. officials said.
   The United States said it would not support a new agreement until
it had guarantees that purchasing countries outside the agreement
would not get coffee for less than countries inside the pact.
   A 50 percent drop in coffee prices _ to about 88 cents per pound
_ is the worst slump since the late 1920s. Colombia could lose $200
million in coffee revenue this year.
   In a letter to President Bush, Colombian President Virgilio Barco
said the lack of a new agreement setting export quotas will have
``devastating consequences'' on the Colombian economy.
   ``This is a grave crisis and requires immediate attention,''
Barco told Bush.
   What neither Barco nor any other Colombian official will comment
on is whether slumping cocaine sales also might have devastating
consequences on the economy.
   Since drug trafficking and its earnings are secret by nature, no
one knows to what extent Colombia's economy depends on the cocaine
trade.
   Studies by universities and other independent sources give widely
varying figures. Some say drug money contributes 1.5 percent to 3
percent of the nation's gross national product.
   If the figure is 3 percent, that would be just over $1 billion a
year Colombia would lose if drug traffickers were driven out.
   The nation has launched a vigorous crackdown on the drug trade
since the assassination Aug. 18 of leading presidential candidate
Luis Carlos Galan.
   After three weeks of the crackdown, the Colombian armed forces
have seized more than $200 million in property from drug traffickers.
   Drug barons' investments in real estate in Colombia the last six
years have been as high as $5.5 billion, according to a story this
year in the Bogota daily El Tiempo.
   But unlike coffee earnings, the drug trafficking money that
enters the economy does not generate jobs.
   A U.S. narcotics official in Bogota said recently that the
crackdown on drugs has cut back cocaine shipments substantially, but
he had no idea exactly how much.
   ``Twenty percent, 50 percent? I don't know,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890913-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 0135EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-AuschwitzConvent     09-13 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auschwitz Convent,0311</SECOND>
<HEAD>Polish- and Jewish-American Groups Call for Removal of Convent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of Polish-American and Jewish-American
groups are calling for a return to a 1987 agreement to move a Roman
Catholic convent from the site of the Auschwitz death camp.
   ``The continuing issue over the Carmelite convent has escalated
in some quarters, causing deep anguish to the point that it both
breeds unnecessary hostility and makes a solution more difficult to
achieve,'' the leaders said in a statement Tuesday.
   It was signed by Edward Moskal, president of the Polish American
Congress; Ira Silverman, executive vice president of the American
Jewish Committee; and Harold Gales and the Rev. Leonard Chrobot,
co-chairmen of the National Polish-American Jewish-American Council.
   The convent just outside the Auschwitz concentration camp is seen
by many Jews and others as an intrusion of Christian symbols at a
place where 2.5 million Jews were murdered by the Nazis during World
War II.
   A 1987 accord between Jewish and Roman Catholic representatives
stipulated the convent should be moved by Feb. 22, but the deadline
passed and the convent remained. The Polish primate, Cardinal Jozef
Glemp, has termed the accord ``offensive.''
   The signers of Tuesday's statement called for a return to the
1987 agreement that recognizes both ``the Nazi aim of destroying the
Jewish people in a unique, unthinkable and unspeakable enterprise''
as well as ``the martyrdom of the Polish people during the
totalitarian horror throughout the war of 1939-1945.''
   The statement said the suffering of Poles and ``the murder of
Polish Catholics at Auschwitz has not been adequately recognized or
appreciated.'' An estimated 1.5 million Christians were killed at
Auschwitz.
   At the same time, it said, ``Jewish Americans believe that the
uniqueness of the mass murder of Jews at Auschwitz has not been
understood or appreciated by non-Jews.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
