<FIRST>r i AM-Ethiopia-Peace     09-13 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ethiopia-Peace,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ethiopian Peace Prospects Called Dim</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prospects for a peaceful settlement
of Ethiopia's 28-year-old civil war ``appear to be dim,'' President
Mengistu Haile Mariam said Tuesday.
   Speaking at a rally marking the 15th anniversary of the Ethiopian
revolution, Mengistu said ``no positive indications'' have emerged
from preliminary peace talks in Atlanta.
   Ethiopian officials are meeting in Atlanta with leaders of the
Eritrean People's Liberation Front in an attempt to map a plan for
more substantive talks. The negotiations are being guided by former
President Carter.
   ``The latest indications from Atlanta are that the opposition
group is not interested in a peaceful solution of the conflict,''
Mengistu said.
   The president said the Eritrean Front ``appears to be
intransigent and adamant on its demands.''
   Mengistu did not elaborate, but in the past the Eritrean Front
has demanded the people of Eritrea be allowed to vote on whether
they want independence, federation with Ethiopia or autonomy.
   The government, which has proposed a greater measure of autonomy
for its northernmost province, has unequivocally ruled out any
referendum.
   Mengistu's assessment of the talks was far more pessimistic than
one given to reporters Sunday by Isaias Afwerki, the head of the
rebel delegation in Atlanta.
   Afwerki said the Eritreans ``have reason to believe they are
getting close to a solution,'' but acknowledged that several points
of contention were prolonging the talks.
   Mengistu's 35-minute speech was one of the shortest he has
delivered on Revolution Day, which marks the anniversary of the
overthrow of the late Emperor Haile Selassie.
</TEXT>
