<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     09-13 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0562</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GOSNOLD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wanted: Teacher-principal, versed in all
subjects, good at one-on-one instruction. Must like seclusion.
   The island town off Cape Cod is looking for the right person to
run its one-room, one-pupil elementary school.
   ``You kind of have to be a jack-of-all-trades,'' said Berkeley
School Superintendent Russell F. Latham, whose district includes
Gosnold. ``You're even sort of a part-time custodian.''
   Gosnold is the only town on Cuttyhunk island, a 3-by-2-mile
expanse that lies about 15 miles off the mainland and about 10 miles
west of Martha's Vineyard. Though a popular tourist spot in summer,
Cuttyhunk has only about 50 year-round residents.
   Back in the 1930s, as many as 17 students were enrolled in
Gosnold's century-old schoolhouse. But more and more families have
moved. This year, like last, only one youngster is in school.
   ``He's a neat kid, he's in seventh grade and we need a certified
teacher to teach him,'' Latham said. The previous teacher resigned
over the summer.
   ``She was a youngish woman. I guess she decided she had enough
time being on the island.''
   Depending on experience, the new teacher will earn an annual
salary of $20,000 to $25,000, he said. Three finalists will be
interviewed Friday and school officials hope a teacher will start
work next week.
   Whoever is hired ``should understand a little bit about island
life and have an interest in being on the island nine months a
year,'' Latham said.
   For starters, there's only one telephone: a pay phone at the
general store. And there's the Cuttyhunk winter. A ferry to the
mainland runs only on Tuesdays and Fridays in the winter, and a
seaplane that makes regular flights during the rest of the year
doesn't fly when there is ice, Latham said.
   The town has an inn-restaurant, a bakery and deli-style sandwich
shop, and of course, a general store. Beyond that, there are town
offices, the library, the docks, the school _ and not a whole lot
more.
   People who can't live without malls, movie theaters and cocktail
lounges _ Gosnold is a dry town _ would do best to look elsewhere,
Latham said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An immigrant who fled Afghanistan by
camel after the Soviet invasion in 1979 can ride in true style after
winning $4.3 million in the state lottery.
   Mohammad Zahir, 51, who works in Jacksonville as an automobile
technician, will receive 20 annual installments of $218,000 for
holding one of three winning tickets in the Sept. 2 lottery, which
had a $13 million jackpot.
   Zahir, who didn't discover he had won until returning home from a
trip to visit relatives in New York, said he enjoys his job and
plans to continue working.
   He also told lottery officials Tuesday he will use part of his
winnings to buy a house and travel. Zahir and his wife, Latifa, have
two grown sons _ both electrical engineers in Jacksonville _ and a
daughter who is a student at Jacksonville University.
   It wasn't the first time Zahir won a lottery game. When he lived
in Afghanistan, he once won five cans of vegetable oil, 150 pounds
of rice and some fabric, he said.
   The other lottery winners turned in their tickets earlier.
</TEXT>
