<FIRST>u w AM-LuxembourgAmbassador 1stLd-Writethru   09-13 0199</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Luxembourg Ambassador, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0428,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fred Bush Withdraws</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS ``fired'' to ``hired'' in 2nd graf</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gregg-Senate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fred Bush has withdrawn himself from
consideration as ambassador to Luxembourg, an administration
official said Tuesday night.
   Bush, no relation to the president, thus became the first
political casualty of the housing influence-peddling scandals.
   Fred Bush earned large fees as a consultant to developers who
hired him to help win approval for their projects by the Department
of Housing and Urban Development.
   He was an aide to George Bush as vice president and chief fund
raiser for the president's successful 1988 campaign.
   His nomination as ambassador languished in the Senate, however,
and in a rare move generally interpreted as indicating the chances
of confirmation were between nil and nothing, the Senate sent the
nomination back to the White House just before the August recess.
   ``It became obvious it wasn't going to be worth the pain and he
withdrew his name,'' said the administration official, who spoke on
condition that he not be identified.
   The official said President Bush had not decided whom to nominate
in Fred Bush's place, or what if any other job to offer him.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
