<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 0025EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u p AM-Koch 1stLd-Writethru a0405 09-13 0631</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Koch, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0405,0642</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Recasts top 2 grafs.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY SCHWARTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For more than a decade, Edward I. Koch led New
York with a brash, often combative style. When he faced his last
hurrah on Tuesday, he accepted defeat graciously and called his
years in office ``glorious.''
   With his loss to Manhattan Borough President David Dinkins in the
Democratic primary, the 64-year-old mayor was denied his goal of
becoming the first four-term mayor in the city's history.
   ``I have had 12 glorious years as mayor,'' Koch declared in his
concession speech. Urging his supporters not to feel sorry for him,
he said ``Believe me, there is a life after the mayoralty.''
   Traditionally, New York's mayor is a national political figure.
But Koch _ with his smart-aleck remarks, his eye for the television
cameras, his zest for his office _ became a worldwide celebrity.
   He wrote a bestseller, ``Mayor,'' and two other books. He
appeared on ``Saturday Night Live.'' He was interviewed in Playboy.
   And he was quoted, ad infinitum. Jimmy Carter's brother, Billy,
was ``a wacko.'' Developer Donald Trump was ``piggy, piggy, piggy.''
Jews would ``have to be crazy'' to vote for Jesse Jackson.
   That nasal, feisty voice was unknown to most New Yorkers when
Koch ran for mayor in 1977. His name was recognized by only 6
percent of New Yorkers outside of his congressional district.
   Koch, the Bronx-born son of Polish immigrants, had been active in
liberal Democratic politics; in 1963, he defeated party boss Carmine
DeSapio in a race for district leader. He was elected to the City
Council in 1966 and to Congress from Manhattan's Silk Stocking
district in 1968.
   A 1973 campaign for mayor foundered after 45 days for lack of
money, and 1977 did not look much more encouraging: he faced seven
other candidates, including the incumbent, Abe Beame, and the
flamboyant Bella Abzug.
   In the summer of the Son of Sam murders, Koch pounded away at one
issue _ the death penalty. His ads were created by media wizard
David Garth. And he often was seen arm-in-arm with former Miss
America Bess Myerson.
   Coming from nowhere, Koch was the top vote-getter in the primary.
In a runoff, he defeated New York's secretary of state, Mario Cuomo;
in November, he beat Cuomo (who was the Liberal nominee) and two
others.
   In 1981 and 1985, he would win re-election handily, garnering
three-quarters of the vote each time. His only setback was in 1982,
when he lost to Cuomo in a bid for governor of New York.
   Koch was credited with helping the city emerge from its fiscal
crisis of the 1970s. Under his guidance _ and the stern eye of state
watchdogs _ a spendthrift city tightened its belt.
   But in his third term, Koch was besieged by troubles. The suicide
of Queens Borough President Donald Manes heralded a series of
scandals that never stopped. A patronage operation was found to be
operating in the basement of City Hall. Myerson was tried (and
acquitted) on charges she conspired to fix the divorce case of her
lover, Carl Capasso.
   Koch was accused of racial insensitivity when blacks were killed
in altercations with white gangs in Howard Beach and Bensonhurst _
the latter incident occurring weeks prior to Tuesday's primary.
   Problems that were not at issue when Koch was first elected _
crack, AIDS, homelessness _ plagued the city. The mayor's ratings
plunged to under 30 percent. But he fought back, closing Dinkins'
lead.
   ``I've had 12 wonderful years and expect to have four more,''
Koch said early in the day on Tuesday. ``But I have had a
professional life that everybody could envy. I've enjoyed _ with the
pain, occasionally _ every day.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
