<FIRST>u p AM-DetroitMayor 2ndLd-Writethru a0829 09-13 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Detroit Mayor, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0829,0396</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to UPDATE vote totals.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DT1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEOFFREY HAYNES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Coleman Young easily outpolled 12 primary
challengers Tuesday and will seek an unprecedented fifth term in a
November runoff against accountant Tom Barrow, who defeated Rep.
John Conyers for the No. 2 spot.
   With 306 of 921 precincts reporting, Young had 31,361 votes, or
48 percent, to 17,281, or 26 percent, for Barrow. Conyers had
10,647, or 16 percent. The other 10 candidates shared the remainder.
   Conyers and Young had been considered the challengers most likely
to advance to the head-to-head Nov. 7 runoff with Young.
   Early voter turnout in the non-partisan election was nearly twice
as heavy as four years ago, apparently reflecting the lively
campaigns waged by some of Young's opponents.
   Election officials predicted that slightly more than 30 percent
of the city's 507,000 registered voters would vote in the nation's
sixth-largest city.
   Young, 71, didn't vote Tuesday, having already cast an absentee
ballot under an option available to senior citizens. Conyers and
Barrow each had an entourage of supporters in tow when they cast
ballots early in the day.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Young, Detroit's first black mayor, largely steered clear of his
opponents during the primary campaign. Barrow and Conyers said he'd
been in office too long and favored downtown development ahead of
neighborhood services.
   Young rarely returned fire. Instead, he used some of his
estimated $5 million in campaign funds for television and radio
commercials focusing on his 15 years in office. Actor James Earl
Jones narrated several ads over a background of soft blues music.
   Neither of the city's two major daily newspapers endorsed the
mayor. The Detroit News endorsed Barrow and the Detroit Free Press
supported Conyers. Each charged that Young had led a closed
administration and said the mayor's office needed a change.
   Young seemingly anticipated the attacks. When he announced his
bid for a fifth term in May, the mayor said his principal opponent
was the news media, which he said had been out to get him for years.
   His anger was especially piqued by front-page headlines about a
paternity lawsuit filed against him by a former city employee. Young
at first denied and then admitted that he was the father of the
woman's 6-year-old child.
</TEXT>
