<FIRST>r p PM-MobileMayor     09-13 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mobile Mayor,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mobile Mayor Unseated by Political Newcomer</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Primary Rdp</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOBILE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Political newcomer Mike Dow unseated Mayor
Arthur Outlaw in a bitter mayoral runoff in Alabama's second-largest
city.
   With all votes counted Tuesday night, Dow had 30,444 votes, or 56
percent, to 23,715, or 44 percent, for Outlaw, who is chairman of
the state Republican Party, in the non-partisan race.
   ``What I hope we can accomplish is to keep the people of Mobile
this excited about this city,'' Dow, 42, told several hundred
cheering supporters in his victory speech.
   In conceding, Outlaw, a 63-year-old executive, told supporters,
``I'm not happy about it and I'm not going to lie to you about
that.''
   Dow, who did not declare a party affiliation, had challenged
Outlaw's leadership, particularly his drive for a proposed $40
million waterfront convention center without first seeking voter
approval.
   Although the race was described as non-partisan, some viewed it
as an early test of Republican Gov. Guy Hunt's strength for a 1990
re-election. The Mobile area went heavily for Hunt in 1986 and is
considered GOP territory. Some of Dow's key supporters were aligned
with Attorney General Don Siegelman, who is considered one of Hunt's
potential Democratic opponents.
   In the Aug. 22 general election, 42,272 voters cast ballots for
seven candidates, giving Dow a 1,000-vote edge over Outlaw and
forcing the runoff.
</TEXT>
