<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 0254EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Freighter-Cocaine     09-13 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Freighter-Cocaine,0504</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Agents Make Biggest Bust Since Bush Crackdown</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal agents made the largest cocaine seizure
since President Bush announced his crackdown on drug trafficking,
capturing 2,700 pound of cocaine, a freighter and four other boats.
   The seizure capped a one-year undercover investigation that
tracked a shipment of cocaine from Aruba to the Bahamas.
   Near the Bahamas, a U.S. Coast Guard jet spotted the freighter
and a patrol boat fired dozens of warning shots to capture a
speedboat, the U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration announced
Tuesday.
   ``This is a textbook example of what the taxpayers can expect
from a coordinated drug enforcement effort,'' said Tom Cash, special
agent in charge of Miami's DEA office.
   Officials from the Coast Guard, DEA, the Customs Service and
local police participated in the bust, which netted 17 suspects and
cocaine with an estimated street value of $50 million.
   The cocaine is believed to have originated in Medellin, Colombia.
It was loaded onto the freighter Nerma on Aruba, an isalnd off
northern Venezuela, officials said.
   The drug organization supervising the smuggling was based in
Miami and had been under investigation for a year, officials said.
More arrests were expected.
   The 236-foot freighter, the ``mother ship'' of the operation, was
spotted Saturday night near the Bahamas by a Coast Guard
surveillance airplane, authorities said.
   Early Sunday, Customs and Coast Guard officers saw four
speedboats approach the Nerma as the freighter's crew prepared to
unload bales and barrels of cocaine, authorities said.
   After the speedboats met up with a 42-foot fishing boat, a Coast
Guard patrol boat chased one of the speedboats for 22 minutes and
fired 43 warning shots to stop the boat.
   On Monday morning, authorities seized the Nerma and two other
speedboats and recovered a total of 1,172 pounds of cocaine,
authorities said. Fifteen bales of cocaine were floating in the
water near the Nerma.
   An additional 1,540 pounds was confiscated when the fishing boat,
the J.J. Lorick, was seized late Monday at a marina on the Miami
River, authorities said.
   DEA officials believe the cocaine was already ``in the pipeline''
to this country before the Aug. 18 assasination of Colombian
presidential candidate Luis Carlos Galan, which prompted a drug
crackdown in the South American country. Bush announced his battle
against drugs Sept. 5.
   Cash said the bust ``is indicative of the magnitude of the
pipeline.''
   The Nerma's seven Danish crew members were arrested and ordered
held without bond Monday.
   Six other men were arrested aboard the three captured speedboats,
and four more were arrested near the Lorick, including one man
suspected of being the owner of the freighter, Cash said.
   Six of the defendants appeared before a U.S. magistrate. One was
ordered held on $200,000 bond and two were held on $75,000 bond. The
others were ordered held in pretrial detention.
   All 17 defendants face federal charges of possession of cocaine
with intent to distribute.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
