<FIRST>u a BC-EmmyAwards     09-13 0838</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Emmy Awards,0866</SECOND>
<HEAD>PBS Wins 18 News and Documentary Emmys</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs separate planned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Public Broadcasting Service won 18 Emmy
Awards for news and documentaries Tuesday night. CBS won 16; ABC
eight and NBC five.
   The awards were presented by the Nation Academy of Television
Arts and Sciences.
   The SYN cable network won two awards and the Home Box Office
cable network won one.
   The entries had to air between Jan. 1 and Dec. 31, 1988.
   There were more than 850 entries in 27 categories, which included
awards for interviews, investigative journalism, analysis and
cultural programming.
   For outstanding coverage of a single breaking news story, CBS won
for its program on ``The Tragedy of Pan Am Flight 103'' and NBC won
for its segment on the USS Vincennes, which shot down an Iranian
passenger plane.
   There were seven winners for outstanding background and analysis
of a single current story.
   In the program category, PBS won for ``Race for the
Superconductor,'' on the series ``Nova.'' ABC won for ``Burning
Questions _ the Poisoning of America'' and for ``Nightline in the
Holy Land: Town Meeting.'' CBS won for ``Nightmare Next Door'' on
the series ``48 Hours.''
   In the segments category, ABC won three awards, all for segments
of ``20-20.'' The segments were ``Still on the Wrong Track,'' ``Fall
From Grace,'' and ``A Formula for Tragedy.''
   For outstanding investigative journalism, PBS won for ``Murder on
the Rio San Juan'' on the series ``Frontline.'' CBS won for its
segment on ``Men of God: Borrowing on Faith'' on the series ``West
57th,'' and ABC won for its segment on ``Cutting Corners, Costing
Lives'' on the series ``20-20.''
   For outstanding interviews and interviewers, PBS won for its
program ``Masks of Eternity.'' ABC won for its segment on Austrian
President Kurt Waldheim on ``ABC News Nightline.'' CBS won for three
segments: ``Soviet Dentist'' on the ``CBS Evening News with Dan
Rather,'' ``Edward Teller'' on ``60 Minutes,'' and ``Cara's Story''
on ``60 Minutes.''
   For outstanding coverage of a continuing news story, there were
three program winners. PBS was honored for the ``Election '88
Wrapup'' on ``CE Newsmagazine.'' CBS was honored for two shows on
the series ``48 Hours'' _ ``48 Hours on Gang Street'' and ``Faith
Under Fire.''
   There were four segment winners for outstanding coverage of a
continuing news story. NBC won for ``Palestinian Uprising'' and
``Sudan Famine,'' both on the ``NBC Nightly News with Tom Brokaw.''
CBS was honored for ``Pat Robertson'' and ``Homeless in America:
Suffer the Children,'' both on the series ``West 57th.''
   For outstanding informational, cultural or historical
programming, PBS won for its program ``Can the Vatican Save the
Sistine Chapel?'' on ``Nova'' and HBO won for the program ``JFK: In
His Own Words.''
   CBS was honored for informational, cultural or historical
programming for three ``West 57th'' segments: ``Marriage License
Bureau,'' ``Children in Crisis: Saving Face,'' and ``Broadway Baby.''
   For outstanding news and documentary achievement, PBS was honored
for the programs ``We Shall Overcome'' and ``Living With Aids'' on
the series ``Point of View.''
   David Davis, who produced ``The Unquiet Death of Eli Creekmore''
for PBS, was honored as an individual for outstanding news and
documentary achievement.
   For outstanding individual achievement in writing, Anthony Potter
and Eric Sevareid won for ``Eric Sevareid: Not So Wild a Dream'' on
PBS. Stanley Breeden was honored for ``Australia's Twilight of the
Dreamtime'' on PBS.
   For outstanding individual achievement in directing, Roger
Goodman won for ``Nightline in the Holy Land: Town Meeting'' on ABC.
   For outstanding individual achievement in researching, Marlon T.
Riggs won for ``Ethnic Notions'' on PBS.
   For outstanding individual achievement in cinematography, Norris
Brock won for ``Inside the Soviet Circus'' on PBS.
   For outstanding individual achievement in electronic camerawork,
Jim Douglas won for ``Greetings from the North Shore'' on PBS.
   For outstanding individual achievement in sound, Rick Patterson
won for ``Inside the Soviet Circus'' on PBS. Fred Burnham, Francis
Daniel, Marc Gilmartin, Ken King, Lawrence Loewinger, Glen Marullo,
David Mathew, Allen Patapoff and Mark Roy won for ``The Geometry of
Life'' on PBS.
   For outstanding individual achievement in tape editing, Warren
Lustig won for ``1988: Year in Review'' on CBS and Jess Bushyhead
was honored for ``1988: The Year in Review'' on NBC.
   For outstanding individual achievement in film editing, Holly K.
Fine won for ``The Wall Within'' on CBS. Margot Francis and Joan
Morris won for ``Sarafina! Words of Freedom'' on NBC.
   For outstanding individual achievement in lighting direction,
Martin S. Dick was honored for ``West 57th'' on CBS.
   For outstanding individual achievement in graphic design, John
Andrews and Todd Ruff were honored for ``Adam Smith's Money World''
on PBS.
   For outstanding individual achievement in title sequences,
Richard Greenberg won for ``USA Today: The Television Show'' on SYN.
   For outstanding individual achievement in art direction, Jeremy
Conway won for ``USA Today: The Television Show'' on SYN.
   For outstanding individual achievement in music, Charles Kuskin
won for ``The American Experience'' and Lee Holdridge was honored
for ``The Explorers: A Century of Discovery,'' both on PBS.
</TEXT>
