<FIRST>r a PM-Inmates'Infection     09-13 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Inmates' Infection,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Promises Quick Decision on Jail Disease</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Hearing scheduled to resume at 10:30 a.m. EDT.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH RENDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge promised a quick decision on
whether to release up to 500 misdemeanor offenders from an
overcrowded jail where a mysterious bacterial infection has killed
two prisoners.
   Mark Canfield, chief of epidemiology for the Harris County Health
Department, said Tuesday that the source of an outbreak of flulike
symptoms at the county jail was unknown.
   ``We can expect to be working on it throughout the week. We have
a lot of variables involved,'' he said.
   On Monday, Attorney James Oitzinger asked U.S. District Judge
James DeAnda to force jail officials to relieve overcrowding and to
isolate those at greatest risk of contracting the infection.
   Oitzinger is representing the prisoners in a continuing lawsuit
before DeAnda over jail crowding.
   DeAnda, citing the seriousness of the situation, heard evidence
Tuesday and said he would respond to the request as early as today.
   Late last week, the infection killed inmates Ricky LaBreck, 30,
and Rene Antonio Fuentes, 21. Both had had their spleens removed,
leaving them more susceptible to the infection, doctors said.
   Eighteen inmates, including the two who died, have been treated
at a hospital, and cultures have indicated the presence of the
pneumococcus bacteria in five, Canfield said. One hospitalized
inmate also is without a spleen, he said.
   The others have various flulike symptoms that may be early signs
of the infection or perhaps just effects of a virus, said Nora
Shire, a spokeswoman for Ben Taub Hospital.
   Between 20 and 30 prisoners were being evaluated at the jail
infirmary with similar flulike symptoms, Canfield said.
   Sheriff Johnny Klevenhagen testified Tuesday that experts from
the U.S. Centers for Disease Control in Atlanta and those from the
county, city and jail do not blame crowding for the deaths.
   Klevenhagen opposes the early releases of the misdemeanor
offenders from the jail, which was designed to house 4,200 inmates,
but has about 8,300.
   Jail officials voluntarily canceled religious services,
recreational activities and classes, and the medical staff screened
inmates for conditions that could put them at greater risk than
healthy people from bacteria.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
