<DOCNO> AP890913-0034 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 0307EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r e BC-Theater     09-13 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Theater,0433</SECOND>
<HEAD>Red Army Singers, Dancers Touring U.S.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Will stand for PMs.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Alexandrov Red Army Song and Dance Ensemble
put together a program clearly intended to win Americans audiences.
It starts with the ``The Star Spangled Banner'' and ends with ``God
Bless America.'' And in between are not only Russian folk songs but
other internationalisms including a soloist who sounds like an Irish
tenor.
   The company opened Tuesday night for eight performances at the
City Center. Next it goes to 29 other American cities.
   The troupe has swashbuckling dancers _ men and women _ in
colorful folk costumes. Crowded behind the dancing space the
orchestra has Russian instruments, including balalaika and dombra,
and Western symphony instruments.
   Most impressive of all, to this member of the audience, was the
male chorus of more than 80 voices. Members of the chorus stood on
four rows of risers at the back of the stage. Their prominent sound
was baritone. When they hummed in harmony, it was glorious.
   Soloists were tenors and baritones. The Russian deep bass voice,
as rich as fertile black soil, that Americans know from opera, was
not to be heard.
   But Barseg Tumanyan, a rich baritone, saved the bass lovers from
disappointment. He sang ``The Toreador Song'' in French and ``I Got
Plenty of Nothin''' in English. He obviously had learned that one
from a recording. Every time he sang ``No use complaining'' the
words had an Italian accent. He got so much applause that he sang
``I Got Plenty of Nothin''' a second time.
   A trumpet soloist revealed that he'd been listening to recordings
by Louis Armstrong.
   These dancers did the kind of things other Russian troupes do but
their impact was heightened by musical numbers between their dances.
They did choreographed swordfights, danced smoothly and fast in
lines, danced in a crouch, did one-hand cartwheels, and did some
storytelling dances with villagers and comic characters.
   Lighting was interesting, giving rows of men in uniform some
variety, as only shoulders were lighted, and shadows made hats
suddenly look like ancient Roman helmets.
   Alexander Alexandrov founded the ensemble in 1928. The group
started for the United States in 1939 but World War II broke out and
the troupe turned back.
   This is its first American tour.
   Capturing the tone of the program, on the back wall of the stage
at City Center, were huge flags of the United States and Soviet
Union side by side.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890913-0035 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 0150EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u p AM-CoelhoSeat 2ndLd-Writethru a0439 09-13 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Coelho Seat, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0439,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with Condit winning; picks up 5th
graf, `Condit, 41...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COLLEEN BARRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MODESTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic Assemblyman Gary Condit
trounced seven other candidates Tuesday to win the seat given up by
former House Democratic Whip Tony Coelho, who resigned under an
ethics cloud.
   With 323 of 397 precincts counted, Condit had 46,420 votes, or 56
percent, to 27,131, or 34 percent, for Republican former state
Agriculture Director Clare Berryhill. Five other Republicans and a
Libertarian divided the remaining vote in the special election for
the San Joaquin Valley's 15th District.
   Condit's majority enabled him to avoid a Nov. 7 runoff with
Berryhill. Under state law, all candidates appear on the same
primary ballot, allowing voters to cross party lines.
   Condit will serve the remainder of Coelho's term, which expires
in 1990.
   Condit, 41, is from Modesto, while Berryhill, 63, is from Ceres.
The other candidates were Republican contractor Cliff Burris of
Merced, GOP farmer Robert Weimer of Atwater, Republican engineer
Dave Williams of Livermore, Libertarian Roy Shimp, a Merced teacher;
Republican businessman Jack McCoy of Modesto; and Republican Chris
Patterakis, a retired Air Force major.
   Patterakis and McCoy dropped out of the race last month, but it
was too late to remove their names from the ballot.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Coelho, once a rising star in the Democratic Party, resigned June
15 after failing to report a $50,000 loan from a savings and loan.
   He said there was nothing wrong with the loan, and said it wasn't
reported because of a clerical error.
   But the incident drew greater attention because it coincided with
the downfall of House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas. Coelho said he
resigned because he didn't want to give the Republicans two
prominent targets.
   Despite the circumstances surrounding Coelho's resignation,
Condit stressed his ties to the former House whip in television
commercials and mailings.
   Abortion, highway congestion and agriculture problems were major
issues in the race.
   Berryhill said he opposed abortion except in cases involving
rape, incest and a threat to the life of a mother. Condit said he
also opposed abortion but felt the decision to have one should be
personal.
</TEXT>
