<FIRST>r w PM-US-Soviet-IMF     09-13 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Soviet-IMF,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>For Release at 10 a.m. EDT; time set by source</HEAD>
<HEAD>Soviets Urged to Adopt Western Ways Through Monetary Fund</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union should be brought to Western
ways through membership in the International Monetary Fund, two
experts on international affairs proposed in a study published today.
   ``The fund would still run the risk that (Soviet President
Mikhail) Gorbachev could be replaced by hard liners, but since the
Soviet Union would at most be granted 5 to 6 percent of the votes on
the IMF Executive Board, any disruptive tactics could be
contained,'' wrote Catherine Gwin and Richard E. Feinberg.
   Nearly all of the IMF's member governments are devoted to private
enterprise, although China, Hungary, Poland and Yugoslavia belong.
The Soviet Union does not. The United States has the largest block
of votes with 19.14 percent.
   Gwin is special program adviser at the Rockefeller Foundation.
Feinberg, a former member of the State Department Policy Planning
Staff, is executive vice president of the Overseas Development
Council, a private group financed largely by foundations.
   Their volume is called ``The International Monetary Fund in a
Multipolar World: Pulling Together.''
   The IMF provides loans and other assistance to developing nations.
   Gorbachev has expressed interest in joining the fund, but the
U.S. government has opposed the idea.
   The authors suggested the Soviets could get advice from the fund
as China has done from the IMF's sister organization, the World
Bank. Membership in the fund is a condition for joining the bank and
the two organizations have the same 151 member countries.
   The authors said the Soviets need guidance on money, banking,
price reform and exchange and trade relations.
   As ``confidence-building'' measures, they recommended:
   _Consultations among officials of the fund and the Soviet Union.
   _Provision by the Soviets of data on their aid to the Third World.
   _Soviet co-financing of some World Bank aid projects.
   _Cooperation with the World Bank in some areas such as protection
of the environment.
   Integrating the Soviets into the world economy could give the
fund a central purpose for the 1990s, the writers suggested.
   The IMF has been a failure in the past decade, according to
another writer in the volume, Jeffrey D. Sachs, professor of
international trade at Harvard University.
   Sachs said few of the 39 developing nations the fund has tried to
help this decade have become able to meet their international
obligations without undermining their internal economies.
   ``Most of the problem debtor countries are further away than ever
from renewed creditworthiness.''
   A fund official said there would be no immediate comment from
fund Managing Director Michel Camdessus.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
