<FIRST>r w PM-Drugs-Funding     09-13 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drugs-Funding,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Drug Plan Funding Under Fire from State and Local Officials</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bush administration blueprints for fighting the
drug war are coming under fire from state and local officials who
say the battle would strain their budgets without providing the
money to get the job done.
   ``Almost everyone acknowledges that this is not enough money,''
Mayor Joseph P. Riley of Charleston, S.C., told a Senate Judiciary
Committee hearing Tuesday on how the drug plan will affect state and
local budgets.
   Riley praised President Bush and national drug policy director
William Bennett for addressing the problem. But he said the $350
million the strategy envisions sending to state and local
governments to bolster law enforcement would be less than 1 percent
of what they already spend.
   He said there could be a net loss when aid to state and local
governments under the plan is balanced against cuts in federal
grants for juvenile justice programs, community development and
housing.
   Officials appearing as witnesses were virtually unanimous in
saying federal aid under the proposal was insufficient. Several
complained cuts in existing grant programs could actually harm
efforts to solve the drug problem.
   ``It is inconceivable that we would go out to fight a war with $8
billion to solve a problem that we conservatively estimate at $120
billion,'' said John Gustafson, president of the National
Association of State Alcohol and Drug Abuse Directors. ``You can't
do it with an 8 percent solution.''
   Judiciary Chairman Joseph Biden, D-Del., said he didn't want to
go back to his constituents after passing the measure only to be
told ``you made life worse for us because you increased my taxes or
you didn't increase my taxes but I don't have any bus service
anymore.''
   State Rep. Dan Blue of North Carolina, chairman of the law and
justice committee of the National Conference of State Legislatures,
said states were ``pleased that the national government is joining
our efforts to eradicate drug abuse.''
   ``Unfortunately, development of the national strategy did not
include a sufficient analysis of the potential costs to state and
local governments,'' he said.
   One administration proposal criticized by the officials would
require drug testing of all people arrested, prisoners, parolees and
those released on bond while awaiting trial.
   Biden said that would cost $244 million of the $350 million in
law enforcement aid.
</TEXT>
