<FIRST>r w PM-AthleticScholarships     09-13 0594</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Athletic Scholarships,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bradley Bill Would Force Schools to Disclose Graduation Rates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There are places like Villanova where all or
practically all of the scholarship basketball players leave with
degrees in their pockets after four or five years.
   But Villanova is an exception.
   At many other schools, less proud to step forward and be counted
publicly, hardly any of the players in high-dollar major sports
programs such as football and basketball get their degrees.
   National Collegiate Athletic Association figures for 1988 show 30
schools had graduation rates of 5 percent or less for basketball
players, and seven with rates of 96 percent or greater.
   Most of the association's 800 member schools fall somewhere in
between.
   That wide disparity would not disappear under Sen. Bill Bradley's
plan to force all colleges to make public the graduation statistics
they already compile and report privately to the NCAA, which
compiles them in an annual composite report.
   ``It doesn't guarantee that (student-athletes) are going to make
it,'' said Bradley, D-N.J., who was a Rhodes Scholar and
professional basketball star before taking up politics. ``Education
requires hard work.''
   But Bradley insisted his ``consumer disclosure'' legislation
would help youngsters interested in getting an education find the
right place to play ball.
   Dr. Patricia Lucas, principal of Southeast High School in
Bradenton, Fla., and a spokeswoman for the National Association of
Secondary School Principals, strongly agreed during a hearing before
the Senate Labor and Human Resources Committee.
   She said legislation would help those ``whose maturity has not
progressed beyond the stage of dreaming of the glory of college and
professional sports.''
   The Bradley bill would require the individual figures be reported
to the U.S. Department of Education, broken down by sport. Each
institution would have to disclose its rates to prospective athletic
recruits and the figures would be printed on any scholarship papers
signed by the student.
   The head of the NCAA and a college president pleaded for more
time before the federal government steps in with a law, at least
until the NCAA meeting in January.
   ``If we don't pass meaningful legislation, I will personally
lobby for this bill,'' NCAA Executive Director Dick Schultz said.
   He argued the 48 percent graduate rate for college athletes at
NCAA member institutions is actually slightly better than the rate
for general student bodies. And he said academic rules for athletes
put into place over the past five years have not had time to show up
in statistics.
   But Bradley said the NCAA was offering ``too little, too late''
and told reporters he intended to press for passage of his bill
before the January NCAA meeting. Bradley introduced similar
legislation last year, but didn't push it.
   Those testifying in favor of the bill included Villanova
basketball coach Rollie Massimino, whose team is a perennial power
and has won one national championship.
   Massimino told the committee that _ which the exception of some
who transferred to other schools or otherwise left Villanova in good
academic standing _ all 52 of his player got their degrees.
   It wasn't always easy, he said, especially in the early part of
his 17-year tenure _ before his reputation was established and
everyone realized he was serious about emphasizing academics. He
said he suffered under the pressure to win before he told himself,
``We're either going to do it or we're not and we're going to do it
my way.''
   Massimino said the result shows a collegiate athletic program can
be run without losing sight of a college's educational mission.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
