<FIRST>r w PM-FrankInvestigation     09-13 0609</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Frank Investigation,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressman Sees Ethics Panel Clearing Him in Sex Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Barney Frank says he's eager to refute
``inaccurate charges'' about his relationship with a male prostitute
and will fully cooperate with an ethics committee investigation into
his conduct.
   The Committee on Standards of Official Conduct _ the ethics
committee _ voted Tuesday to begin a preliminary investigation into
the Massachusetts Democrat's activities with prostitute Steve Gobie.
   Frank, an acknowledged homosexual, has said he originally hired
Gobie for sex and then employed him _ using personal funds _ as a
personal aid from July 1985 through August 1987.
   Frank called the ethics panel ``the best possible forum'' to
resolve conflicting accounts he and Gobie have given on some details
of their relationship.
   Gobie, for instance, said he operated a prostitution ring from
Frank's Capitol Hill apartment with the lawmaker's knowledge, but
Frank insists he was unaware of any such activity.
   According to Gobie, Frank used his congressional immunity to void
parking tickets incurred by Gobie, when the prostitute used the
lawmaker's car to keep appointments for illicit sex. Frank said he
only had tickets waived when the car was used for official business.
   Frank said he requested the ethics investigation several weeks
ago ``when I saw what I believe to be very inaccurate charges
floating around.''
   ``And I welcome the chance to go before the ethics committee with
canceled checks for parking tickets, with the statement of my
landlady, who lived in that house on a day-to-day basis ... with
people on my staff who have evidence to give.''
   Commenting after delivering a speech to a bankers' group, Frank
said the impact on his political future would depend on ``what the
ethics committee decides. Frankly, if some of the accusations that
were made were true, then I think I would be in very serious trouble
and ought to be.''
   Ethics committee Chairman Julian Dixon, D-Calif., said the
investigation was prompted by ``the assertions surrounding Barney
Frank's employment of Mr. Steve Gobie.''
   The committee voted in secret, and Dixon would not reveal whether
the vote was unanimous.
   The vote began only the first round of the House's internal
disciplinary process, and will determine whether a more complete
investigation is necessary. The panel can issue subpoenas and take
testimony during the preliminary stage.
   The inquiry could lead to a statement of an alleged violation,
which is similar to an indictment. This could result in a
disciplinary proceeding and a recommendation to the full House for
punishment, which could range from a reprimand to expulsion.
   Dixon also announced the committee accepted the request of panel
member Chester Atkins, D-Mass., to withdraw from consideration of
the Frank case.
   ``Mr. Atkins felt in this particular case he could not be a fair
and impartial person,'' Dixon said. House Speaker Thomas S. Foley
appointed former ethics committee Chairman Louis Stokes, D-Ohio, to
replace Atkins on the Frank case, although Atkins will remain active
in other committee investigations.
   In a statement, Atkins said, ``Barney Frank is my friend. I
cannot end our friendship today, and I cannot be sure that my
judgment of this friend would be `impartial and unbiased' as the
House rules require. The public has a right to expect of us no
outright predispositions.''
   Atkins also said his dual role as a panel member and
Massachusetts' Democratic chairman ``would, at the outset, serve to
undermine the committee's standing. If I remain on the ... committee
_ for this case _ I compromise the process. If I recuse myself, I do
much more to uphold the credibility of the process.''
</TEXT>
