<FIRST>r w PM-AbortionPolitics     09-13 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion Politics,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strategists Unsure of Abortion Impact on State Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many Democrats say the Supreme Court's ruling
on abortion gives them an opening in the 1989 state elections, but
strategists are cautioning the issue remains a political wildcard
until ballot results are counted.
   Celinda Lake, a pollster for Democratic candidates, said Tuesday
that polling in many states suggests significant numbers of voters
may shift to candidates supporting abortion rights.
   She acknowledged, however, the impact of the court's decision
this summer permitting state's greater regulatory power over
abortion has not been put to the test of a full political campaign.
   ``I think we really don't know what happens when we come into an
election and this issue is getting hammered on,'' she said at a
discussion of abortion politics sponsored by a liberal Democratic
research organization.
   Lake and other political analysts said abortion may prove a
decisive issue in the governor's elections this fall in Virginia and
New Jersey. Democratic candidates in both states have staked out
positions generally in favor of abortion rights.
   A consultant the Virginia Democratic candidate Lt. Gov. L.
Douglas Wilder suggested Wilder plans to launch television
advertising focusing on the abortion issue. He faces Republican
nominee J. Marshall Coleman, who has softened his opposition to
abortion but remains perceived as the anti-abortion candidate, the
analysts said.
   ``Until this year, we always said this is an issue you don't want
to ... pay to put on TV,'' said Frank Greer, a Washington-based
media consultant to the Wilder campaign. ``This year, people are
going to be paying ... and I think that will make it a cutting
issue.''
   But Charles Cook, editor of The Cook Political Report newsletter
and a political analyst, said much of the national polling showing
voters generally in favor of abortion is meaningless because voters
may decide their votes on other issues.
   He said Democratic candidates who push pro-abortion positions
risk alienating older Democratic voters, less educated voters and,
in many states, black voters. For Republicans who oppose abortion,
he said, to push the abortion issue forcefully is to risk losing
younger voters and women.
   ``From a political standpoint I think this is very, very
dangerous for the Democratic Party and it's one that really ought to
be thought through before there is any movement to make the
Democratic Party the pro-choice party and for the Republican Party,
for that matter, to become the pro-life party,'' Cook said.
   The analysts commented at a luncheon sponsored by the Center for
National Policy and held at the National Democratic Club.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
