<FIRST>r w PM-Gregg-Senate     09-13 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gregg-Senate,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Divided Senate Confirms Former Bush Aide as Ambassador</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate is sending former CIA agent Donald
Gregg to Seoul as U.S. ambassador to South Korea, dismissing months
of attacks on his credibility and alleged involvement in the
Iran-Contra affair.
   The Senate voted 66-33 on Tuesday to confirm President Bush's
nomination of Gregg after opponents said his sworn denials were
``absurd on their face'' and defenders said rejecting him would be
unfair.
   Twenty-one Democrats joined all 45 Senate Republicans in voting
for the nomination. Thirty-three Democrats voted no.
   Sen. Charles Robb, D-Va., played a key role in debate, mounting a
detailed defense of Gregg's conduct during the years he served as
national security adviser to Vice President Bush.
   Robb, who said he supported the nominee out of ``conscience and
conviction,'' said he would vote for Gregg ``in the hope that we can
put the unfortunate experience of executive-legislative distrust
behind us and begin anew in the spirit of a sustainable, bipartisan
foreign policy.''
   Robb said he is convinced Gregg did not lie to Congress. The
record shows not ``a crafty, all-knowing political operative,'' said
Robb, but rather ``a dedicated public servant, concerned with the
issues and setting the record straight.''
   ``When we take time to consider each concern, we find an
explanation ... His biggest sin seems to be that he served in
government when our system broke down,'' he said.
   Bush's nomination of Gregg, a former CIA station chief in Seoul,
has been pending since March.
   In two sessions before the Senate Foreign Relations Committee,
Gregg denied, under oath, allegations he was involved in the Reagan
administration's secret and illegal effort to resupply the Contra
rebels in Nicaragua.
   But many of Robb's Democratic colleagues said Gregg's denials
were just not credible.
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell of Maine, who was a member
of the Senate Iran-Contra investigating committee, said he believes
Gregg's explanations ``are so inconsistent with the known facts that
they cannot be believed.''
   ``Mr. Gregg has clearly not been straight with us,'' said Sen.
Alan Cranston, D-Calif. ``Few who have reviewed the record have come
away with any confidence in Mr. Gregg's veracity.''
   Sen. Albert Gore, D-Tenn., scoffed at Gregg's explanation of why
Bush's agenda for two separate meetings as vice president included
the subject of ``Contra Resupply.''
   Gregg testified the citations were the result of a
misunderstanding of how the agenda topics should be listed. He said
the actual topic was ``Copter Resupply,'' referring to the resupply
of helicopters for the armed forces in El Salvador.
   ``Are we to seriously accept a bald-faced presentation of that
kind?'' Gore asked. ``It's absurd on its face.''
   ``To vote to confirm we have to believe this nominee did not lie
brazenly and repeatedly,'' Gore said. ``It's a little difficult to
swallow.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
