<FIRST>r w PM-US-Mideast     09-13 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Mideast,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jordan Demands Israel Commit Itself To Yielding West Bank and Gaza</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Crown Prince of Jordan is demanding a
commitment from Israel that it would relinquish the West Bank and
Gaza in exchange for peace.
   In a speech Tuesday night, Prince Hassan accused Israel of trying
to drive a wedge between Palestinian Arabs and the Palestine
Liberation Organization, but he disavowed any Jordanian intention to
represent the Palestinians.
   At a news conference earlier, Hassan dismissed as a ``pipedream''
of some Israeli politicians the idea that Jordan would agree to a
deal to resume control of the West Bank.
   Speaking after meetings with President Bush and Secretary of
State James A. Baker III, the prince said Israel and the United
States should accept the PLO as the legitimate representative of the
Palestinians in negotiations.
   He denounced Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's plan for
elections among Palestinians on the West Bank and in Gaza, saying
``the purpose is to drive a wedge between them and their recognized
leadership.''
   Jordan controlled the West Bank from 1948 until 1967 while Egypt
ran Gaza. The two Arab countries lost the territories to Israel in
the 1967 Six-Day War.
   Shamir's plan, which has U.S. support, is designed to have
elected Palestinians negotiate with Israel five years of local
self-rule for the 1.4 million Palestinian inhabitants. Afterward,
joined by Egypt and Jordan, they would negotiate an overall
settlement.
   But Hassan said an agreement could only be arranged at an
international that includes the PLO and the Soviet Union. ``Jordan
will not represent the Palestinian people at the conference. Nor
will it negotiate the settlement of the Palestinian problem on
behalf of the PLO,'' he said.
   He said Jordan was willing to attend as part of a mixed
delegation with Yasser Arafat's group. In the speech and at the news
conference, he referred to the PLO leader as ``President Arafat.''
   Earlier Tuesday, the State Department gave cautious praise to a
plan by Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak for Palestinian elections.
But there was no indication whether Israel or the PLO would go along.
   The plan by President Hosni Mubarak includes a demand that Israel
accept the idea it should trade land for peace. Negotiations for an
overall settlement of the Arab-Israeli dispute would be held three
to five years after limited Palestinian self-rule began.
   Israeli Prime Minister Shamir has steered clear of any scheme
that would commit Israel to relinquishing West Bank and Gaza
territory. The PLO, meanwhile, demands nothing less than statehood.
   Baker is sounding out Mideast leaders about Mubarak's ideas. He
met last week with Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin and on
Tuesday with Hassan. Mubarak is expected here within a few weeks and
Shamir in November.
   ``We continue to encourage all parties to find ways to launch an
Israeli-Palestinian dialogue to discuss the Israeli election
initiative,'' said Margaret Tutwiler, the State Department
spokeswoman. ``To the extent these 10 points can be helpful, in that
regard we welcome Egypt's efforts.''
   Other elements of Mubarak's proposal include permitting
Palestinians who live in East Jerusalem to participate in the
balloting and supervision of the voting by international observers.
   At a news conference later, Hassan called Mubarak's proposal
worthwhile, but said a settlement of the Arab-Israeli dispute
required an international peace conference.
   ``We see the Egyptian proposals as a mechanism for holding
elections,'' he said.
   Hassan met with Bush at the White House for about 15 minutes and
told reporters they discussed generalities.
   ``I had the very moving impression of the president's personal
concern toward these developments,'' he said.
</TEXT>
