<FIRST>r w PM-US-Panama     09-13 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Panama,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Reinforces Sanctions Against Panama</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration is reinforcing economic
sanctions against Panama but U.S. officials concede the new action
will likely fall short of toppling military strongman Manuel Antonio
Noriega.
   State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said Tuesday
Panama will be ineligible to participate in an expansion of the U.S.
quotas for sugar imports.
   In addition, she said the administration is expanding the list of
Panamanian companies and individuals which Americans will not have
permission to deal with.
   U.S. officials, insisting on anonymity, said they doubted the new
measures were strong enough to dislodge Noriega from power.
   But they said a stronger package of economic sanctions could do
more damage to the Panamanian people than to Noriega, who is under
indictment on drug smuggling charges by two Florida grand juries.
   Ms. Tutwiler said that without the sanction on sugar exports,
Panama would have the authority to export more than 23,000 tons to
the United States under the revised quota.
   The announcement did not come as a surprise since the Reagan
administration had suspended Panama's sugar quota as far back as
December 1987.
   The new action reflected administration displeasure over
Noriega's decision to install a long-time associate as Panama's
unelected president two weeks ago.
   The State Department has accused Noriega of sabotaging elections
last May rather than recognize the victory of the opposition
candidate.
</TEXT>
