<FIRST>r w PM-LuxembourgAmbassador     09-13 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Luxembourg Ambassador,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fred Bush, Linked to HUD Probe, Withdraws</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fred Bush, a former aide and fund-raiser for
the president, will not fight for his nomination as ambassador to
Luxembourg, according to an administration official.
   Bush, who is no relation to the president, faced stiff opposition
in the Senate to his nomination because of his involvement in
allegations of influence peddling at the Department of Housing and
Urban Development.
   ``It became obvious it wasn't going to be worth the pain and he
withdrew his name,'' said the administration official, who spoke
Tuesday on condition he not be named.
   The official said President Bush had not decided who to nominate
in Fred Bush's place, or whether he would offer him another job.
   Fred Bush earned large fees as a consultant to developers who
hired him to help win approval for projects dependent on HUD grants.
   After one appearance before a House subcommittee investigating
the scandal-plagued agency, Bush was asked to testify a second time
to explain discrepancies that appeared later between his testimony
and other evidence. Subcommittee members also were openly skeptical
of some of Bush's memory lapses when he testified.
   He was an aide to George Bush as vice president and chief
fund-raiser for the president's successful 1988 campaign.
   His nomination as ambassador languished for months in the Senate
before senators sent the nomination back to the White House just
before the August recess.
</TEXT>
