<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 0337EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-AIDSDrugs     09-13 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS Drugs,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scientists Search For Faster Ways Of Testing AIDS Drugs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Health experts say research on how fast the
AIDS virus progresses in humans could speed testing of drugs to
combat the disease.
   Such a measure ``will make drug development a lot faster and more
efficient,'' said Dr. Samuel Broder, director of the National Cancer
Institute and a leading AIDS researcher.
   ``You might be able to make determinations much quicker without
having to let studies go to where there is a deterioration of
clinical status,'' he said.
   About 300 researchers from federal, university and commercial
laboratories met at the National Academy of Science headquarters
Tuesday to discuss what characteristics in the blood of AIDS
patients could be used to gauge how fast the disease infects the
immune system.
   If an agreement is reached and approved by the Food and Drug
Adminstration, it could lead to the use of a laboratory blood test
that would swiftly determine progress of the AIDS virus infection in
a patient, experts said. This would help measure the effects of
drugs to fight the disease.
   Stages of infection by the human immunodeficency virus that
causes AIDS, are now measured by clinical effects, such as
opportunistic infections, or wasting, or chronic lymph node
enlargement. These are called ``clinical endpoints'' and they often
can take months or years to develop.
   A number of investigators believe the progress of AIDS can be
accurately measured by testing the blood for the number of CD4
lymphocyte cells. These cells are part of the immune system and are
the primary target of the AIDS virus.
   Normally, humans have 800 or more CD4 cells per cubic millimeter.
But once the AIDS infection becomes active, this number begins to
drop. CD4 cell counts of less than 200 are thought to reflect an
immune system that is in serious trouble.
   A number of researchers have suggested that tracking the rate of
decline of CD4 cells would be a method of measuring the progress of
the AIDS virus.
   If a candidate drug caused this decline to slow, stop or reverse,
the researchers believe, it would suggest the drug was slowing
progress of the AIDS virus.
   Determining the CD4 cell is a realtively simple laboratory test
that can be quickly performed. Researchers said it would enable them
to plot from week-to-week the precise progress a patient makes while
receiving experimental therapy for AIDS.
   But, some investigators at the meeting said not all patients
respond in the same way to infection by the AIDS virus. Some
patients with CD4 counts well above 500 have developed opportunistic
infections, while others with much lower CD4 counts remain
symptom-free.
   ``A lot of people are in agreement that CD4 is an important
prognostic factor, that is it can predict how you are going to do
over an interval of time,'' said Broder. ``But there is still not an
agreement as to whether you can use CD4 alone. There's no consensus
on that.''
</TEXT>
