<FIRST>r a PM-Elderly-Crack     09-13 0220</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Elderly-Crack,0229</SECOND>
<HEAD>75-Year-Old Man Arrested on Charges of Selling Crack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA ROSA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 75-year-old man who allegedly told
undercover investigators he sold crack to pay his dying wife's
medical bills pleaded innocent to drug charges.
   Martin Franklin of Santa Rosa was arrested Friday following an
eight-month investigation. He has been held in Sonoma County Jail on
$30,000 bail since the arrest and entered his plea Tuesday.
   ``He's the oldest client I've had charged with selling drugs,''
said L. Stephen Turer, Franklin's lawyer.
   Turer said he hoped to convince Municipal Court Judge Knoel Owen
that his client be freed on supervised probation pending trial
because of on-going problems with his legs.
   ``He's no young man,'' Turer said.
   Police said Franklin sold crack to undercover investigators last
May and June.
   Franklin told investigators he sold the crack to pay for medical
bills accummulated by his 65-year-old wife, who died in July of Lou
Gehrig's disease, said Police Sgt. Ken Knobelauch.
   Police believe Franklin sold crack for a about one year, said
Knobelauch.
   Officers found an unspecified amount of crack in Franklin's truck
and about $1,000 in cash at his home in Santa Rosa when he was
arrested Friday, Knobelauch said.
   Two other men who police believe may have supplied Franklin with
drugs were arrested last week, Knobelauch said.
  
</TEXT>
