<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 0411EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-RanchoSeco     09-13 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rancho Seco,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Utility Rejects Plan to Restart Nuclear Reactor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The owner of the Rancho Seco nuclear
power complex rejected a company's proposal to buy and restart the
plant, apparently ending the possibility that the reactor would be
revived.
   The surprise 5-0 vote by directors of the Sacramento Municipal
Utility District was led by Cliff Wilcox, a longtime supporter of
nuclear power and Rancho Seco.
   Wilcox gave a reluctant and emotional rejection of the proposal
from Quadrex Corp., a Campbell-based energy engineering company.
   ``In my estimation it's not a deal that can fly,'' Wilcox said.
He expressed doubts that Quadrex had the expertise or the money to
get the plant going again.
   The municipal utility shut the plant June 7, a day after voters
became the first in the country to order an operating nuclear power
plant to be closed. The reactor had been plagued with problems for
more than a decade and the utility had spent hundreds of millions of
dollars on repairs in recent years.
   Quadrex was the only company to propose reviving Rancho Seco's
nuclear reactor. Other companies have proposed converting the plant
to natural gas.
   Although other proposals to restart the reactor could surface,
any such plan would have to be approved by voters in the utility
district as well as utility directors.
   Just after the directors' vote Monday night, Quadrex chairman
William Derrickson said the utility ``made a giant error, but it's a
free country. They're trading no risk for a lot of risk.''
   But the director of a national anti-nuclear group said he was
delighted with the decision.
   ``This was a triumph of common sense over ideological zealotry
and bravado,'' said Scott Denman of the Safe Energy Communiciations
Council, which is based in Washington, D.C.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
