<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 0413EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Refugees-HungarianVisas     09-13 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Refugees-Hungarian Visas,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>East Germans Have Long Had Little Trouble Getting Approval for Hungary
Trips</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Refugees, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East Germans have long viewed Hungary as an
attractive vacation spot. In recent months, it has also became a
Mecca for thousands hoping for a permanent change of address in the
West.
   Reform-minded Hungary draws tens of thousands of vacationers each
year from from East bloc ally East Germany.
   Traditionally, it has been relatively easy for East Germans to
obtain permission to travel to Hungary, but far more difficult to
get approval for visiting the West.
   In the past, it has usually taken three or four weeks to get
official approval to visit Hungary once an application is filed with
East German police.
   Getting approval to travel to the West can take years, and many
applications are rejected.
   Official figures are not available on the number of East Germans
who file applications to visit Hungary or the West.
   But, according to unofficial estimates, at least 1 million of
East Germany's 16.6 million people want to leave their Communist
homeland for good.
   Hungary has long offered East German vacationers a refreshing
change, even more so since Hungary set out on the road toward major
political reforms.
   A 1969 border agreement between the two countries was an obstacle
to East Germans who might be tempted to try to cross into the West
from Hungary.
   But in May, Hungary began removing its border barriers. At least
6,000 East Germans took advantage of the removals and fled to the
West this summer.
   Then, on Sunday, Budapest announced that any of the 60,000 East
Germans in Hungary who wanted to leave for the West could do so.
   Thousands of those ``vacationers'', many of them having spent
several weeks in refugee camps, headed straight for the Austrian
border and Hungarian officials said thousands more were arriving
from East Germany via Czechoslovakia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890913-0061 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 0428EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Germany-Welcome     09-13 0547</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-Welcome,0569</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bavarians Greet East Germans; Newcomers Worried about Reprisals</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Refugees, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASSAU, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bulletin board inside Passau's huge
convention center has become the hub for many East German refugees
trying to catch up with friends and relatives or find jobs and
housing.
   ``To the Drichel family from Coswig. Call Hilda. We've found you
a place to stay,'' reads one note on the board at Niebelungenhalle.
   About 500 of the new arrivals are staying at the center, which
has been filled with bunks and stoves and become a community in
itself.
   Many of the estimated 11,000 refugees who have arrived since
Hungary began letting them flee to the West at midnight Sunday
filled five tent camps near the Austrian border and officials sought
more space in military barracks.
   In Passau, several hundred local residents waited for hours to
greet new arrivals with cheers, tears, hugs and job offers.
   A large banner outside the center said ``Herzlich Willkommen,''
or ``hearfelt greetings.'' Red and silver helium balloons bearing
the same message bobbed among the well-wishers.
   ``This reception is really amazing,'' said Ute Kindl, a young
East German woman. ``I'm really speechless over the warmness and
kindness here.''
   Some said they were deeply grateful to Hungary for opening its
border.
   ``We'll never be able to repay them for this,'' said Heinz
Schmidt.
   Inside Niebelungenhalle, Red Cross and other relief workers
advised the emigres on how to get settled. Local residents donated
hundreds of coats, dresses and other clothes.
   Many refugees roamed the enormous building seeking information
about friends and relatives who had made the trek West.
   One source was the bulletin board.
   ``Hello Michael, I'm at the Wilshofen camp. Your brother,
Andreas,'' said one note, referring to one of several tent
communities for refugees in Bavaria.
   ``Would like to make contact with people from Karl-Marx Stadt (an
East German city). I was born there,'' wrote one woman.
   Another message saids: ``Hello Kirsten! Remember Gabi from
school? Reachable this weekend.'
   The bulletin board also contained offers of jobs ranging from
bakers to nurses and electricians. Many prospective employers have
been accustomed to having difficulty finding skilled craftsmen and
apprentices.
   Hans Klein, chief government spokesman told a news conference
that in Passau alone ``8,000 job offers have been received'' for
emigres.
   While the locals warmly greeted the refugees, elsewhere in West
Germany the flood of emigres _ and ethnic Germans from other parts
of Eastern Europe _ has caused some resentment. A few West Germans
fear the newcomers are taking away jobs and scarce housing.
   Although the emigres were jubilant upon arriving in the West,
some also were worried about possible reprisals against loved ones
left behind in their communist homeland.
   Scores lined up at public telephones to call families in East
Germany and friends and relatives in West Germany.
   ``Our parents still don't know for sure what we have done,'' said
one young man who arrived with his wife from Leipzig. They asked not
to be identified by name to reduce the risk of problems for their
family.
   ``We just hope this won't hurt them. They (East German security
officials) have a way of making life difficult for people whose
relatives have fled to the West,'' the man said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890913-0062 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 0317EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     09-13 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Dips, Stocks Also Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar closed marginally lower against the
Japanese yen Wednesday, while the Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index
also declined.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, a 219.22-point winner
Tuesday, closed at 34,286.94, down 45.94 points or 0.13 percent.
   The dollar closed at 146.70 yen, down 0.03 yen from Tuesday's
close of 146.73 yen. It opened higher at 147.23 yen, and traded
between 146.60 yen and 147.30 yen.
   Currency traders said the dollar, which rose in early trading
following its overnight gains on overseas markets, slipped as market
players in Tokyo sold the currency for position adjustments.
   ``The currency rate was moving very little in Tokyo,'' said Toru
Kanai, a foreign exchange analyst with New Japan Securities Co.
   He said trading was mixed, mainly because market players were
reluctant to make major moves prior to U.S. economic reports due out
later this week.
   The United States is to announce a series of economic figures,
including the retail price index for August due out Thursday and
trade figures for July on Friday. Such figures are watched closely
as indicators of U.S. economic performance.
   ``Until then, participants will remain cautious lacking fresh
market-affecting news,'' Kanai said.
   On the stock exchange, the index fell as market players stepped
off to the sidelines, discouraged by the dollar's rebound against
the yen, stock dealers said.
   Participants, mostly institutional investors, sold shipbuilding
and steel issues to take profits from gains the previous day, said a
dealer with a major securities firm, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
