<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 0502EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Philippines-Politics     09-13 0710</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-Politics,0732</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gun-Smuggling Case Emerges Into Major Political Issue, Challenge
To Aquino</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A simple case of gun-running has
emerged as a major national issue, challenging President Corazon
Aquino to deliver on promises to dispense justice and restore ethics
in government regardless of the political cost.
   The episode began Sept. 5 when customs agents at Ninoy Aquino
International Airport found 314 handguns and rifles in baggage
allegedly owned by Rep. Nicanor de Guzman, who had just arrived from
California.
   De Guzman, a member of the pro-Aquino Struggle of the Democratic
Filipino party, denied owning the weapons. Philippine Airlines
claimed he and a Filipino businessman checked in the luggage at Los
Angeles International Airport.
   The incident quickly took on a political dimension. De Guzman, an
obscure lawmaker from Nueva Ecija province, is an associate of Mrs.
Aquino's powerful brother, Rep. Jose ``Peping'' Cojuangco.
   In addition, the incident occurred amid growing discontent over
perceived corruption in government, inaction in Congress, political
favoritism and a breakdown in the criminal justice system.
   De Guzman remains free pending a magistrate's investigation. Last
month, however, Dominique Adams, a 22-year-old Salt Lake City woman,
was jailed after customs found 70 handguns in her luggage.
   She was freed on bail and is awaiting trial.
   Preferential treatment of de Guzman risks charges of political
favoritism similar to what was rampant under ousted President
Ferdinand Marcos. A rush to justice risks undermining the system of
political alliances which has helped keep Mrs. Aquino in power.
   ``What is at stake here is not only the case of one man,'' said
Rep. Oscar Santos. ``This is not for the survival of the political
life of one man but the collective life of Congress itself because
people might no longer believe in us.''
   So much media attention has been generated by the case that even
if de Guzman is innocent and exonerated, many Filipinos will assume
he got off because of political connections.
   ``Almost everything the citizenry detests, hates and abominates
are writ large on this unfortunate affair,'' wrote Mrs. Aquino's
former spokesman Teodoro Benigno in the Philippine Daily Star.
``Unless she (Mrs. Aquino) moves fast and moves dramatically, she
can be overtaken and overpowered by events.''
   Realizing the political risks, presidential advisers moved to
contain the fallout. Through inept handling, they made the situation
worse.
   Two days after the weapons were seized, Mrs. Aquino summoned
reporters and declared there would be ``no white-wash.'' But
reporters' questions centered on rumors that her brother tried to
intercede on de Guzman's behalf.
   ``As soon as I was informed of the discovery of firearms at the
airport, I called up my brother and told him that apparently some
people are dropping your name,'' Mrs. Aquino said. ``And definitely,
he has no knowledge of the matter.''
   Mrs. Aquino never fully explained why her first reaction was to
call her brother. Asked why Cojuangco's name was often linked with
political intrigue, Mrs. Aquino delivered a rambling answer which
included the Biblical admonition about those without sin casting the
first stone.
   The next day, headlines in Manila newspapers focused on Mrs.
Aquino's defense of her brother rather than her promise of no
whitewash.
   The de Guzman case also threatens to strain relations between the
administration and the House of Representatives.
   Early today, the House decided to suspend de Guzman for 60 days.
But some congressmen complained the administration wanted to
``sacrifice'' one of their colleagues to boost its image.
   Through a system of alliances forged largely by Cojuangco and
House Speaker Ramon Mitra, the 199-member House had been the more
pro-administration of the two Congressional chambers.
   But relations worsened after the Cabinet announced last month
that firearms imported by House members in 1988 but confiscated by
the military would be publicly burned to show Mrs. Aquino's ``strong
commitment'' to law and order.
   House members were widely criticized for trying to import the
weapons. Many of them felt the Cabinet had revived the embarassing
issue to enhance Mrs. Aquino's reputation at their expense.
   The Cabinet announcement followed a report by a private survey
group, the Social Weather Stations, that Mrs. Aquino's approval rate
among Manila residents had dropped to 35 percent, the lowest of her
administration.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
