<FIRST>r p PM-WrightSeat     09-13 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wright Seat,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texas Democrats Hold onto Wright Seat</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Primary Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DN2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICE GRAVINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Pete Geren barely defeated a
Republican for the seat held 34 years by another Democrat _ Rep. Jim
Wright. Then he acknowledged he faced a big job in Washington.
   ``No one fills the shoes of the speaker of the House,'' Geren
said. ``It's going to be a long road back to restoring the clout and
the influence that Fort Worth and Tarrant County have grown used to
having.''
   Geren received 40,210 votes, or 51 percent, to 38,590 ballots, or
49 percent, for television commentator Dr. Bob Lanier in Tuesday's
special election runoff to replace Wright, who resigned during an
ethics investigation.
   The 37-year-old winner, a former aide to Sen. Lloyd Bentsen of
Texas, will serve the remainder of Wright's term, which ends next
year.
   Lanier, who received endorsements from President Bush and former
Dallas Cowboys coach Tom Landry, told supporters not to throw away
campaign signs because he'll probably challenge Geren in 1990 for
the seat.
   ``We don't feel like we really lost that much,'' said the
44-year-old political newcomer. ``I mean, we did better than
anybody's done in this county for this particular party.''
   Lanier led Geren and six other candidates in a special election
Aug. 12, but didn't gain a majority, making the runoff necessary. He
is featured as medical commentator on ``60-Second Housecall,'' a
television spot syndicated to local news broadcasts in more than 40
television markets.
   Republicans had hoped to break the Democrats' grip on the
district, but Geren raised almost twice as much money as Lanier and
had previous experience: a 1986 loss to Republican Joe Barton for a
different congressional district.
   Voters showed little interest in the campaign. About 27 percent
of the 287,000 registered voters turned out.
   Wright resigned in June amid allegations he repeatedly violated
congressional ethics rules involving speaking fees and business
deals.
   During the campaign to succeed Wright, Geren and Lanier
emphasized their endorsements and differing backgrounds.
   Geren, endorsed by Wright and Bentsen, cited his experience as a
legislative aide.
   Lanier said he was in better touch with his constituents'
concerns than his opponent.
   Geren supports sending U.S. troops to Colombia to fight drug
dealers, opposes restrictions on owning semiautomatic weapons and
signed a pledge to vote against any new taxes. He said the war on
drugs will be his first concern on Capitol Hill.
</TEXT>
