<FIRST>r a PM-AlaskaOtters     09-13 0223</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Alaska Otters,0229</SECOND>
<HEAD>Last of Otters Affected by Spill Headed to Zoos</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The last 13 otter pups rounded up after the
Exxon Valdez oil spill six months ago have been shipped from Alaska
to the Point Defiance Zoo and Aquarium.
   The otters arrived Tuesday and were to spend up to three months
at Point Defiance before being sent to zoos and aquariums around the
United States, said associate zoo director Lily Moore.
   She said the otters cannot be released in the wild because they
have become too accustomed to people.
   A staff paid by Exxon will provide 24-hour care for the otters
until they go to other zoos. They will not be on public display.
   The 13 otters either were rescued from the nation's worst oil
spill or born to mothers who had been brought to animal care centers
in Seward and Valdez, Alaska, after the March 24 spill in Prince
William Sound.
   ``These are orphans of the spill that will go other places,
hopefully to remind people there is a place otters can live in the
wild, and that place is fragile,'' said Bruce Batten of the U.S.
Fish &amp; Wildlife Service in Anchorage.
   The wildlife service said only the Anchorage eagle center and the
Seward bird center still are caring for wildlife harmed by the spill.
</TEXT>
