<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 0557EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-TortoiseQuarantine     09-13 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tortoise Quarantine,0460</SECOND>
<HEAD>BLM Orders Closure of 59 Square Miles of Desert to Protect Tortoise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOJAVE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government will close 59 square
miles of the Mojave Desert under an emergency quarantine in hopes of
protecting the endangered desert tortoise.
   ``There is some evidence that some of the users out there are
increasing the stress level in the tortoise,'' said Barbara
Maxfield, a Bureau of Land Management spokeswoman in Riverside.
   ``Vandalism is the major cause for the decline in the
population.''
   The closure, to begin Oct. 1 and last up to a year, will affect
recreationalists, specifically off-road enthusiasts who drive
all-terrain vehicles through the desert, Mrs. Maxfield said Tuesday.
   Sheep grazing will continue as long as enough forage is left for
the sheep. Sheep ranchers must apply for special permission to set
foot on the land, officials said.
   Gerald Hillier, BLM California Desert district manager, said a
minimum of 350 pounds of food for sheep must be available per acre.
   ``The desert tortoises must have emerged before we will allow the
sheep on public lands,'' Hillier said. ``No more than five bands of
800 animals each will be permitted.''
   He said there were provisions for miners also.
   The quarantine area is north of this desert city, 70 miles north
of Los Angeles.
   It was called so that researchers could monitor the species,
which was placed on the endangered list Aug. 4 by the U.S. Fish and
Wildlife Service.
   Biologists are concerned that a respiratory disease is killing
thousands of the burrowing tortoises, which can live up to 80 years.
Ravens and man's encroachment on the desert also threaten the desert
animals.
   The non-profit Desert Tortoise Preserve Committee estimated last
year that since the 1920s, population has declined from an estimated
1,000 per square mile to as few as 20 per square mile in some parts
of the Mojave in California.
   Designation of the desert tortoise as an endangered species has
disrupted a construction boom in Las Vegas. The gambling city and
several other parties filed suit last month in federal court in
Washington, D.C., claiming restrictions on building should be
confined only to areas where the respiratory disease is a problem.
   Two off-road races scheduled for Sunday in the desert were
canceled by the BLM because of fears the motorcycles and
four-wheel-drive vehicles would upset the species. The American
Motorcyclist Association, which sponsored both races, said the BLM's
decision discriminates against off-road enthusiasts.
   Signs may be posted to warn of the closure and some fencing may
be erected, Mrs. Maxfield said. Ranger patrols will be increased,
she added, saying that those caught in the area would be cited for
trespassing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
