<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 0605EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p PM-KochProfile     09-13 0723</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Koch Profile,0748</SECOND>
<HEAD>Koch's Last Hurrah</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Primary Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY SCHWARTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Edward I. Koch's first mayoral campaign lasted
just 45 days, and ended with neither a whimper nor a bang. It ended
in silence _ no one paid attention to this liberal congressman in
1973.
   What was trumpeted as Koch's last campaign for mayor ended
Tuesday with a thumping defeat that altered the political landscape
of the nation's largest city, perhaps forever.
   The man whose feisty, nasal tones came to signify New York for 12
years was defeated by Manhattan Borough President David Dinkins, who
became the city's first black mayoral nominee of a major party. And
everybody was paying attention this time.
   ``I want you not to feel sorry for me,'' Koch, 64, told
supporters, saying he had had ``12 glorious years as mayor.''
   ``Believe me, there is a life after the mayoralty,'' he said.
   Koch congratulated Dinkins saying, ``he won it fairly, squarely
and by a large margin _ a substantial victory.''
   Koch lost for many reasons. Among them:
   _Early in his administration, he alienated many blacks by closing
a Harlem hospital after promising to keep it open. He was constantly
accused of racial insensitivity, especially when he suggested Jews
would have to be crazy to vote for presidential candidate Jesse
Jackson in 1988.
   _His third term was besieged by corruption. Queens Borough
President Donald Manes committed suicide as scandals were uncovered.
Indictments followed.
   _Many grew tired of Koch's act. Irish-Americans were infuriated
when he said the British army was a peacekeeping force, not an army
of occupation. Others were offended when he declared war on street
peddlers.
   Twelve years ago, his outspoken behavior charmed many.
   Koch, the Bronx-born son of Polish immigrants, began his
political career as a liberal.
   In 1963, he toppled Democratic Party boss Carmine DeSapio in a
race for district leader. Koch was elected to City Council in 1966
and to Congress from Manhattan's Silk Stocking district two years
later.
   His 1973 campaign for mayor foundered for lack of money, and 1977
did not look much more encouraging. He faced seven other candidates,
including incumbent Abe Beame and the flamboyant Bella Abzug.
   In the summer of the Son of Sam serial killings, Koch pounded
away at one issue _ the death penalty. His ads were created by media
wizard David Garth, he often was seen arm-in-arm with former Miss
America Bess Myerson.
   Coming from nowhere, Koch was the top vote-getter in the primary.
In a runoff, he defeated New York Secretary of State Mario Cuomo; in
November, he beat Cuomo, who was the Liberal nominee, and two others.
   He kept his one-bedroom apartment in Greenwich Village, though he
grew more accustomed to life in Gracie Mansion. He took the subway
to his inauguration. He rejoiced in cheap wines and Chinese
restaurants.
   Koch had an opinion on just about everything. When President
Carter came to town, Koch greeted him with a letter protesting
administration policy on the Middle East. He called Carter's
brother, Billy, a ``whacko.''
   Koch wrote a best-seller, ``Mayor,'' then ``Politics'' and, in
collaboration with Cardinal John O'Connor, ``His Eminence and
Hizzoner.''
   ``How'm I doin'?'' the mayor asked again and again.
   The answer, for a long time, was positive. Koch was credited with
managing city government well and helping New York emerge from the
fiscal crisis. He was re-elected by an overwhelming margin in 1981.
   His first setback came in 1982. After promising he never would
seek another elective office, he announced his candidacy for
governor. Cuomo beat him.
   In 1985, Koch easily won re-election again. Then things began to
fall apart.
   The scandals erupted. Koch suffered a minor stroke. A patronage
scheme operating out of City Hall was uncovered. The mayor never was
accused of corruption, but the damage had been done.
   Also, two black men died in separate confrontations with white
gangs, the second just weeks before the election.
   Problems that were not issues in 1977 _ drugs, AIDS, homelessness
_ plagued the city. Koch's ratings plunged to under 30 percent. But
he fought back, closing Dinkins' lead.
   ``I've had 12 wonderful years and expect to have four more,''
Koch said earlier Tuesday. ``But I have had a professional life that
everybody could envy. I've enjoyed _ with the pain, occasionally _
every day.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
