<DOCNO> AP890913-0069 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 0558EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SolarFlare     09-13 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Solar Flare,0405</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Space Mission Takes Clearest Image to Date of Solar Flare</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD BENKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rocket-mounted telescope has provided
the clearest photographs ever taken of a solar flare and the sun's
outer corona, a scientist said.
   With only a 1{-hour launch window on Monday, scientists halted
the countdown two minutes before ignition and waited for signs of a
solar flare before launching the telescope aboard a 50-foot rocket
from White Sands Missile Range.
   Leon Golub, a Harvard University astrophysicist who headed the
project, said he received satellite data indicating an increase in
X-rays associated with solar flares before resuming the countdown.
   The rocket soared to a height of about 200 miles before
parachuting back to Earth with 40 frames of exposed film.
   Solar flares are eruptions that burst suddenly from the face of
the sun, sending waves of electromagnetic radiation and charged
particles out into space. They can disrupt communications and cause
northern lights on Earth.
   The sun currently is at the peak of an 11-year cycle for flare
activity, but even so no more than 10 flares occur each day, Golub
said in a telephone interview late Tuesday from Sunspot, N.M.
   In a photograph released Tuesday, dramatic disturbances are seen
swirling all across the face of the sun, including one peculiar
double-loop flare that Golub said he could not explain.
   Elsewhere, bright loops are all part of the corona, a layer of
ionized gas surrounding the sun, he said.
   ``This picture shows much more detail than has ever been seen
before in the corona,'' Golub said.
   The photo also revealed a small point of bright light on the
sun's surface. One theory suggests that such bright points are
minimal during peak flare periods and increase dramatically as
flares subside. Golub said he hopes to take more photos during a
time of minimum solar activity in about five years to see if there
are more bright points.
   ``This is the first time we've ever really been able to see one
of those little things,'' he said of the small bright spot. ``If we
look again at solar minimum, the sun might actually be covered with
hundreds of those small regions.''
   Golub said his camera improved on earlier models by using a
mirror with multiple coatings that screen out all but one X-ray
wavelength.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890913-0070 </DOCNO>
