<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     09-13 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0253</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Nikkei Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar edged down a fraction against the yen
today, while the Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index declined.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which had gained
219.22 points Tuesday, closed at 34,286.94. It was down 45.94
points, or 0.13 percent, from Tuesday's finish of 34,332.88 points.
   Volume was estimated at a thin 600 million shares, compared with
a daily average of 1 billion.
   The dollar opened higher at 147.23 yen, and ranged between 146.60
yen and 147.30 yen. It closed at 146.70 yen, down 0.03 yen from
Tuesday's close of 146.73 yen.
   Volume was estimated at $7.696 billion, up from Tuesday's $6.446
billion.
   Currency traders said the dollar was firm in early trading
following its overnight gains on overseas markets, but slipped as
dealers sold the currency or stood aside to await U.S. economic data
due for release later this week.
   ``The currency rate was showing little movement in Tokyo,'' said
Toru Kanai, a foreign exchange analyst with New Japan Securities Co.
   He said trading was mixed, mainly because dealers were reluctant
to make major moves before U.S. economic reports due out Thursday
and Friday. They include the retail price index for August and trade
figures for July.
   ``Until then, participants will remain cautious,'' Kanai said.
   On the stock market, the key index fell as investors remained on
the sidelines, discouraged by the little movement in the dollar's
rate, dealers said.
</TEXT>
