<DOCNO> AP890913-0071 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 0559EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Restaurant-Racism     09-13 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Restaurant-Racism,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>Restaurant Owner Drops No-Blacks Policy for James Brown's Lawyer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORTH AUGUSTA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A restaurant owner says he dropped a
longstanding policy of refusing to serve black customers after
enjoying a visit from an attorney for soul singer James Brown.
   Bruce Salter, operator of the Buffalo Room, said he would
continue serving blacks ``as long as they don't come in and tear up
the place.''
   Salter's policy against serving blacks has made the Buffalo Room
the subject of investigations by the FBI, Justice Department civil
rights division and the state Alcoholic Beverage Control Commission.
   George Hill, a black lawyer whose client Brown is in prison in
Columbia, said Salter let him into the restaurant and bar twice
Tuesday.
   Hill said he had read that Salter claimed to have once kicked
Brown out of his establishment.
   ``I wanted to check it out,'' Hill said.
   Hill said when he knocked on the door early Tuesday afternoon,
Salter slammed the door in his face. Hill waited at the door and
Salter peeped his head out and asked what he wanted.
   ``I told him, `I think you're a nice man,''' Hill said.
   Salter again retreated. About five minutes later he walked out
onto the covered porch and asked Hill what he had meant about being
a nice man.
   ``He was breathing fire when I first came,'' Hill said.
``Eventually he invited me in. We came into the bar first and then
he said `come on in the dining room and sit down, I want to talk to
you some more.' It turned into a 2{ hour visit.''
   Salter said he invited Hill back because Hill is an intelligent
man and he enjoyed talking to him.
   Hill said he believes Salter will continue serving blacks, and
did not invite him in just because the alcohol commission has
scheduled a license revocation hearing for the Buffalo Room on Oct.
12.
   Asked whether admitting Hill had anything to do with the hearing,
Salter said: ``I ain't gong to say nothing. Let them think what they
want.''
   The 1964 Civil Rights Act prohibits discrimination on the basis
of race in such public places as restaurants. Conviction carries a
maximum sentence of a $1,000 fine and a year in prison.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
