<FIRST>r p PM-BuffaloMayor     09-13 0224</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Buffalo Mayor,0230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Incumbent Griffin Wins Democratic Primary in Bid for Fourth Term</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Primary Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Incumbent James Griffin defeated two
challengers in a a Democratic primary, bringing him within striking
distance of an unprecedented fourth four-year term.
   Griffin received 28,490 votes, or 41 percent, on Tuesday to
24,568 ballots, or 36 percent, for former city Judge Wilbur Trammell
and 15,971, or 23 percent, for state Assemblyman William Hoyt.
   Trammell had been seeking to become the city's first black mayor.
Hoyt was endorsed by the party.
   The victory gave Griffin four ballot lines in the Nov. 7 general
election. He was unchallenged in the primary as the endorsed
candidate of the Republican, Conservative and Right to Life parties.
   ``I think people realized what we've done over the past 12
years,'' Griffin, 60, said Tuesday night. ``And, I ran a positive
campaign, I think people responded to that.''
   Hoyt, 52, and Trammell, 62, also are expected to be on the
November ballot. Hoyt has the Liberal Party's endoresement and
Trammell is seeking to run as an independent.
   Griffin campaigned mostly on his record, saying he revitalized
downtown and the Lake Erie waterfront, helped restore neighborhoods
and created jobs.
   Trammell received campaign help from former Democratic
presidential candidate Jesse Jackson, Atlanta Mayor Andrew Young and
former Rep. Shirley Chisolm, D-N.Y.
