<FIRST>r a PM-RappersFined     09-13 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rappers Fined,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Fines Rappers for Lewd Concert</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge fined three members of the rap groups
NWA and Too Short $100 each on charges of disorderly conduct, saying
their Riverfront Coliseum concert was lewd and disgraceful.
   Too Short member Todd Shaw, 23, of Hayward, Calif., and NWA
members Osea ``Ice Cube'' Jackson, 20, of Los Angeles, and Lorenzo
Patterson, 22, of Long Beach, Calif., also were ordered to pay $30
each in court costs.
   Two other NWA members also faced municipal court hearings on the
charges. Antoine Carraby, 27, of Compton, Calif., was to appear
today, and Eric ``Eazy-E'' Wright, 25, also of Compton, is scheduled
for a hearing Monday.
   Municipal Judge Harry H. McIlwain on Tuesday rejected a motion to
dismiss the case on grounds the charges violated the performers'
freedom of speech rights. The judge stayed the fines for 30 days to
let the performers appeal.
   ``I want you to appeal, and I just hope the courts don't make the
same kind of mistake with this that they did with the decision to
allow burning the American flag,'' McIlwain told lawyers for the
performers, who didn't appear in court.
   Defense Attorney Louis Sirkin conceded that the performers
repeatedly asked members of the youthful audience to come onto the
stage to engage in sex acts, but said that didn't constitute
disorderly conduct.
   ``What may be offensive to some is entertainment to others,''
Sirkin said.
   Ernest McAdams Jr., assistant city prosecutor, retorted, ``The
First Amendment was not designed to protect people ... from public
obscenity charges.''
</TEXT>
