<FIRST>r p PM-DetroitMayor     09-13 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Detroit Mayor,0523</SECOND>
<HEAD>Accountant Wins Spot in Runoff Against Coleman Young</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Primary Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DT3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEOFFREY HAYNES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Accountant Tom Barrow knocked off 13-term
congressman John Conyers in the city's non-partisan mayoral primary
to win a spot in a runoff against four-term incumbent Coleman Young.
   ``You can run Coleman, but you can't hide,'' Barrow, a nephew of
prizefighter Joe Louis, told frenzied supporters Tuesday night at
his victory rally.
   ``It's time for you to come on out here because we're going to
talk about issues. You're gonna have to explain, Coleman, why it is
that crime is so bad and what you intend to do to stop it.''
   Young, the city's first black mayor and dean of the nation's
black city executives, wouldn't commit to a debate with Barrow, whom
he beat 61 percent to 39 percent in the 1985 election.
   With all precincts reporting, Young had 103,827 votes, or 51
percent, and Barrow had 48,695 votes, or 24 percent. Conyers was
third with 36,247, or 18 percent. Ten other candidates, including
City Council President Erma Henderson in a distant fourth place,
shared the rest of the vote.
   Young, 71, celebrated at a jammed reception where music from
Michael Jackson's ``Bad'' album boomed over a sound system.
   ``Don't celebrate too long, because the war is not over,'' he
said. ``The victory is not won.''
   Conyers, who entered the race a day before the filing deadline in
May, refused to concede during a brief appearance at a reception
Tuesday night.
   Barrow, 40, campaigned practically since losing the 1985 race.
But he has never held office and does not have a well-financed
political machine to match Young's.
   ``I think Barrow unfortunately is not going to be able to
mobilize the kind of organizational structure necessary to unseat
the mayor,'' said Wilbur Rich, an associate professor of political
science at Wayne State University and the author of a Young
biography. ``I think he'll try to replay the 1985 election, which is
not going to be enough to give the mayor serious competition.''
   Barrow campaigned on what he called Young's favoritism of
downtown development over neighborhood renewal. Young, meanwhile,
pointed to jobs and riverfront development created during his 16
years in office.
   Young reported raising $5 million for what he says is his last
election, an unprecedented fifth term. Barrow campaign manager
Geoffrey Garfield said Barrow's grassroots approach can match
Young's media barrage.
   ``We out-organized everybody else, that's why we won,'' Garfield
said. ``It wasn't about the media, the radio or computers. We had
people power and went door to door.
   ``Now that people know that Coleman can be beaten, we expect
fund-raising will pick up. We got this far against a 25-year
congressman that everyone thought was going to wipe us out. It was
the most organized campaign this city has seen in 20 years.''
   Conyers, whose campaign appeared unfocused, was given a slight
edge over Barrow in pre-election polls because of his name
recognition and quarter-century in Congress representing Detroit's
west side.
</TEXT>
