<SECOND>PM-Miss America-Preliminaries,0518</SECOND>
<HEAD>Miss Missouri, Miss Ohio Win Preliminary Miss America Competitions</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY STERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The winner of the first preliminary
swimsuit competition in this year's Miss America Pageant says she
didn't eat the most recommended meal for a young woman about to
parade down a runway.
   ``I had five cookies for dinner,'' Miss Missouri, Debbye Turner,
said after Tuesday's competition. Wearing a blue terry-cloth robe
over her canary yellow swimsuit, she said, ``I don't believe in
starving.''
   Meanwhile, Miss Ohio, Kristin Huffman, won the first preliminary
talent competition with a powerful vocal performance.
   Miss Huffman, who has said she does not want to be known as a
``bible banger,'' could not resist giving thanks to her parents and
the power of their prayer for her victory.
   ``I felt good vibes from them,'' she said of her parents, both
singers, who were in the audience.
   Miss Turner, a 5-foot-7{, 118-pound brunette from Mexico, Mo.,
said she may have even put on a little weight since winning her
state pageant.
   ``I was probably a little smaller three months ago,'' she said.
   However, she said she had worked hard through aerobic
weightlifting to maintain her figure. ``Being on stage in a swimsuit
does motivate one not to have tummy,'' she said.
   The 23-year-old senior at the University of Missouri-Columbia
Veterinary School lists as one of her hobbies collecting ``surgery
souvenirs,'' which include puppy fetuses and cat spines.
   Miss Huffman, a 24-year-old from Canal Winchester, Ohio, sang a
classical piece titled ``Csardas'' to win the talent contest.
   ``My major goal is just to make sure people enjoy it,'' she said.
   She performed her powerful number in a tomato-red sheath trimmed
in gold sequins and a flowing red train, and carried a sequined mask
decorated with red ostrich feathers.
   Miss Huffman, an olive-eyed blonde who hopes to become an opera
singer and teach voice at a college, said she knew she performed
well because ``the heat was coming off me.''
   She recently graduated from Northwestern University with a
master's degree in music. For 21 years, she has performed with her
family's professional singing group for community, business and
church groups.
   Tuesday's competition was the first of three nights of swimsuit,
talent and evening gown rounds. The winners of the evening gown
competitions will be kept secret to heighten the suspense for the
final night.
   The preliminary competitions for the 51 contestants are the first
steps to the live televised Miss America Pageant on Saturday. On
Friday night, the contestants participate in the colorful Miss
America Parade on the resort's Boardwalk.
   The 10 women who accumulate the most points in the preliminary
rounds and interviews with the judges will start all over again
Saturday night for the right to succeed Miss America 1989, Gretchen
Elizabeth Carlson.
   The 63rd annual pageant will air live on NBC-TV at 10 p.m. EDT
Saturday. Gary Collins and Miss America 1971, Phyllis George Brown,
will be the hosts.
</TEXT>
