<FIRST>r p PM-CoelhoSeat     09-13 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Coelho Seat,0446</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democrat Wins Race to Succeed Coelho in Congress</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Primary Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FR1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COLLEEN BARRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MODESTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic state Assemblyman Gary Condit
won a special election for the seat of former House Democratic Whip
Tony Coelho, who resigned in June rather than face a probe of his
finances.
   Relying heavily on Coelho's loyal supporters and strong political
organization in this agricultural San Joaquin Valley district,
Condit won 57 percent of the vote in Tuesday's primary and easily
avoided a November runoff.
   Clare Berryhill, a 64-year-old Republican rancher, former state
legislator and ex-director of the state agriculture department, was
a distant second.
   With all precincts reporting, Condit had 50,527 votes to
Berryhill's 31,166, or 35 percent. Five other Republicans and a
Libertarian divided the remaining 8 percent.
   Under state law, all candidates appear on the same primary
ballot, allowing voters to cross party lines.
   Coelho left the House following disclosures that he failed to
report a $50,000 loan to finance a junk bond deal. He said there was
nothing improper about the loan and that it was not reported because
of a clerical error.
   But the incident was magnified because it coincided with the
ethics probe and downfall of former House Speaker Jim Wright, and
Coelho said he wanted to avoid giving Republicans two prominent
Democratic targets.
   Though Coelho left Congress under a cloud, Condit and Berryhill
said Tuesday night that Coelho's support was a major factor in the
41-year-old Democrat's victory. Condit will serve the remainder of
Coelho's term, which expires in 1990.
   ``They had Tony Coelho's political machine behind them, so they
were better organized. We were at a disadvantage from the very
beginning,'' Berryhill said.
   Condit said Coelho's resignation was not an issue because ``the
voters in this district respected the way Tony stepped down. He was
a great asset to the district.''
   Instead of keeping his distance, Condit used television ads and
mailings that stressed his ties to Coelho.
   ``I feel fabulous. It's a great victory,'' a jubilant Condit told
about 300 supporters at his victory party.
   Major issues in the race included abortion, highway congestion
and agricultural problems.
   Condit said he personally opposed abortion but saw it as a
``personal decision that one needs to make for one's self.''
Berryhill opposed abortion except in cases involving rape, incest
and a threat to the life of the mother, and he claimed the support
of the California Pro Life Council.
   Robert Weimer, a Republican who fashioned himself as ``the only
full-blown pro-choice candidate,'' drew only 3.3 percent of the vote.
</TEXT>
