<HEAD>Rain Drenches South-central United States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms drenched parts of the south-central
United States today as central Oklahoma got more than 5 inches of
rain, and precipitation continued from the southern Plains into
western Missouri.
   Flash flood watches were in effect for parts of Texas as well as
Oklahoma.
   Late evening thunderstorms in Oklahoma produced high winds in the
Okemah area, damaging several homes and knocking down trees and
power lines.
   Thunderstorms also struck southern Arizona, producing golf
ball-size hail and 61 mph gusts at Sierra Vista.
   Showers and thunderstorms also developed from western North
Carolina to Delaware early this morning.
   Rain fell in the middle Mississippi Valley, and along the
southern Atlantic and Gulf coasts.
   Fair skies prevailed across the rest of the nation.
   In eastern Colorado a snow advisory was posted for the northern
foothills, the Palmer Divide, and the northern and central mountains
where 4 to 7 inches were expected.
   A freeze advisory was in effect this morning for northeastern
Colorado, and central Wyoming, and a frost advisory for northeastern
Minnesota.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms scattered
from Florida and the Gulf Coast region, the Tennessee and lower
Mississippi Valley to the southern Plains, as well as the central
and southern Appalachians; rain widespread from the central Rockies
across the central Plains and the middle Mississippi Valley into the
upper Great Lakes.
   High temperatures were expected to reach the 70s and 80s across
much of the nation.
   Highs likely would be 10 to 20 degrees below normal across the
Central Plains and mid-Mississippi Valley.
   Other predicted highs: 60s in northern Maine; 90s from Florida
and southern Georgia across the Gulf Coast region into southern
Texas; and 90 to 105 from the desert Southwest into interior valleys
of California and Oregon.
   The nation's temperatures at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 29 degrees at
Yellowstone Park in Wyoming to 85 at Phoenix.
