<FIRST>r p PM-DinkinsProfile     09-13 0651</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dinkins Profile,0673</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dinkins Wins Historic Nomination</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Primary Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   David Dinkins lost the first office he was
elected to when the Harlem district he represented in the state
Assembly was gerrymandered out of existence.
   Now Dinkins is charting new political territory.
   Tuesday night he became the first black politician ever nominated
by a major party to run for mayor of New York City, defeating Mayor
Edward I. Koch in the Democratic primary. He will face Republican
nominee Rudolph Giuliani in his bid to become the city's first black
mayor.
   ``You, the people of New York, made history today and I promise
you I shall never let you down,'' Dinkins, 62, told supporters at
his victory celebration.
   Koch also had sought to make history _ he was pursuing an
unprecedented fourth term. But Dinkins blamed him for ethnic and
racial tensions and corruption scandals. The fatal shooting of a
black teen-ager confronted by a gang of whites three weeks before
the election heightened the issue of race.
   Racial harmony was a centerpiece of Dinkins' campaign, and he
portrayed himself as a ``healer.''
   ``We're all together now. Remember me? I'm the guy that brings
people together,'' Dinkins said in his victory speech.
   To Dinkins' supporters, such an attitude is typical. They say he
is cautious and thoughtful, a conciliator and consensus-builder.
   They also say he is a gentleman. Even opponents like the
contentious Koch agree Dinkins is ``a very decent guy.''
   But some question whether a nice guy can run a city facing a
myriad of difficult problems, stand up to special interests fighting
over its $27 billion budget and ride herd over its more than 200,000
employees.
   ``He has been careful to the point of timidity and his indecision
sometimes frustrates his colleagues,'' The New York Times said of
Dinkins when it endorsed Koch.
   His friends say that's unfair.
   ``Some people try to be critical of the fact that he gives
reasoned, well thought-out opinions, which should be valued in
public officials,'' said Rep. Charles Rangel.
   A Trenton, N.J., native, he graduated in 1950 from Howard
University with a mathematics degree. He moved to Harlem in 1951 and
was married two years later.
   Dinkins graduated from Brooklyn Law School in 1956 and became a
Democratic district leader. In 1965, he won a state Assembly seat
but lost a re-election bid after his district was reapportioned.
   He served as city clerk for 10 years until he was elected
Manhattan borough president in 1985 on his third attempt. He is the
city's highest elected black officeholder.
   He has been outspoken against apartheid in South Africa, yet was
slow to comment on the case of Tawana Brawley, a black teen-ager who
claimed she was sexually assaulted by a group of white men. When he
did he was critical of her advisers. He also has denounced
statements by Louis Farrakhan as anti-Semitic.
   In a display of independence, he supported Jesse Jackson's 1984
presidential bid when other black leaders backed Walter Mondale.
Jackson returned the favor by coming to New York twice to campaign
for Dinkins.
   Dinkins has been haunted by the four years _ 1968-71 _ when he
neglected to pay his state income taxes. The slip was revealed in
1973 and cost him a deputy mayor's post. Dinkins paid $15,000 in
back taxes and admitted his negligence.
   He brushes off questions about that now, saying it was an
oversight that he rectified.
   Of average height and with a slight paunch, Dinkins exudes
confidence and carries himself in a reserved and dignified manner.
He's an avid tennis player with a mean forehand, even though he's a
grandfather.
   ``I've been described as a nice guy, as a gentleman,'' Dinkins
said last February. ``But I'm also an ex-Marine. And I don't intend
for a second to get shoved around in this or any other campaign.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
