<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a brief look at the major elections held around the
nation Tuesday:
   U.S. HOUSE
   _ Texas: Democrat Pete Geren edged Republican Bob Lanier in a
special election for the 12th District seat vacated by former House
Speaker Jim Wright.
   _ California: Democrat Gary Condit whipped Republican Clare
Berryhill and six other candidates vying for the 15th District seat
left vacant by Rep. Tony Coelho, the former House Democratic whip.
   MAYORS
   _ New York: Mayor Edward Koch lost to Manhattan Borough President
David Dinkins in a four-way Democratic primary. Former federal
prosecutor Rudolph Giuliani swamped cosmetics heir Ronald Lauder for
the GOP nomination.
   _ Detroit: Mayor Coleman Young topped a field of 13 candidates in
his bid for a record fifth term. Accountant Tom Barrow grabbed the
second spot for a November runoff.
   _ St. Paul, Minn.: City Council President Jim Scheibel led a
nine-way non-partisan race to succeed Mayor George Latimer, who is
retiring. A runoff between Scheibel and former City Councilman Bob
Fletcher will be held Nov. 7.
   _ Minneapolis: Mayor Don Fraser dominated a field of seven
candidates in a non-partisan primary. He faces his leading
challenger, firefighter Jens Peterson, on Nov. 7.
   _ Buffalo, N.Y.: Mayor James Griffin defeated two challengers in
the Democratic primary. He also ran unopposed for the Republican,
Conservative and Right to Life party nominations.
   _ New Haven, Conn.: State Sen. John Daniels defeated John
DeStefano Jr., for the Democratic nomination for the seat of
retiring Mayor Biagio DiLieto.
   _ Toledo, Ohio: Democrat John McHugh easily defeated Republican
Mayor Donna Owens and a write-in candidate in a non-partisan
primary. McHugh faces Owens in a November runoff.
   _ Yonkers, N.Y.: Mayor Nicholas Wasicsko decisively won the
Democratic primary over former City Councilman Dominick Iannacone.
Wasicsko faces Democrat-turned-Republican, Vice Mayor Henry
Spallone, in the November general election.
