<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell against major currencies in light
European trading early today ahead of the release of economic
figures due later in the week. Gold prices rose.
   Dealers said the dollar was driven lower by technical factors in
the absence of news, then stabilized in late-morning trading.
   U.S. retail trade figures for August were due to be released
Thursday. Trade figures for July were due Friday, as well as
producer prices and industrial production for August.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell to a closing 146.70 Japanese yen from 146.73 yen at
Tuesday's close. Later, in London, it edged back up to 146.75 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Tuesday:
   _1.9807 West German marks, down from 1.9880
   _1.7085 Swiss francs, down from 1.7160
   _6.6718 French francs, down from 6.6950
   _2.2312 Dutch guilders, down from 2.2330
   _1,418.25 Italian lire, down from 1,421.75
   _1.1853 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1892
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.5526 from $1.5470 late
Tuesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $358.90 a troy ounce, up
from $358.75 bid late Tuesday. At midmorning, the city's five major
bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $358.80.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $358.90, up from $358.55 bid late
Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold closed at a bid $359.93, unchanged
from Tuesday's closing bid price.
   Silver edged up in London to a bid price of $5.09 a troy ounce
from $5.08 bid late Tuesday.
</TEXT>
