<FIRST>r p PM-NewHavenPrimary     09-13 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-New Haven Primary,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Senator Becomes First Black To Win Democratic Primary</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Primary Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Veteran state Sen. John C. Daniels
defeated a candidate backed by Democratic leaders to become the
party's first black nominee for mayor in this overwhelmingly
Democratic city.
   ``As I campaigned throughout the city, people said it was time
for change,'' Daniels said in claiming victory Tuesday night.
   Unofficial returns showed Daniels capturing 16,012 votes to
11,082 for John DeStefano, a former top official of retiring Mayor
Biagio DiLieto. DeStefano won the Democratic Town Committee's
endorsement and gained automatic entry in the primary with the
support of DiLieto.
   Turnout Tuesday was the highest in 10 years, with 53 percent of
the city's registered Democrats going to the polls.
   Because Democrats outnumber Republicans by almost 10-to-1 in this
city, the winner of the Democratic primary is widely expected to win
the Nov. 7 general election.
   The 53-year-old senator will face Alderwoman Robie Pooley, 48.
She defeated attorney Tobin Hitt, a political newcomer, by 1,227 to
728, according to unofficial Republican returns.
   Republicans have not held office in New Haven for 36 years. The
last GOP primary was 31 years ago.
   DeStefano, 34, urged all Democrats to unite behind Daniels.
   ``You know it isn't all bad,'' he told his supporters. ``I came
out of this with a better haircut and a better sense of humor.''
   Both Daniels and DeStefano had sought to keep the issue of race
out of the campaign, and both sought multi-racial, multi-ethnic
support. Blacks represent about 35 percent and Hispanics about 12
percent of the city's 127,000 population.
   Nevertheless, Daniels had described himself as the candidate who
could best bring the city's diverse neighborhoods together.
   A 5-term senator who owns a plumbing business, Daniels once
entered the 1969 mayoral race before withdrawing after several
weeks. He said he finally became a candidate two decades later after
polls showed a minority candidate could win.
   DiLieto's withdrawal made this primary the first in 20 years in
which the incumbent was not seeking re-election.
</TEXT>
