<DOCNO> AP890913-0091 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 0914EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CardboardCremations     09-13 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cardboard Cremations,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>Funeral Home Accused of Cremating Bodies in Cardboard</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA MYERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A funeral home has agreed to pay up to $14,200
to settle charges of cremating bodies in cardboard boxes instead of
the wooden caskets bought by grieving families.
   The agreement between the Federal Trade Commission and the former
Eddy's Funeral Home in Winnemucca was filed in federal court on
Tuesday.
   ``This case was just your garden variety one of fraud,'' FTC
attorney Nora Dowd said. ``It is very unusual, though, to sell
someone a casket and say you're going to cremate a body in it and
then use a cardboard box.''
   The funeral home was accused of violating federal regulations by
misleading customers, charging people for goods and services not
provided and not giving them written lists of proposed charges.
   Under a consent decree, the former operators of Eddy's must pay
the government $10,000 in civil fines, one tenth the amount the
funeral home was facing. They also must contact at least 24 people
who might have paid for a wooden casket that never was used in
cremations in 1986, 1987 and 1988, and refund them $175 each.
   The former operators did not admit any wrongdoing under the
consent degree.
   The mortuary has been sold by GMJB of Boise, Idaho, and its name
has been changed. Ms. Dowd wouldn't say what led to the allegations,
but ``usually, information like this comes from consumers, or
workers in the funeral homes and sometimes the competition.''
   Scott Gilligan, a lawyer for GMJB managing partner James
McMurtrey, said the mortuary's former director, Alan Olsen, denied
the allegations.
   ``The funeral home had already been closed by the time the FTC
complained and so we were stuck in a position of not being able to
defend ourselves very well,'' Gilligan said. ``And, frankly, because
the funeral home was closed we didn't have a reputation to protect
anymore so it was easier to settle the case.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890913-0092 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 0925EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-FacultyShortage     09-13 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Faculty Shortage,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study: Colleges Face Faculty Shortages if Steps Not Taken</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRINCETON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American colleges and universities will
face a shortage of more than 6,000 teachers by the end of the
century if steps are not taken soon, a study says.
   Through 1992, there will be 1.6 candidates available for each
available teaching position, according to the study being published
by Princeton University Press. But by 1997-2002, the study found,
the candidates-to-job ratio will drop to 0.83, with 30,934
candidates to fill an estimated 37,091 positions.
   The greatest shortages will be not in the sciences as previously
believed but in the humanities and social sciences, the study found.
   ``We need to increase overall production of new Ph.D.'s by
two-thirds,'' said William G. Bowen, co-author of the report and
president of the Andrew W. Mellon Foundation. ``In the humanities
and social sciences, we need to double the current numbers.''
   The study by Bowen, a former Princeton president, and Julie Ann
Sosa, a Princeton graduate now studying at Oxford University, was
believed to be the first statistical confirmation of an impending
faculty shortage.
   Faculty retirements will contribute little to the shortage, the
study found, but many new faculty jobs will open to accommodate the
bulge of students now moving through elementary schools. They will
enter college starting in 1997.
   Restoring the candidates-to-job ratio to an ideal 1.3 level would
require a 64 percent increase in new doctorates overall and a 92
percent increase in the humanities and social sciences, the study
estimated.
   From 1997-2002, the study estimated, the ratio would be 0.71 in
the humanities and social sciences, 0.80 in mathematics and the
physical sciences, and 1.13 in the biological sciences and
psychology.
   Bowen said the statistics were projections, not predictions.
   ``Enlightened policies can be adopted to increase the pipeline so
that the shortages we envision do not come to pass,'' he said.
   Bowen suggested universities shorten the time required to obtain
a Ph.D. and increase the number of fellowships and the amount they
pay. It now takes about seven years to earn a Ph.D in mathematics
and more than 12 years in the humanities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890913-0093 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 0930EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Hungary-Refugees     09-13 0622</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hungary-Refugees,0642</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hungarian Diplomat: New Hungary Will Keep Borders Open</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Refugees, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX BANDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungary has a new foreign policy that
calls for a bigger role in the world arena, and it takes precedence
over old commitments to the Warsaw Pact, a top Hungarian diplomat
said today.
   Ferenc Somogyi, the No. 2 official in the Foreign Ministry, said
Hungary will keep open its borders to the West.
   Hungary, which has been tacitly allowing East Germans vacationing
in that country to escape into West Germany, on Sunday allowed an
organized exodus of more than 12,000 East Germans to begin pouring
into the West.
   ``The Hungarian government's policy of opening the country's
borders will continue,'' he told The Associated Press.
   He said that as long as there is a third country willing to
accept refugees from other East bloc countries, Hunary will allow
them to leave.
   However, the foreign ministry official emphasized that the
current special measures announced Sunday whereby East Germans
seeking to emigrate to the West may cross legally into Austria was a
``unique step'' that applied only to East German citizens.
   ``The East Germans were not treated as refugees, and they did not
request asylum as refugees,'' Somogyi said.
   East Germans are automatically considered citizens of West
Germany and therefore technically do not qualify as refugees.
   The Hungarian decision to allow East Germans to pass the border
to Austria was made after weeks of negotiations with the East Berlin
leadership proved unsuccesful in finding a solution for the
thousands of East Germans in Hungary who refused to return home.
   Budapest suspended a 1969 agreement with East Germany to allow
the exodus.
   The official made a distinction between the country's refugee
policy and the special measures in force for East Germans.
   Hungary in May became the first Soviet bloc country to literally
begin dismantling the barbed wire fencing and technical barriers
along its western border with Austria, saying they had become
obsolete.
   Somogyi said the country's open-border policy applied to these
measures and Hungary's status as a signatory of the U.N. Convention
on Refugees _ the only East bloc country to have signed it.
   ``There are agreements with other Warsaw Treaty countries similar
to the one Hungary just suspended with East Germany, and these
agreements are no longer in line with Hungary's newly assumed
international responsibilities, such as our having signed the Geneva
Convention,'' Somogyi said.
   ``We are working to bring these various agreements into harmony
with (our) new foreign policy,'' he added.
   As part of major reforms that include free elections planned by
June, the Communist government is drawing up laws giving Hungarian
citizens the right to emigrate freely after more than 40 years of
restrictions.
   Last year, Hungary began accepting refugees from allied Romania,
an unprecedented step in inter-East bloc relations.
   ``Anyone from any European country may apply for refugee status
from the Hungarian authorities,'' Somogyi said.
   ``If the conditions stipulated in the Geneva Convention are met,
then the applicant would receive refugee status. If there is a third
country agreeing to take in that person, there would be no obstacle
raised by Hungary,'' he said.
   Dozens of Romanians have attempted to cross from Hungary into
Austria but have been turned back at the border by Austrian
authorities.
   Somogyi said it was still not decided how long the borders would
remain open for the East Germans. However, he recalled that the
government announcement on the move stipulated that they would
remain open ``as long as there is a country prepared to receive them
or to allow transit.''
   So far, more than 12,000 mostly skilled, young East Germans have
crossed into Austria and the majority have already arrived in West
Germany.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
