<FIRST>r i PM-Czechoslovakia-Refugees     09-13 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Czechoslovakia-Refugees,0313</SECOND>
<HEAD>More East Germans Leave Embassy After Negotiations</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Refugees, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Forty East Germans left the West
German Embassy today, abandoning their push for freedom in the West
after East Germany said they will not be prosecuted if they return
home.
   On Tuesday, more than 200 others accepted the East German offer,
and the possibility of applying for legal emigration later, and left
the embassy.
   Many of the East Germans had camped out for days or weeks in
hopes of being granted free passage to the West like thousands of
their countrymen in Hungary, who were allowed to flee into West
Germany this week.
   About 150 East Germans remained on the embassy grounds today,
apparently refusing to join their countrymen returning home.
   Wolfgang Vogel, an East Berlin lawyer who has mediated bilateral
German affairs, met with the East Germans at the embassy on Tuesday
and again today, to persuade them to return home. Sources close to
the talks said no more negotiations were planned and that Vogel had
left Prague.
   Witnesses said about 40 people left today, several driving off in
their own cars and 23 boarding a bus.
   One 25-year-old woman said while weeping that she was returing
because, ``I just couldn't take anymore.''
   The West German mission in Prague was closed to the public Aug.
23, after about 140 East Germans were reported to have taken refuge
there, in hopes of being allowed to emigrate to West Germany.
   Scores more continued to arrive at the Prague embassy after that
and giant tents were erected on the grounds to house them.
   West German officials said those who left the embassy for home
had done so of their own free will. It was not clear what the rest
of those still on the embassy grounds would decide to do.
</TEXT>
