<FIRST>r a PM-WVaPolitics 1stLd-Writethru a0488 09-13 0696</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-WVa Politics, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0488,0709</SECOND>
<HEAD>W.Va. Residents Fed Up With Dirty Politics, Centralized Government</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf pvs, `Caperton's plan ...' to CLARIFY how state
lost $270 million.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RABY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Resignations by top West Virginia
officials and the defeat of three amendments proposed by the
governor have dented the credibility of the state's political
leaders, insiders and observers said.
   Four politicians have left office in shame this summer and a
former state Senate president is on trial in federal court on
extortion and racketeering charges.
   Gov. Gaston Caperton won election last November with a campaign
to clean the state's sullied image. He pushed for the three
amendments as essential parts of his reform plans, only to see them
trounced on Saturday. Opponents of the amendments had accused him of
a power grab.
   Some analysts said the rejection showed voters are fed up with
their political leaders.
   ``Historically, West Virginia has had a relatively high tolerance
for corruption in government,'' said Joe McCoy, a political science
professor at Marshall University.
   ``But citizens today are fed up with it and are expressing those
feelings to prosecutors and elected officials. The diligence of
these investigations are because of a heightened consciousness.
Residents want change.''
   Caperton's plan to fix the state's image was foiled almost from
the start when an audit late last year found that West Virginia had
bungled its finances and lost more than $270 million in investments.
An investigation led to the impeachment and resignation of Treasurer
A. James Manchin last July.
   Shortly after the headlines on that story faded, Attorney General
Charlie Brown resigned Aug. 21 as part of an agreement to halt a
probe into his campaign finances and reports that he lied under oath
during a child custody hearing.
   Next, state Sen. Si Boettner resigned after pleading guilty Aug.
30 to income tax evasion. Then, Senate President Larry Tucker
resigned Thursday after agreeing to plead guilty to extortion
charges.
   And last week, former state Senate President Dan Tonkovich went
on trial on extortion and racketeering charges in what prosecutors
say was a deal to influence legislation in return for money.
   In the wake of those scandals, Caperton suffered his first major
setback.
   By a landslide, voters defeated amendments that would have
eliminated three state offices and put their duties under the
governor's control, given the governor greater authority over
education and allowed cities and counties to reorganize.
   ``One of the principles of politics of a new governor is never to
load the voters up with too long an agenda, so that they can digest
it,'' said David Bingham, a political science professor at West
Virginia University.
   Earlier this year, Caperton raised taxes by nearly $400 million
and the Legislature borrowed $135 million to begin paying off a debt
estimated at $300 million to $400 million.
   Since taking office in January, Caperton also has reorganized 150
departments under seven ``super secretaries,'' divided the Board of
Regents into separate entities and created an Ethics Commission to
study conflicts of interest in state and local government.
   Caperton blamed the defeat of his proposed amendments on bad
public relations. But House Speaker Chuck Chambers, a Democrat like
the governor, said the results amounted to a referendum on
Caperton's performance and showed voters were unhappy about the tax
increase.
   Bingham agreed. ``The voters are mad about the taxes and somewhat
mad about the reorganization,'' he said.
   In recent surveys, residents named unemployment and taxes as the
state's most pressing problems. Seventy percent of residents in an
August survey felt Caperton was doing a fair or poor job.
   The Senate turned over a new leaf on Tuesday in electing Keith
Burdette as president to replace Tucker. Burdette, at 34 the
youngest person to hold the job, said his top priority is restoring
credibility to state government.
   ``The job's got to be done. We've got to pick up and go on,''
said Burdette. ``There's no question, we're an institution in
crisis. But you have to believe that the overwhelming majority of
the members of this Legislature are good people who don't have their
hands in somebody else's pocket.''
 
</TEXT>
</DOC>
