<FIRST>r a PM-BoeingFine     09-13 0124</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boeing Fine,0127</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boeing Pays $200,000 Fine Over Miswiring</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boeing Commercial Airplanes has paid the Federal
Aviation Administration $200,000 to settle charges of failing to
promptly report wiring defects on new jets.
   ``It is the largest fine ever paid at one time by an (airplane)
manufacturer,'' said FAA spokesman Dave Duff.
   Boeing paid the fine Thursday and the settlement was made public
Tuesday. Under the settlement, Boeing did not admit to any
wrongdoing. It also agreed to report safety defects ``in a timely
manner.''
   The settlement involved miswiring of fire extinguishers in 94
planes and FAA allegations that Boeing had failed to adequately
report such cases. Boeing said the fire protection systems have been
redesigned and never failed in service.
</TEXT>
