<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 1103EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Israel     09-13 0554</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel,0573</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israeli Leaders Discuss Egyptian Plan, Cairo Meeting Rejected</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's four top leaders today discussed an
Egyptian plan calling on Israel to trade occupied lands for peace.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's senior aide, however, dismissed
the plan and suggestions for Israeli-Palestinian peace talks in
Cairo.
   Also today, a car belonging to U.S. Deputy Counselor David Winn
was set ablaze in front of his house in annexed east Jerusalem.
Police said the car was severely damaged, and blamed Palestinian
``nationalists.''
   In the occupied Gaza Strip, masked Arabs stabbed to death a
Palestinian suspected of collaborating with Israel officials,
Palestinian reports said.
   The death of 35-year-old Jibara Abu Taha brings the toll to at
least 114 Palestinians killed as alleged collaborators during the
21-month-old revolt against Israeli rule. During the uprising, 567
Palestinians have been shot in clashes with the Israeli army or
civilians, and 40 Israelis have been killed.
   In Jerusalem, three dailies quoted American and Israeli sources
as saying Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, in coordination with the
United States, soon will issue invitations for a peace meeting in
Cairo.
   It would include a Palestinian delegation from the occupied lands
and an Israeli delegation, Haaretz and Davar newspapers said.
American and Soviet officials also would be invited, the
English-language Jerusalem Post said.
   Davar reported the proposal was discussed last week by U.S.
Secretary of State James A. Baker III and Israel's Defense Minister
Yitzhak Rabin.
   Davar and Haaretz said the Palestinian delegation would adopt
Mubarak's 10-point peace proposal, while Israel would adhere to its
plan for elections in the occupied lands for negotiators of an
interim settlement with Israel.
   Shamir's office director, Yossi Ben-Aharon, rejected the Egyptian
plan, telling Haaretz the Palestinians must adopt Israel's plan
before any talks.
   Shamir, Foreign Minister Moshe Arens, Finance Minister Shimon
Peres and Rabin today discussed the Egyptian plan, but spokesmen
declined to provide details of the talks.
   Israel radio reported Shamir refused to discuss the plan at a
subsequent session of a 12-member inner Cabinet. But it quoted him
as saying he and the other three top leaders Friday will formulate a
stance on the Egyptian plan.
   Of the four leaders, only Peres has supported the Egyptian plan
calling for talks based on the U.S.-backed principle of trading land
for peace and giving voting rights to 140,000 east Jerusalem Arabs.
   Shamir's right-wing Likud bloc opposes territorial concessions
and says giving east Jerusalem Arabs a vote would undermine the
unity of Jerusalem as Israel's capital. Peres' left-leaning Labor
Party accepts both ideas.
   Abba Eban, a senior Labor politician and former foreign minister,
today urged the government to adopt Egypt's proposal.
   ``It would be quite irresponsible to reject the Egyptian peace
initiative. We must understand that Israel's proposal has reached
the deadest of dead ends,'' Eban told Israel radio after returning
home Tuesday night from a meeting with Egyptian officials in Cairo.
   Palestine Liberation Organization chairman Yasser Arafat has not
commented on the plan. But one of his main backers, Nablus
businessman Saeed Kenaan, said he favored it. ``It has good points
and I think it can be used as a starting point,'' Kenaan said in an
interview.
   Two radical Marxist PLO factions at odds with Arafat's mainstream
Fatah announced in Syria that they oppose the Egyptian plan.
</TEXT>
