<FIRST>u i PM-Colombia 2ndLd-Writethru a0559 09-13 0571</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Colombia, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0559,0582</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gunmen Attack Judge's Home in Medellin; Huge Weapons Cache Seized</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with army confirming weapons seizure.
Pickup 10th graf pvs, `The reinforcements...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANA HAYWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen attacked a judge's home in the
cocaine center of Medellin, but police guards drove them off,
authorities said today. Troops found caches of grenades and assault
rifles near Bogota.
   One policeman was wounded in the assault Tuesday night on the
house of the federal Judge Laurentino Gallego Gil, a Medellin police
spokesman. The source, who asked not to be named for security
reasons, said in a telephone interview that two police guards
repulsed the attack.
   The assault followed the deployment of more than 500 soldiers and
police Tuesday in Antioquia state, of which Medellin is the capital.
They will bolster the more than 4,000 security force members already
in the northwest region, where drug gangs stage daily bombings,
shootings and arson attacks.
   Hundreds of mourners on Tuesday attended the funeral of former
Medellin Mayor Pablo Pelaez Gonzalez, who tried to rid the city of
drug traffickers. Pelaez was assassinated on his way to work Monday.
   In an army raid on Tuesday just north of Bogota, authorities
found seven Israeli Galil automatic rifles, nine U.S. R-15
semi-utomatic rifles, two Chinese automatic rifles, one Belgian
assault rifle and a British machine gun, said Col. Eduardo Arevalo,
the Defense Ministry spokesman.
   The reliable and well-informed Bogota newspaper El Espectador,
bombed earlier in the month by drug terrorists, said the arms
belonged to Gonzalo Rodriguez Gacha, the reputed No. 2 man in the
Medellin cocaine cartel. Arevalo would not confirm that.
   The newspaper, which printed a picture of the captured rifles,
said the weapons cache also contained grenades, pistols, ammunition
and scanner radios for monitoring police and army frequencies.
Arevalo would not confirm that.
   The reinforcements to the Medellin region were believed to be
part of measures adopted by government to combat the traffickers.
The government declared an unprecendented crackdown on the
traffickers after the Aug. 18 assassination of a leading
presidential candidate, Sen. Luis Carlos Galan.
   Gen. Oscar Botero, the minister of defense, said in announcing
the dispatch of reinforcements to the Medellin area that the
government will sign emergency decrees that will allow sending army
advisers to cities overrun by drug lords.
   Medellin, the country's second-largest city with 2 million
people, is already under a nighttime curfew. Hooded gangs on
motorcycles have been throwing firebombs at government vehicles in
the city and bombings and bomb threats are almost daily occurrences.
   President Virgilio Barco has ordered raids on hundreds of estates
and ranches said to belong to drug dealers and confiscated their
airplanes, helicopters, limousines, satellite dishes, cattle and
exotic pet birds.
   Hundreds of purported traffickers were rounded up, but the top
leaders of the drug cartels escaped and remain at large.
   The cartels supply 80 percent of the cocaine sold in the United
States.
   Authorities say the highest-ranking cartel member seized is
economist Eduardo Martinez Romero, who is accused of laundering more
than $1 billion for the Medellin cartel. He was extradited last week
to Atlanta and pleaded innocent to the charges in federal court.
   Barco has promised to keep extraditing traffickers wanted in the
United States, but no further extraditions have taken place since
Martinez was flown out of Colombia by U.S. drug enforcement agents.
</TEXT>
