<FIRST>r a PM-SalesmanLibel     09-13 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salesman Libel,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-Salesman Wins $26 Million Against Insurance Giant Hancock</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury awarded $26.1 million to a
former insurance salesman who claimed he was badmouthed by his
employer and fired for saving his customers money.
   The jury agreed with Clifford Zalay that John Hancock Mutual Life
Insurance Co. and one of its general agents libeled and slandered
him.
   Zalay, who was fired in 1979, wept after Tuesday's verdict. ``I
took the position that I don't care how big they are and who they
are, I'm going to fight to regain my integrity _ my good name,'' he
said.
   The Boston-based insurance company, which has nearly $30 billion
in assets, is expected to appeal.
   Zalay, 65, ranked among the top 2 percent in sales when he fell
out of favor with the company. He claimed the company badmouthed him
to clients and made it difficult for him to earn a living.
   He charged his former boss sent a policyholder a copy of a letter
of reprimand accusing Zalay of giving that policyholder erroneous
advice. The former boss, Edward Dooley, also sent copies to the home
office in Boston.
   Zalay's attorney, Elihu Berman, said Zalay never gave the
policyholder any advice.
   Zalay also charged that the company sent investigators who told
his clients he was giving bad advice. He said investigators told
policyholders he was under investigation for ``shady dealings,''
accusations that could not be substantiated.
   Zalay maintained the company wanted him out because he urged
clients to buy new insurance by piggy-backing _ using the dividends
or cash value of their policies to buy more insurance. Zalay said
company officials were upset because they were assuming greater risk
without collecting more money.
   Lawyers for Dooley and John Hancock argued that Zalay was a
difficult, abrasive employee who tried to steal clients from other
agents and threw temper-tantrums in the office.
   The jury award included $25.05 million in punitive damages.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
