<FIRST>u w PM-Bush 2ndLd-Writethru a0574 09-13 0815</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0574,770</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teen-Ager Lashes President on Support for Capital Punishment</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs pvs 10th graf, The president, to spell out DARE, and grafs
14-15, Bush also, with 3 grafs to update with meetings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush shone the White House spotlight
today on a school program that teaches youngsters to resist drugs,
and wound up hearing a tough lecture from a 13-year-old against the
death penalty he favors.
   Chantee Charles of nearby Arlington, Va., one of three youngsters
invited to speak at a Rose Garden ceremony, appeared to take the
president aback with her musings on capital punishment, which she
called murder.
   ``It does not solve anything. ... The guard that turns on the
switch to electrocute the prisoner is just as much a murderer as the
person who has commited the crime,'' the seventh-grader said.
   She added that the executioner ``must feel guilty afterwards, but
I guess they get paid for it.''
   Chantee claimed that ``probably thousands'' of innocent prisoners
have been executed, and argued that death penalty proponents ``miss
the point that the prisoner has a family, too.''
   She told reporters afterwards she did not know of the president's
stance in favor of the death penalty.
   After hearing two other young people talk about the need to
resist peer pressure to use drugs, Bush, who favors the death
penalty for cop-killers and drug kingpins, said, ``My turn.''
   But instead of rebutting Chantee, the president thanked all three
youths and said:
   ``It's not easy to get up in front of a big scary audience like
this and do such a good job, say what's on your heart, not worry if
people agree with you or not, but recognizing that there's a common
theme here that you all did a beautiful job on, and that is turning
your back on drugs.''
   The president then launched into a pitch for the $7.9 billion
anti-drug strategy he announced Sept. 5 and has trumpeted daily in
speeches and ceremonies such as the one today that honored the Los
Angeles-based Drug Abuse Resistance Education, or DARE, program.
   Bush recalled that he attended a class last year where a Los
Angeles police officer was teaching the DARE curriculum and ``I know
it works.''
   DARE has spread from its start in 50 Los Angeles classrooms in
1983 to more than 50,000 classrooms across the United States and
abroad, he said.
   ``These kids have dared to excel, and they are succeeding. ... ''
the president said. ``So far so good, and yet so far to go.... Let
us finish the job DARE has started and create an America we can all
be proud of an America free of drugs.''
   Bush also conferred with leaders of more than a dozen major
education groups, including Keith Geiger of the National Education
Association and Albert Shanker of the American Federation of
Teachers. That meeting came two weeks before the president's Sept.
27-28 education summit with the nation's governors in
Charlottesville, Va.
   Former Democratic presidential contender Jesse Jackson also
visited the White House today to confer with Bush's chief of staff,
John Sununu, on the drug strategy.
   Later, Bush was presiding at another White House event to push
for passage of legislation to help spur adoptions of children born
with disabilities and other special needs.
   On Tuesday the president played principal with a televised
address from his library beamed into schoolhouses across the nation
appealing to youths to resist the overtures of drug peddlers.
   ``I'm asking you not to look the other way,'' said the president
in an address that combined avuncular persuasion with grim warnings
of the consequences of drugs.
   ``Even dabblers in drugs bear responsibility for the blood being
spilled'' in drug warfare across America and in Colombia, Bush said.
Young people risk losing their driver's licenses, their futures and
even their lives from drugs, he warned.
   And in words his audience was sure to understand, he insisted,
``Saying `no' won't make you a nerd. It won't make you a loser.''
   Meanwhile, administration officials and Democrats were
skirmishing over how to fund the proposed $7.9 billion battle
against drugs.
   Bush wants to cut other domestic programs to find the extra $717
million needed for his strategy in fiscal 1990.
   White House spokeswoman Alixe Glen said the administration would
``reluctantly support'' a bipartisan plan approved by a Senate
Appropriations subcommittee that would cut 0.225 percent from
defense and many domestic programs to raise $1.8 billion for the war
on drugs.
   She said administration officials were continuing to meet with
leaders of Congress to search for a compromise.
   But White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater accused Democrats of
playing ``price-tag politics'' with the drug plan after Senate
Appropriations Chairman Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., proposed boosting the
drug package to $10.1 billion and financing it by an
across-the-board 0.575 percent cut in military and other
discretionary programs.
</TEXT>
