<FIRST>r w PM-FlagBurning 1stLd-Writethru a0458 09-13 0767</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Flag Burning, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0458,730</SECOND>
<HEAD>Veterans Groups Split Over Flag Statute, Amendment</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 8 grafs new with today's testimony; picks up at pvs 3rd
graf, Rep. Steny</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senators weighing the options of a regular bill
or a constitutional amendment to ban flag burning heard today that
veterans groups aren't united on the issue.
   The American Legion and the Veterans of Foreign Wars told the
Senate Judiciary Committee they supported President Bush's position
that a constitutional amendment was the only way to overcome the
Supreme Court ruling that made flag burning a legally protected form
of expression.
   The testimony came a day after the House sent the flag issue back
to the Senate by approving its bill outlawing flag burning by a
380-38 margin.
   ``We believe the only ironclad way to protect our flag is through
a constitutional amendment,'' said Walter G. Hogan, the VFW's
commander-in-chief. Whether any regular statute could pass muster
with the court was doubtful, he said.
   Leaders of the Vietnam Veterans of America and the Paralyzed
Veterans of America said, however, they thought a statute could be
tried first, before tinkering with the Constitution.
   ``Our members share the `fury factor' with other Americans on
this subject, but they are unprepared to sacrifice free speech in
the process of assuring that flag desecration is properly
punished,'' said Mary R. Stout, national president of the Vietnam
veterans group.
   Democrats after Tuesday's House vote that passage of the statute
might weaken the push for a similar constitutional amendment, but
Bush and others vowed to fight for their politically more strident
approach.
   ``I think there are probably enough members now that will vote
against a constitutional amendment that they won't be able to get
the two-thirds required by the Constitution to pass one,'' said Rep.
Mike Synar, D-Okla.
   Rep. Steny Hoyer, D-Md., chairman of the House Democratic Caucus,
said a constitutional amendment is not necessary to many citizens
and lawmakers who want to protect the flag.
   ``If a statute will do it, fine,'' he said.
   However, Bush and Republican leaders on Capitol Hill contend that
a law cannot overcome the Supreme Court's 5-4 ruling in June that
burning the flag is a form of free speech protected by the
Constitution.
   Many Democrats say a constitutional amendment would tinker
dangerously with the Bill of Rights.
   Judiciary Committee Chairman Jack Brooks, D-Texas, predicted the
new version would be approved by the court because it would outlaw
the act of flag-mutilation and not the intent of the offender.
   Republicans, however, say courts would quickly strike it down
again.
   ``We believe that this bill is insufficient to provide the
protections that we seek, and therefore continue to press for a
constitutional amendment,'' said White House spokesman Marlin
Fitzwater.
   ``This bill is flatly unconstitutional,'' said Rep. James
Sensenbrenner, R-Wis. ``So all passing this bill has done is delay a
vote on a constitutional amendment to protect the flag from
burning,'' he said, acknowledging he was disappointed that only 21
Republicans joined him in voting against it.
   Rep. Chuck Douglas, R-N.H., complained that the Democratic bill
was a sham. ``This is the flag-burner protection act of 1989,'' he
said.
   The bill sets penalties of up to a year in jail plus a fine for
anyone who knowingly mutilates, defaces, burns, or tramples upon a
U.S. flag. It makes an exception for orderly disposal of worn-out
flags, which is usually carried out by veterans groups by burning.
   The legislation, sent to the Senate, also sets a procedure for
expedited court review of its constitutionality the next time a
federal flag-burning case comes along.
   But the Capitol Hill showdown on the constitutional amendment
probably will come before the statute, if enacted, is ever tested.
   To help gain Republican votes for the statute, House Speaker
Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., promised supporters of the constitutional
amendment the House will vote on the proposed amendment after the
Senate acts in October.
   Foley denied that scheduling a vote on the amendment _ a vote
which it appeared earlier he intended to block _ was an
acknowledgement that the Democratic strategy was losing.
   ``It might be taken exactly the opposite way,'' he said, as
``confidence (in) a vote to reject a constitutional amendment.''
   Foley said the House Democratic leadership still believes a
constitutional amendment is unnecessary and such action should be
avoided ``particularly in the sensitive area of the First
Amendment.''
   Bush's presidential campaign included a stop at a flag factory,
and GOP leaders consider the flag burning question a ``wedge issue''
which helps break apart Democratic electoral strength.
</TEXT>
