<FIRST>r a PM-Dukakis-Mortgages     09-13 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dukakis-Mortgages,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dukakis Announces Plan to Combat Mortgage Discrimination</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Michael S. Dukakis outlined a plan today to
fight discrimination in mortgage lending, including stricter
enforcement.
   The plan followed a report by the Federal Reserve Bank of Boston
last month that documented racial patterns in lending.
   ``The Federal Reserve Bank study should be the concern of every
fair-minded citizen of Massachusetts,'' Dukakis said. ``The steps
I'm announcing today will help guarantee that credit in the
commonwealth is color blind.''
   The immediate steps announced by Dukakis will target
state-chartered banks in Boston and other urban areas for tougher
evaluation of their compliance with a federal and state statute that
requires banks to meet local credit needs.
   It will also link compliance with the statute, the Community
Reinvestment Act, to all bank applications requiring the state
Banking Division's approval.
   Next week, Dukakis said, he will ask the Legislature to
strengthen the power of state regulators to guard against
discrimination in mortgage lending.
   Among other things, the governor's proposals would mandate
participation by all lenders in a review board process that resolves
disputes over the denial of mortgages, and would add people from
outside the industry to each board. Currently, participation by
lenders is voluntary.
   The legislative package would also place mortgage companies,
brokers and all parties making five or more mortgage loans a year
under the specific licensing and examination powers of the state
division of banks.
   The legislation would also open community-reinvestment
evaluations to the public. Currently, the law requires them to be
kept confidential.
   The Federal Reserve report found that that Boston's black
neighborhoods received 24 percent fewer home loans than white
neighborhoods.
</TEXT>
