<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 1209EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-WaterBill     09-13 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Water Bill,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>House OKs Nuclear Cleanup in Energy and Water Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House has approved a compromise $18.6
billion spending bill that includes $1.65 billion for cleanup of
environmental damage at Energy Department nuclear weapons plants.
   The 392-27 vote Tuesday represented the House's acceptance of a
compromise energy and water plan that had been agreed to by
congressional negotiators earlier this month.
   The $1.65 billion for cleanup work at the nuclear weapons
facilities is earmarked for the budget year starting Oct. 1. Final
approval by the Senate is necessary before the overall bill goes to
the White House for President Bush's signature.
   Among the funds appropriated for waste cleanup was $27.6 million
to bring the Hanford nuclear reservation, near Richland, Wash., into
compliance with environmental standards, and $29.1 million for a
Hanford ``vitrification'' facility that is designed to treat
radioactive waste by turning it into a glass-like substance.
   The measure also provides $55 million for environmental, health
and safety improvements at the Feed Materials Production Center,
near Fernald, Ohio, which processes uranium for the weapons program
and has been tied to extensive environmental damage.
   An additional $26.7 million was appropriated for unspecified
environmental and safety improvements at other plants.
   Among other energy projects to be financed in the coming budget
year is a modification to the plutonium recovery facility, known as
Building 371, at the Rocky Flats weapons plant near Denver. The bill
appropriates $45 million for that work.
   Another provision of the bill earmarks $225 million for the
superconducting super collider, a massive physics installation at
which scientists plan to explore the nature of matter and energy.
The facility, expected to cost $5.9 billion, is to be built in Ellis
County, Texas.
   The Bush administration had requested $250 million for the
project for 1990, but Congress reduced the construction funds from
$160 million to $135 million while meeting the administration's
requests for operating expenses and capital equipment.
</TEXT>
