<FIRST>u w PM-Bush-Communists 1stLd-Writethru a0466 09-13 0782</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Communists, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0466,740</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Bush Cautious in Dealings With Communists</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 6 grafs with Fitzwater comment after 9th graf, The White;
picks up at pvs 10th graf, Bush also</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's dealings with the changing
communist world so far reflect a calculated caution, and his
non-meeting meeting with Soviet maverick Boris Yeltsin fits the mold.
   Ever the diplomat, Bush sought to avoid offending Soviet Leader
Mikhail Gorbachev by limiting his contact with the outspoken
Yeltsin, here on a speaking tour of the United States.
   Instead of scheduling a meeting with Yeltsin, well known for his
criticism of Gorbachev's policies, Bush chose instead to ``drop by''
an ongoing meeting at the White House between Yeltsin and Bush's
national security adviser, Brent Scowcroft.
   Furthermore, Bush did it on Tuesday shortly before he was to go
on the air with his televised midday anti-drug speech to U.S.
students.
   That limited the time of Bush's exposure to Yeltsin to about 15
minutes and gave Bush something to talk about with him other than
Gorbachev's shortcomings.
   Thus, the White House was able to put out a statement noting Bush
and Yeltsin agreed ``drugs are major problem that touches on both
American and Soviet societies.''
   Since Yeltsin's objective in coming to Washington was clearly not
to discuss drug policy, the choreographed Bush encounter enabled the
president to wiggle out of getting involved in domestic Soviet
politics.
   The U.S. statement noted tersely that Bush told Yeltsin
U.S.-Soviet relations are ``in good shape,'' that Americans back
reforms in the Soviet Union, and that the White House continues to
enjoy ``a very positive relationship'' with Gorbachev.
   The White House did not allow reporters or photographers to
attend the Bush-Yeltsin session in a further effort to reduce it to
a non-event.
   Today, presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater characterize the
discussion as ``very general and philosophical.''
   Asked about Yeltsin's criticism of Gorbachev, Fitzwater said:
``We're sensitive to the progress that's being made'' on the Soviet
president's reform initiatives. ``We don't have any comment on any
speculation on his relative strength.''
   On the decision of communist-led Hungary to open its borders to
allow West Germans to flee to Austria en route to West Germany,
Fitzwater today gave another example of the caution that the
administration has used in dealing with changes in the communist
world.
   ``We want to be supportive, but keep a soft voice,'' the
spokesman said. ``We have been supportive of Hungary's steps to
facilitate the refugees moving from East Germany to West Germany and
other locations.''
   But he indicated the United States did not want to get itself
involved in a policy dispute between Hungary and East Germany on the
matter.
   ``We don't want to speculate on other kinds of consequences. It
might be inflamatory or interpreted as internal meddling,''
Fitzwater said.
   Bush also showed extreme caution and efforts at balance in his
earlier decisions and pronouncements on China, the new government in
Poland and East-West arms negotiations.
   In his response to the bloody Chinese government suppression of
demonstrations in Tiananmen Square last spring, Bush, who served as
U.S. envoy to Beijing in the 1970s, took a cautious middle ground.
   While imposing some sanctions, he stopped short of taking trade
actions he said would hurt the Chinese people; and he sought to keep
the lines of communication open with the government even as he
denounced the bloodshed.
   When a Solidarity activist became Poland's new prime minister
last month, leading the first non-communist government in the Soviet
bloc, the president warmly congratulated the new leader, Tadeusz
Mazowiecki.
   But at the same time, he praised the leader of the old regime,
communist President Wojciech Jaruzelski, for his ``statesmanship''
in cooperating with the new leadership.
   And Bush's response to nuclear-arms negotiations with the
Soviets, particularly on the subject of nuclear warheads in Europe,
was also calculated.
   After a long period of study and delay, the president finally
came forth with a compromise proposal he unveiled at last May's NATO
summit in Brussels _ one that eased a rift among NATO allies.
   Presidential press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said the White
House sought a way to receive Yeltsin that balanced ``the diplomatic
aspects of his visit (with) the political realities of his visit.''
   Fitzwater suggested it would have been hard for Bush to snub the
Soviet visitor.
   After all, the spokesman noted, Gorbachev met in Moscow with Sen.
Alan Cranston, D-Calif., and other members of the opposition
Democratic Party ``so there is some history, or some precedent, for
a meeting like this.''
   Still, Fitzwater said: ``We didn't want to indicate that we were
trying to provide a platform for dissent, as it were.''
</TEXT>
