<FIRST>r a PM-ColoWeather     09-13 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Colo Weather,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snow, Record Cold Stun Denver's Homeless</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A freak snowfall and record cold delighted
winter-wheat farmers, delayed airline passengers and threw Denver's
homeless off guard.
   ``The farmers with the dryland winter wheat are just jumping up
and down because this'll take them through the whole season,'' said
Joe Baskin of the National Weather Service. ``The ground was dry for
planting. This could double production.''
   Denver's 2,600 to 3,200 homeless were unprepared for the 2 inches
of wet snow and high of only 39 degrees Tuesday, and neither were
area shelters. The old record for the lowest high temperature for
the date was 46, set in 1974.
   ``We were definitely unprepared. We didn't have a coat to give
out,'' said Roy Chappell, program director for the Salvation Army's
Shelter.
   The earliest snowfall on record in Denver was Sept. 3, 1961, with
4.2 inches.
   Travelers at Stapleton International Airport experienced average
delays of an hour and 45 minutes because of poor visibility, a
spokesman reported. The heavy snow downed power lines and caused
outages throughout the Denver area.
   Greeley tied the record for its earliest snowfall of the year,
set in 1974, said Glen Cobb, meteorologist at the University of
Northern Colorado.
   Weld County, northeast of Denver, got as much as 3 inches of
snow. Evergreen, in the foothills west of Denver, had six.
Strangely, the high temperature in the state was in the mountain
hamlet of Glenwood Springs, with 71.
   Forecasters said the Arctic cold front would start moving out
slowly today, and temperatures were expected to reach the 70s and
80s by the weekend.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
