<FIRST>u w PM-NixonImpeachment 1stLd-Writethru a0480 09-13 0671</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nixon Impeachment, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0480,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawyer Says Impeached Judge Never Lied</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout with today's proceedings and editing to tighten</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The lawyer for U.S. District Judge Walter Nixon
told a Senate impeachment trial committee today that the perjury
case against the judge is ill-founded because the judge never lied
and had no reason to lie.
   ``He is accused of lying to conceal his innocence,'' defense
attorney David Stewart said in his closing statement to the
12-member committee. ``That makes no sense. It did not happen.''
   The case against Nixon, the imprisoned chief federal judge in
Mississippi's southern district, stems from statements he made to
federal investigators and a grand jury about a marijuana-smuggling
case involving the son of a businessman from whom he purchased
lucrative oil properties.
   Nixon said Tuesday that when he spoke to federal authorities and
the grand jury he did not remember the conversations that have led
to his conviction in federal court on perjury charges.
   Stewart said today that even if Nixon had remembered them and
told federal authorities, the talks were not improper and would not
have led to any charges against the judge.
   He said the trial jury came to the wrong conclusion on the
perjury indictments because it was distracted by an illegal-gratuity
charge that had no basis and on which Nixon was acquitted.
   The articles of impeachment accuse Nixon of lying when he said he
did not discuss or influence the case involving Drew Fairchild, the
50-year-old son of wealthy oilman Wiley Fairchild.
   But Stewart said each of the witnesses that went before the
Senate committee denied that the talks they had with Nixon were
``discussions'' about the case.
   And the key witness, county prosecutor Paul ``Bud'' Holmes,
testified that the conversation he had with Nixon did not influence
how he handled the Drew Fairchild case.
   On Tuesday, Nixon said his conversations March 11, 1983 about the
Drew Fairchild case were ``such a nothing thing in my life'' and
that after they were over he immediately forgot about them.
   ``I had no intention to hide anything. There was nothing to
hide,'' said Nixon. ``It has been blown up so much and magnified. It
amounted to nothing. It resulted in nothing.
   ``Everything had been a misunderstanding ... I guess that's why I
didn't remember it.''
   The judge called it ``one little day in my life involving a few
minutes'' that were overshadowed by his docket of 1,400 active
cases, worries over his wife recovering from oral surgery and the
problems of raising seven children.
   Nixon said the conversations he had were not ``discussions'' of
the Fairchild case, but only talk about Fairchild's fear that he was
being blackmailed by the prosecutor _ Holmes _ handling his son's
case.
   ``The thrust of the whole case is that Judge Nixon does not
recall and that is the reason for the statements that he made for
which he is accused of perjury,'' Sen. Wyche Fowler, D-Ga., chairman
impeachment trial committee, said Tuesday.
   He said the committee would summarize the evidence for the full
Senate which he expects to hear the case sometime in October.
   Nixon, 60, is serving a five-year prison sentence for perjury.
   Appointed by President Lyndon Johnson, he is the lone Democratic
appointee among nine federal district judges in Mississippi, and
will continue to collect his $89,500 annual salary unless he dies,
resigns or is convicted of the impeachment charges voted unanimously
by the House of Representatives.
   The articles of impeachment approved unanimously by the House
allege that Nixon:
   _Lied when he told a grand jury he never discussed the case
against Drew Fairchild with Holmes.
   _Lied when he told a grand jury he had nothing to do officially
or unofficially with the Fairchild case and never influenced anyone
in the case.
   _Undermined ``the integrity of the judiciary'' and disobeyed the
law by making 14 false or misleading statements during an interview
with the federal investigators and in his sworn grand jury testimony.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
