<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--DogDeaths     09-13 0181</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Dog Deaths,0186</SECOND>
<HEAD>English Dogs Die of Suffocation on Ferry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An English firm could be charged with
cruelty to animals after 79 beagles suffocated on a ferry from
England to Sweden, police said Wednesday.
   Passengers appealed to the ship's crew to find out why the dogs
were crying, but nothing was done.
   Bengt Inaeus, a detective in Sodertalje south of Stockholm, said
100 beagles were put in a van on the ferry from Harwich to the
Swedish port of Goteborg on Sept. 6.
   The Swedish pharmaceutical company Astra planned to use the dogs,
obtained from a kennel in England, to test drugs. Inaeus said when a
kennel worker went to check on the dogs after six hours, 79 were
dead.
   Astra spokesman Staffan Tarnby said the dogs suffocated probably
because of a failure in the van's air supply system.
   Neither Inaeus nor Tarnby would identify the kennel or its
English transport firm.
   ``There were other animals on the ferry, and none of them died,''
Inaeus said. ``So we can't blame the general conditions on the
vessel.''
</TEXT>
