<FIRST>r i AM-France-Iran     09-13 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-Iran,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>France to Restart Talks With Iran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   France is sending a senior diplomat to Iran to
resume talks on settling long-standing differences with the Islamic
Republic, the Foreign Ministry announced Wednesday.
   The ministry's secretary-general, Francois Scheer, will go to
Tehran on Monday ``to take up with Iranian authorities discussions
on the differences between the two countries,'' a spokesman said.
   Paris and Tehran have been negotiating the repayment of $1
billion that Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi of Iran loaned to France for
a nuclear project.
   France has repaid $630 million but is demanding compensation for
its losses following the Iranian revolution that resulted in the
shah's ouster in 1979.
   The two countries re-established diplomatic ties in June 1988,
nearly six weeks after France's last three hostages in Lebanon were
freed. Ties were broken at the height of a battle of wills over an
Iranian Embassy employee wanted for questioning about terrorist
attacks in Paris.
   Iran also has claimed the former conservative government of
Premier Jacques Chirac promised to free Anis Naccache, the head of a
commando team serving a life sentence for the attempted
assassination in 1980 of the shah's last prime minister, Shahpour
Bakhtiar.
   When French Foreign Minister Roland Dumas visited Tehran in
February, Iran said Paris had not kept promises made in negotiations
for freeing the three French hostages.
   France has denied negotiating for its hostages' freedom, and the
Socialist government of President Francois Mitterrand says it has no
knowledge of any deals.
</TEXT>
