<DOCNO> AP890913-0131 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 1329EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-HUD-Pierce'sMill     09-13 0842</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD-Pierce's Mill,840</SECOND>
<HEAD>Residents Love Mill Project At Center of HUD Controversy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBIN P. TEATER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DURHAM, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wilma Smith is unhappy with the notoriety her
home has gained as a result of the HUD scandals in Washington, and
she has a simple wish.
   ``I hope they finish this thing up with HUD so everyone can get
back to being a happy family,'' says Mrs. Smith, 54, who has lived
for nearly two years at the Durham Hosiery Mill housing project.
   Ella Holeman, another resident, praises her home at the
renovated, turn of the century factory as safe.
   But it isn't questions of security or comfort that interest
investigators in Washington _ it's political influence.
   The mill project has become a symbol of influence peddling at the
Department of Housing and Urban Development during the Reagan era,
and is expected to be discussed prominently Friday when
congressional hearings resume with the scheduled testimony of former
Secretary Samuel Pierce.
   Pierce in May told Congress he played no major role in HUD
funding decisions. But shortly afterward, a former deputy, Shirley
Wiseman, said her boss personally ordered the North Carolina project
funded over the objections of several agency experts. Ms. Wiseman
also disclosed that the city's then-mayor, who lobbied HUD for the
funding, was a former law partner of Pierce's. Other locally
prominent Republicans became involved in shepherding the project to
approval.
   Since the disclosures, Pierce has been publicly linked to a
number of other HUD funding decisions, all within his legal
authority.
   In an interview published this week, the former secretary
acknowledged approving the $15 million Durham project, which opened
in November 1987.
   ``Occasionally you have to step in an overrule your staff,'' he
told Time magazine. ``That Durham project was a great success.''
   Critics question the wisdom of turning the mill into low-income
housing because it is near railroad tracks and on a site believed to
be contaminated by toxic wastes. But Mrs. Smith and her fellow
tenants agree with Pierce.
   The four buildings of the complex have been connected with
glass-enclosed walkways. All of the apartments are carpeted and
include private bathrooms, kitchens and combination living-dining
areas. The complex also features a recreation room, a reading-TV
room and laundry areas.
   ``I love the environment,'' said Christine Gooch, 50, who has
lived at the project for a year. ``It's convenient to the bus stop,
grocery stores and downtown.''
   ``I like everything about it,'' said Rubin Johnson, 69, who moved
to the Hosiery Mill five months ago. ``I feel very safe here.''
   The mill, built in 1902, employed about 1,000 people in its
owners' heyday as the world's largest supplier of cotton hosiery.
The mill shut down in 1936 and in 1978 was placed on the National
Register of Historic Places.
   HUD records show the mill project, which was developed by John L.
Allen of Myerson-Allen Co. Inc. of Boston, languished in financial
trouble for six years, winning HUD funding only after Allen hired
two Republican consultants.
   One was Lou Kitchin, the southeastern political director for the
Reagan and Bush presidential campaigns. He received $25,000. City
records show Allen also paid $12,000 to GOP state Rep. Harold J.
Brubaker.
   Kitchin said he did not take advantage of his political ties and
only helped Allen put his HUD proposal together. Brubaker said his
role was to bring Allen and Kitchin together and he collected only
airfare and expenses for his work.
   Then-Mayor Charles Markham also lobbied HUD. Markham and Pierce
practiced at the same law firm in the 1960s.
   ``We are not social friends,'' Markham said in a recent
interview. ``My contacts with him in the last 24 years have been
very infrequent and very casual.''
   Markham wrote several letters to HUD and met with Pierce's top
aide, Deborah Gore Dean to seek support for the project.
   ``These conversations were for us to set out why we felt this
project would be good for Durham,'' Markham said. ``I still think
it's a good project.''
   Still, the controversy surrounding the project prompted its
managers to send residents a memo this summer assuring them they
didn't have to worry about it closing.
   ``Our concern is that residents will misunderstand,'' said Janice
Daley, a regional manager for Myerson-Allen. ``We've been kind of
quelling the rumors and doing the best we can. We said, `Nobody is
going to make you move.'''
   Ms. Daley said the complex has been full since spring. The 174
low-income elderly and disabled people occupy one- and two-bedroom
and efficiency apartments.
   Residents don't care about the political controversy. They prefer
to talk about safety and camaraderie.
   ``The living conditions are good,'' said Ms. Holeman. ``If
somebody is not around, we have somebody to check on you. We have a
sick committee.''
   Mrs. Smith still wishes the attention would pass, saying some
residents remain worried about their future.
   ``Some people don't understand what they read,'' said Mrs. Smith,
head of the tenant association. ``I feel like somebody is ballooning
things out of proportion. Please let us live in peace.''
</TEXT>
