<FIRST>r a PM-TrainAccident     09-13 0132</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Train Accident,0137</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rail Cars Containing Flammable Mixture Derail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BYRON, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven rail cars loaded with 140,000 gallons
of a flammable mixture of butane and propane jumped the tracks
today, forcing the evacuation of 15 homes, authorities said. No one
was injured.
   One 20,000-gallon tank car leaked some of the liquefied petroleum
gas, or LPG, after the accident, officials said.
   An area within 1,500 feet of the derailment was cordoned off
because of the threat of explosion, said Southern Pacific spokesman
Andy Anderson.
   Emergency crews in goggles worked to drain off the LPG into other
tankers or trucks. The derailed cars were on their sides.
   Anderson said the 33-car train derailed before dawn about 45
miles east of San Francisco, apparently because of a mechanical
problem under one car.
