<FIRST>u p PM-NYCMayor 2ndLd-Writethru a0569 09-13 0816</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NYC Mayor, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0569,0836</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dinkins, Giuliani Win Mayoral Primaries</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS four grafs after 10th graf pvs, `The other ...' with
Koch, Dinkins at rally today.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Primary Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY13,16,18, LaserColor NY 17,22</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL STIEG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   David Dinkins said today his strong showing among
white voters in a Democratic primary that ended the 12-year era of
brash and combative Ed Koch positions him well to become New York
City's first black mayor.
   The Manhattan borough president will face former federal
prosecutor Rudolph Giuliani, who thrashed cosmetics heir Ronald
Lauder in the Republican primary Tuesday.
   ``You, the people of New York, made history today, and I promise
you I shall never let you down,'' Dinkins, the first black to win a
major party nomination in New York City, told cheering supporters.
   Dinkins received 537,313 votes, or 51 percent, to 445,816, or 42
percent, for Koch, in the four-candidate race in this Democratic
stronghold. The victor took more than 90 percent of the black vote,
half the Hispanic vote and about 30 percent of the white vote. By
comparison, the Rev. Jesse Jackson won 17 percent of the white vote
in the 1988 Democratic presidential primary.
   ``I can indeed reach beyond my base,'' Dinkins said this morning
on the CBS program ``This Morning.'' ``Victory with just
African-American and Latinos, that would not be a good thing for the
city.''
   ``He won it fairly, squarely, and by a large margin,'' Koch told
supporters. ``I am ready to serve, to help him become the next
mayor.''
   Giuliani, seeking to become the first Republican elected mayor
since 1965, got 75,720 votes, or 67 percent, to 36,905, or 33
percent, for Lauder, whose record $12 million in campaign spending
went mostly for negative television commercials.
   ``I want to bring new life into New York City _ new blood, new
heart, new people, and make this again the magical city that it once
was,'' said Giuliani, who also will be on the Liberal Party and
Independent Fusion lines.
   Lauder, a former ambassador to Austria, will remain on the Nov. 7
ballot as the Conservative Party's nominee.
   The other Democratic candidates trailed far behind Dinkins and
Koch. Former transit chief Richard Ravitch had 48,289 votes, or 5
percent, and Comptroller Harrison J. Goldin had 28,790, or 3 percent.
   At a City Hall rally today before 3,000 people, Koch called for
Democratic unity against Giuliani.
   ``A new campaign has begun and now is the time for supporters of
David Dinkins, Ed Koch, Dick Ravitch and Jay Goldin to join hands
and join forces in a unified campaign to ensure victory for David
Dinkins this fall,'' Koch said.
   Dinkins asked the crowd, ``Have we scraped and struggled to
survive nine years of reactionary Republican government in
Washington just to hand over our city to the very same forces?''
   ``No!'' the crowd shouted back.
   Koch, the loudmouthed symbol of New York to much of America,
first won election as a long shot in 1977 while the city was in the
throes of a fiscal crisis. He was re-elected twice by huge margins.
   But the city's mood shifted away from his brash style as AIDS,
drugs, homelessness, crime and other urban ills seemed to demand a
milder touch. The calm, deliberative Dinkins projected that image.
   The campaign drama heightened in the last weeks after a black
youth was slain in an attack by a white gang, heating up simmering
racial tensions.
   Dinkins said the killing was an example of the hatred Koch had
not addressed. Koch was criticized for suggesting that marchers
protesting the killings were making things worse.
   Koch, forcing a smile Tuesday night, said ``I've had 12 glorious
years as mayor,'' Koch said.
   But he reminded the crowd, ``You'll have me from now to December
31st. I do not intend to keep my mouth shut.''
   Dinkins quieted his supporters when they booed at the mention of
Koch.
   ``Oh no, oh no _ we're all together now,'' said Dinkins, joined
at the podium by Jesse Jackson. ``Remember me? I'm the guy that
brings people together.
   ``With your help I intend to be a mayor who leads a new era of
change, a mayor who sets and pursues a new standard of integrity,''
Dinkins said. ``I intend to be a mayor who restores a new rule of
law in our streets, in our schools and in our subways.''
   Giuliani gained fame as U.S. attorney by prosecuting Wall Street
cheats, corrupt politicians and mobsters.
   His multiparty candidacy is reminiscent of the city's last
Republican mayor, John Lindsay, but Giuliani preferred to compare
himself to the legendary Fiorello LaGuardia, mayor from 1934 to 1945.
   ``He united all New Yorkers,'' Giuliani said. ``LaGuardia was a
Republican like I am, a Republican who reaches out for the support
of others, of Democrats and Liberals, of Conservatives and
Independents.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
