<FIRST>r a PM-O'Hare-EmergencyLanding     09-13 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-O'Hare-Emergency Landing,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jet Skids Off O'Hare Runway</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pilot of an American Airlines jetliner
reported hydraulic-system trouble before the plane skidded off a
runway at O'Hare Airport, but airline officials said today they
don't know if the problem was anything more than a faulty warning
light.
   Two of 113 people aboard Tuesday afternoon suffered minor
injuries while evacuating down emergency chutes, American spokesman
Thomas Stack said.
   Ambulances and firefighting equipment were standing by near the
runway during the landing.
   The plane from Rochester, N.Y., landed normally but then, for
reasons that were not immediately clear, skidded off the runway,
American spokesman Al Becker said today. He said the nose gear
collapsed as the plane left the pavement. There was no fire.
   Before landing, the pilot had ``radioed about a problem. ... He
mentioned hydraulic problems,'' Becker said.
   ``It may have just been a warning light,'' he said. ``We've
really got to investigate today to know.''
   Passenger Andre Ruzycki said passengers applauded the pilot after
the plane came to rest.
   ``It was no worse than any roller-coaster ride, really,'' said
Ruzycki. ``No one was really aware of anything until we touched
down. ... We weren't told anything until we were being evacuated and
told to get off the plane quickly.''
   Federal Aviation Administration spokesman Mort Edelstein said the
FAA and the National Transportation Safety Board would inspect the
plane.
   The plane was a two-engine MD-80, which is essentially a DC-9
redesigned for noise reduction, Edelstein said. Becker didn't know
how old the aircraft is but said the MD-80s are no more than five
years old.
   Edelstein said the plane had been scheduled to fly on to Salt
Lake City after a stop in Chicago.
   ``The pilot reported hydraulic system problems as he was coming
in on approach,'' Edelstein said. ``He was asked if he wanted
emergency vehicles on standby, and he said yes.''
   The crash of a United Airlines DC-10 in Sioux City, Iowa, on July
19 focused attention on hydraulic system problems. The pilot of that
plane was unable to use the landing gear, and the plane cartwheeled
on landing and burst into flames, killing 112 of 296 people aboard.
</TEXT>
