<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 1442EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ColtStrike     09-13 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Colt Strike,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gunmaker, Union Dispute Cost of Back-Pay Ruling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Colt Firearms Division said a ruling that
it rehire 800 strikers with back pay could cost the gunmaker less
than $16 million, not the $40 million estimated by the union.
   An administrative law judge, Martin Roth, said in a ruling
released Monday that Colt had engaged in dozens of unfair labor
practices during the 3{-year-old strike, and he ordered the workers'
reinstatement.
   The United Auto Workers and Colt said Tuesday it was too early to
say whether they would appeal the ruling to the National Labor
Relations Board.
   Colt Industries spokesman Michael Dunn on Tuesday estimated the
company's total liability at less than $6 million. He declined to
say how the company arrived at the figure.
   Robert Madore, a regional official with the UAW, stuck by his
estimate that the back wages totaled $40 million, or an average of
$50,000 per worker.
   ``I don't know how they come up with their figure,'' Madore said.
``I think they're going to have to sharpen their pencil.''
   Madore speculated that the discrepancy stemmed from a company
offer at some point during the strike to let 50 strikers return to
work. Roth's ruling said the company must pay back wages to strikers
``to the date of a valid offer of reinstatement.''
   ``If they have 50 job openings and they offer 50 jobs to 800
workers, does that stop the back pay? It can't realistically,''
Madore said.
</TEXT>
