<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 1435EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Smoking Bjt   09-13 0649</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Smoking, Bjt,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senators Clash Over Proposed Airline Smoking Ban</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tobacco state lawmakers vowed Wednesday to
grind the Senate to a procedural crawl unless attempts to ban
smoking on all airline flights are dropped, but their unbowed
opponents said they welcomed a showdown.
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, planned a vote
for Thursday on whether to block a filibuster by cigarette industry
supporters. The filibuster _ unlimited debate in hopes of preventing
a vote _ is aimed at killing legislation by Sen. Frank Lautenberg,
D-N.J., expanding current airline smoking restrictions to all
domestic flights.
   The maneuvering came as outgoing Surgeon General C. Everett Koop
told a congressional hearing that minors should be forbidden from
buying cigarettes from vending machines.
   Koop, who leaves his job this month, said federal legislation was
needed because 43 states have laws banning tobacco sales to minors
but don't enforce them.
   In the Senate fight over airline smoking, tobacco state senators
said they would accept a permanent version of the current smoking
ban on two-hour airline flights. But Mitchell scheduled the vote
after ban opponents said they would try to block the Senate's work
unless advocates of tougher restrictions dropped their efforts.
   Lautenberg said he would press his legislation, saying, ``We
won't succumb to threats.''
   Sen. Wendell Ford, D-Ky., said tobacco senators would accept
language the permanent ban on two-hour flights, which the House
passed Aug. 3. The restriction effects four-fifths of all flights.
   But he said unless smoking opponents accepted his offer, he would
slow consideration of the $11.9 billion transportation spending bill
for next year that contains the cigarette restrictions.
   ``This one will take basically a week to get through,'' he said
of the transportation measure, one of 13 spending bills
congressional leaders want to complete by the Oct. 1 start of fiscal
1990.
   ``There's more at stake here I think than just the question of
smoking on airliners,'' he said. ``It's a question of the budget so
the rest of the world can work.''
   Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., said any delays would be Lautenberg's
fault for inserting the restrictions into the bill in the first
place.
   ``He may end up rolling us, but he will know that he has been in
a fight,'' he said.
   Helms said his state _ the nation's leading tobacco producer _
has 30,000 tobacco growers ``to whom I have made a commitment that
I'd protect their interests as long as I'm in the United States
Senate, and I'm going to do that.''
   Lautenberg asked his opponents to drop their efforts.
   ``If they have a case to make they ought to make it and let us
vote on it,'' he said. ``But that is not likely to happen. We'll
endure.''
   Airline employees and health groups have pressed for a total
smoking ban on aircraft, claiming that cigarette fumes can cause
cancer and other diseases for everyone aboard a flight.
   Tobacco interests say there's been no proof that the smoke
endangers non-smokers and argue that there are plenty of other
chemicals soiling recirculated aircraft cabin air.
   Across Capitol Hill, Koop told the House Energy and Commerce
transportation subcommittee that giving youngsters easy access to
cigarettes was comparable to letting them purchase alcohol simply
because they had the money in their pockets.
   ``There is no logical reason why we should have a double standard
for controlling the sale of tobacco and alcohol, the two major legal
addicting drugs used in our society,'' he told a congressional
hearing.
   The Tobacco Institute, the cigarette industry's trade group, has
said 80 percent of cigarette machines are located where teen-agers
do not congregate.
   But Koop said that still leaves enough machines to justify
federal action.
   ``Even 20 percent of the 374,000 vending machines in the United
States represents a huge number of sites from which teen-agers can
readily obtain cigarettes illegally,'' Koop said.
</TEXT>
