<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 1454EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-MilitaryConstruction     09-13 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Military Construction,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Eliminates Military Construction Money in Philippines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Senate subcommittee on Wednesday approved a
$7.7 billion spending bill that would eliminate President Bush's
request for military construction in the Philippines and make a
drastic cut in funds for South Korea.
   By voice vote, the Senate Appropriations subcommittee on military
construction approved a spending bill that is $1.3 billion below the
funding level for fiscal 1989 and about $300 million less than
Bush's request for the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1.
   ``This is an 18 percent reduction in real terms from last year's
military construction budget,'' said Sen. James Sasser, D-Tenn.,
chairman of the subcommittee. ``This is appropriate considering the
budget deficit.''
   Specifically, the bill eliminates the $40.8 million Bush
requested for such construction items in the Philippines as
dormitories at Clark Air Base, storage facilities and maintenance
shops.
   The House, in its bill, approved $6.1 million for military
construction in the Philippines.
   The Senate subcommittee, adhering to earlier action in the Senate
authorization bill, also eliminated the $35.4 million for family
housing in the Philippines.
   Bush's request of $86.3 million for military construction in
South Korea was cut by $85.5 million, largely affecting the
facilities at the Osan Air Base. The Senate authorization bill
approved $66.9 million for construction in South Korea while the
House adopted legislation earmarking $74.2 million for Korean
construction.
   ``It's a question of how long military forces will be in Korea,''
Sasser said. ``In the Philippines, there will be a renegotiation of
base rights.''
   Under the Philippines constitution, the country must negotiate a
new agreement with the United States on the location of Clark Air
Base and Subic Bay Naval Base and the continued presence of U.S.
forces.
   While cutting money for overseas projects, the subcommittee added
$250 million to the bill for National Guard and reserves in the
United States. Bush had requested $452.6 million.
   The subcommitte also cut $50 million from the president's request
of $101.5 million for housing the B-2 stealth bomber at the Whiteman
Air Force Base in Missouri. The reduction mirrors the action taken
in the authorization bill and reflects the delay in the program.
   The full Appropriations committee is expected to vote on the
subcommittee bill on Thursday. Once passed by the full Senate,
members of the House and Senate will meet in conference to hammer
out a final version.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
