<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 1519EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-Sharon     09-13 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Sharon,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sharon Advocates ``Removing'' Arafat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel's Minister of Industry and Trade, Ariel
Sharon, said Wednesday that Israel should ``remove'' PLO leader
Yasser Arafat, just as he said the United States tried to kill
Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi.
   Sharon, who unsuccessfully sought his Likud bloc's nomination for
prime minister in the past, also said he would like to lead Israel
to a peace agreement with its neighbors but rejected ceding any
captured Arab lands.
   The retired general, in the United States to promote his new book
``The Warrior,'' told reporters at a breakfast meeting that ``there
are certain people whose activities cannot be tolerated by free,
democratic societies. Therefore, they should be removed.''
   President Reagan tried to kill Gadhafi in an air raid in April
1986 because the Libyan strongman had ordered a bomb placed in a
West German discotheque frequented by U.S. servicemen, Sharon said.
   ``Arafat is in the same category,'' he added.
   The United States never publicly identified Gadhafi as the target
of its raid but U.S. officials indicated they hoped to shock some of
his supporters into breaking with him. Gadhafi said the aerial
bombing of Tripoli and Benghazi killed his infant adopted daughter.
   Sharon predicted the number of Jewish settlers in the occupied
West Bank would reach 100,000 next year, and said Israel should
grant autonomy to the estimated 1.5 million Palestinians living
there but retain control of the region's defense.
   He rejected the PLO's demand that Israel allow the creation of a
Palestinian state in the West Bank, reiterating his view that there
is already a Palestinian state _ in Jordan, whose population is
predominantly Palestinian.
   He praised King Hussein for his courage and survival in the face
of domestic and foreign enemies, but urged the Jordanian monarch to
reverse his recent decision to allow groups associated with Arafat's
Fatah wing of the PLO to operate in Amman. ``For his own safety he
should expel them,'' Sharon said.
   Sharon, whose recent invitation to visit the Soviet Republic of
Georgia was withdrawn by Soviet authorities, said he hoped to be
able to visit there one day.
   His parents were born in Russia and he still has an aunt in the
city of Tashkent, he said.
</TEXT>
