<DOCNO> AP890913-0148 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 1537EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-AlyeskaTesting     09-13 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Alyeska Testing,0503</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tests Catch Drinking Crew Members</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 16 tanker crew members have
been stopped from boarding their vessels at the oil shipment
terminal in Valdez since June because they had been drinking,
authorities said Wednesday.
   The alcohol screening program was set up in response to the
grounding of the tanker Exxon Valdez, which hit a reef hours after
it left the terminal, said George Jurkowich, a spokesman for Alyeska
Pipeline Service Co.
   The Exxon Valdez dumped almost 11 million gallons of thick North
Slope crude oil in Prince William Sound on March 24 in the nation's
worst oil spill.
   The captain, Joseph Hazelwood, was tested hours after the
accident and alcohol was found in his system.
   Crew members who go ashore while their tankers are in port pass
through security at the Alyeska terminal before reboarding. They are
given breath tests if it appears to security guards they have been
drinking, Jurkowich said.
   All ships' masters are tested before their vessels leave the
terminal complex, Jurkowich said.
   Between the time the screening system was set up June 1 and
Friday, 1,087 crew members have passed through the terminal, 56 have
been tested and 16 have been foud to have unacceptable levels of
alcohol, Jurkowich said. They were prevented from boarding their
ships.
   ``We think it is a success because we are detecting a small
percentage of people who are under the influence,'' he said. ``If a
crewman leaves his vessel _ leaves the terminal _ when they come
back to the terminal they are required to pass through Alyeska's
security office.''
   Jurkowich said the blood-alcohol level of crew members must be
below .04 percent. That is the Coast Guard's highest allowable level
for operation of a commercial vessel.
   The state of Alaska and many other states consider motorists
drunk if they have a blood-alcohol level of .10.
   If a crew member fails, he must wait an hour and be retested.
   It's up to the ship's owner or agent to determine what happens to
a crew member who isn't allowed aboard the tanker.
   In a related matter, a check of maritime pilots in Portland,
Ore., found six of 57 had their driver's licenses suspended at some
time for drunken driving, a television station reported.
   KATU-TV reported Tuesday the suspensions are listed in Oregon
Department of Motor Vehicles records on the pilots, who board ships
to guide them through the treacherous entrance to the Columbia River.
   Geoff Stone, President fo the Columbia Bar Pilots Association,
responded that there has never been evidence that drinking posed a
safety problem with the pilots. Driving records don't necessarily
have a bearing on a pilot's behavior on the job, he told the station.
   The maritime pilots are licensed and must pass a drug screening
test, he said.
   There are 64 pilots for the port. Seven are residents of
Washington state, where driving records are kept private.
</TEXT>
