<FIRST>r i AM-Cambodia     09-13 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cambodia,0474</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aid Workers Flee as Cambodia Fighting Intensifies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NATE THAYER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   SITE 2, Thailand (AP) _ Western relief workers fled a refugee
camp on the Thai-Cambodian border Wednesday as fighting intensified
between Cambodian factions less than two weeks before Vietnam's
pledged troop pullout from Cambodia.
   Officials from Cambodia's Khmer People's National Liberation
Front blamed the latest clashes on the failure of last month's
Cambodian peace talks in Paris.
   Thai military sources and relief workers said more than 20
mortars fired by troops of Cambodia's Vietnamese-installed
government hit guerrilla positions near the Thai village of Ban
Sangae, a mile from Site 2 refugee camp. No casualties were reported.
   A Western relief official also reported heavy fighting near Nong
Chan, 13 miles north of the Thai border town of Aranyaprathet.
   ``United Nations and international relief workers were forced to
evacuate Site 2 because of nearby fighting,'' a senior U.N. official
said.
   More than 100 workers from international relief agencies work at
the camp of 140,000 Cambodians. It is the largest on the frontier
and is administered by the Khmer Front and supplied by the United
Nations.
   Another Western official said access to the camp Thursday would
be restricted to essential medical staff.
   On Tuesday, he said, one mortar landed inside the camp but did
not explode.
   Abdul Gaffar, a senior Khmer Front official, said the fighting
has intensified because talks aimed at ending Cambodia's 20-year-old
conflict failed.
   His organization is one of three guerrilla factions opposing the
Phnom Penh government. A Khmer Front official at Site 2 said the
front received 27 truckloads of Chinese weapons and ammunition in
the past week.
   The Paris talks ended without a political settlement largely
because of Phnom Penh's refusal to include the radical communist
Khmer Rouge in a future coalition government.
   The Khmer Rouge, the most powerful opposition faction, killed
hundreds of thousands of civilians in an attempt to build an
agrarian society between 1975 and 1978.
   Vietnam invaded Cambodia in 1978, ousted the Khmer Rouge and
installed a government. It has pledged to withdraw its troops from
Cambodia by the end of September.
   Gen. Manat Thinkulabute, the Thai military officer responsible
for Trat and Chantaburi provinces where several Khmer Rouge
strongholds are located, said he expects fiercer fighting along the
border in the next two to three months.
   The guerrillas responded coolly this week to efforts by
Thailand's Prime Minister Chatichai Choonhavan to negotiate a
cease-fire, according to The Nation newspaper of Bangkok.
   Chatichai met guerrilla leaders Monday and Tuesday and is to meet
Cambodia's premier, Hun Sen, in Bangkok at an unspecified date.
   The Nation quoted Kraisak Choonhavan, Chatichai's son and one of
his advisers, as saying the prime minister would continue efforts to
break the deadlock.
</TEXT>
