<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--MovieMixup     09-13 0153</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Movie Mixup,0156</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rape Scene From Movie Broadcast During Children's Show</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A television station inadvertently aired
several seconds of the final strobe-lit rape scene from the movie
``Looking for Mr. Goodbar'' during a morning children's program.
   The scene was broadcast Tuesday on KABB-TV in the middle of
``Real Ghostbusters,'' a program that airs from 7 a.m. to 7:30 a.m.
   Apparently one of KABB's producers was editing the rape scene
last week to air at night while the station was receiving a
satellite feed of the cartoon. A station technician hit the wrong
switch and the scene was edited onto the station's videotape of
``Real Ghostbusters,'' said Sam Bickel, KABB program director.
   ``We try to do a good thing and we wind up doing a bad thing,''
Bickel said. ``It was real quick. But it was a mistake.''
   The station received 15 viewer complaints after the scene was
aired.
