<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 1604EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-CleanAir     09-13 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Clean Air,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panel, Beginning Work on Bush Bill, Promises Major Changes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of a House panel said Wednesday they'll
try to amend every major provision of President Bush's clean air
bill, but all agreed it's time to break a 10-year stalemate and pass
the pollution-cutting measure.
   The House Energy and Commerce environment subcommittee was the
first panel to consider the Bush legislation, although the initial
session was reserved for opening remarks. Amendments that would
begin to shape a political compromise will be offered beginning
Tuesday, Chairman Henry A. Waxman, D-Calif., said.
   ``This bill is a delicate mosaic,'' said chief Republican sponsor
Norman F. Lent of New York, who said he feared that the Energy and
Commerce Committee might fashion a compromise that could unravel on
the House floor.
   The president's bill seeks to significantly reduce the three
major air pollution causes: ozone, which causes urban smog; acid
rain, and airborne toxic chemicals.
   The opening statements made clear that major battles will be
fought, beginning with the expected three-week subcommittee
consideration, over reducing auto emissions, which also produce
smog. Another fight: Do electric customers of dirty-burning power
plants get the entire bill for achieving acid rain reductions.
   Other amendments will seek to ban tall industrial smokestacks
that merely carry pollution elsewhere; to increase protection for
national parks; to establish strict standards to protect health near
toxic chemical plants, and to ensure that no one fuel is favored in
a program for alternative motor fuels.
   Lent was upbeat about chances for passage of the bill this
Congress, commenting, ``Republicans will be far more willing to
support a Bush bill than they would have been to support a bill by
the Democrats.''
   GOP lawmakers had no such alternative the last eight years,
because former President Reagan did not propose a clean air bill
during his eight years in office. The last major clean air revisions
were approved in 1977.
   Waxman repeated his determination to toughen Bush's language on
auto emissions. He aims to tighten tailpipe emission requirements,
to strip a provision to average pollution emissions by engine
category and to require that on-board anti-pollution equipment be
guaranteed for 100,000 miles, twice as long as in current law.
   Rep. John D. Dingell, D-Mich., the chairman of the full Energy
and Commerce Committee, is expected to oppose Waxman's changes and
argue the auto industry's position. The automakers contend that
introduction of new cars each year, with their sophisticated
anti-pollution devices, would bring a drastic cut auto pollution as
older models are replaced.
   Dingell and Waxman have fought each other to a stalemate in the
past on this issue.
   Lawmakers from Pennsylvania, West Virginia, Georgia, Ohio,
Illinois, Indiana, Kentucky, Tennessee and Missouri are demanding
that other regions help them pay for acid rain reductions. These
states argue that, otherwise, their electric utility customers would
finance a disproportionate share of measures to cut emissions of
sulfur dioxide, the major component of acid rain.
   Bush seeks to cut sulfur dioxide by 10 million tons by the year
2000, based on 1980 levels. His bill places the entire burden on
utilities with power plants that burn dirty, high-sulfur coal _
which are prevalent in the nine states.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
