<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 1723EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-OilyRocks     09-13 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oily Rocks,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Washington Gets First-hand Look at Oil-Stained Alaskan Rocks</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX17</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Environmentalists tried a new tactic Wednesday
in their dispute over Exxon's cleanup of oil-stained beaches in
Alaska: They brought bits of the still polluted beaches to
Washington.
   Messengers from the National Wildlife Federation spread out
across Capitol Hill to deliver zip-lock plastic bags of oil-stained
Alaska rocks to every member of Congress.
   Rock samples also went to the White House, to other key members
of the Bush administration and to the top executives of Exxon Corp.,
in New York, according to spokesmen for the federation _ as well as
to reporters at a news conference.
   ``These are the rocks that Exxon has cleaned twice,'' Jay Hair,
the federation's president. He said he brought them back from Smith
Island, one of the areas of Alaska most affected by the massive
spill from the Exxon Valdez oil tanker last March.
   The island's beaches already have been cleaned twice by Exxon,
but oil continues to seep up from beneath, having penetrated as much
as 40 inches in some areas, the environmentalists said.
   ``We wanted every member of Congress to actually touch these
rocks, to smell the palpable coatings of crude oil, to experience
for themselves in a small way the immensity of this disaster,'' Hair
said.
   Criticism of Exxon's cleanup efforts increased this week as the
hugh oil company was pulling most of its equipment and manpower out
of the polluted areas for the winter. No further cleanup activity is
planned until next spring.
   Exxon, which has estimated that the cleanup costs likely will
exceed $1 billion, claims that most of the contaminated beaches have
been ``environmentally stabilized'' and has hinted that it may not
return for further cleanup activities next next year.
   Hair ridiculed Exxon's references to beaches being
``environmentally stabilized.''
   ``That's an Exxon euphemism. It does not mean cleaned up in any
scientific sense,'' said Hair, whose federation is the country's
largest conservation group with 5.8 million members. ``No beaches
have been cleaned. Exxon can not make this thing go away by their
arrogance.''
   Earlier this week nearly a dozen of the country's major
environmental groups criticized Exxon's cleanup efforts, saying that
claims by the oil company that 1,090 miles of contaminated shoreline
have been cleaned cannot be substantiated by scientific fact.
   The groups said the damage caused to wildlife by the spill has
yet to be calculated, but that so far the confirmed casualties
include more than 33,000 birds, 138 bald eagles, and 980 sea otters.
Alaska's fishing industry also has been thrown into chaos.
   Hair said that in many cases shorelines have been exposed to
``irretrievable damage.'' But he said Exxon should be directed by
the government to continue cleanup efforts to minimize damage on
severely oiled areas and limit the contamination to the food chain
that continues to threaten wildlife.
   ``At this point there is much that cannot be restored,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
