<DOCNO> AP890913-0158 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 1725EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-MedellinTrial     09-13 0586</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Medellin Trial,0606</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opening Statements Given in Spinoff of Lehder Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys for five men on trial on
charges linked to the Medellin cocaine cartel are innocent and
government witnesses are ``lying to save their souls,'' defense
lawyers said Wednesday.
   A prosecutor argued in opening statements that the conspiracy
existed and created a ``pipeline'' of cocaine leading from Colombia
to the United States.
   The five are accused of conspiring with cartel leader Carlos
Lehder Rivas and others to create a large-scale coke-smuggling ring
which operated from 1974 to 1989.
   Lehder, extradited from Colombia in 1987, was convicted last year
of smuggling more than 20 tons of cocaine into the country and was
sentenced to life in prison without parole. Information developed
for that trial led to the indictment in this case.
   In opening arguments, Assistant U.S. Attorney Ernst Mueller tied
Lehder to other cartel leaders who also were indicted in the case
but remain at large in Colombia. He said that beginning in 1974,
Lehder hired pilots and distributors, including some of the
defendants, to run the ring in the United States.
   ``The central theme you will hear is a core cast of characters
including the Medellin cartel ... had a central purpose that never
deviated _ to import and distribute cocaine in the United States,''
Mueller said.
   He described the beginnings of the operation and told how it grew.
   ``In 1978, there was a veritable cocaine pipeline from Colombia
to Norman's Cay in the Bahamas to the United States,'' Mueller said.
   Attorney Clyde Collins, representing Jack Reed, 58, called the
government's case a fabrication and said Reed was not a key figure.
   ``Lehder's lieutenant? This old man? No!'' Collins said.
   ``Liars, beggars and thieves _ that's who the government will
produce to testify in this trial,'' Collins said. ``They lied to
save their souls.''
   On trial with Reed, 58, who was convicted with Lehder last year
on one conspiracy count and sentenced to 15 years in prison, are
Thomas Howard Herington, 35, Mill Valley, Calif.; Barry Kane, 52,
Hyannis, Mass., and Fort Lauderdale; Donald Kenneth Lady, 41,
Pomona, Calif., and Samuel Thomas Stewart, 53, Anaheim, Calif.
   Herington's attorney, Patrick Hallinan, admitted that his client
did some minor dealing in the past but gave up all ties to drugs.
   Rick Mycock, representing Kane, said most of the evidence against
him will come from George Jung, a felon and admitted liar. He said
Kane was innocent.
   Attorney Ray David, representing Lady, said his client helped
secure some ranches in Mexico for associates, but not for
drug-smuggling purposes. He cautioned jurors not to assume the
clients are guilty by association.
   ``Carlos Lehder is not on trial here and drugs are not on
trial,'' he said.
   Kevin Sanders, who represents Stewart, described him as a
law-abiding family man who operates a legitimate aircraft business.
   ``Sam got here today as the result of a very large and extensive
witchhunt conducted by the U.S. attorney's office,'' Sanders said.
   The Medellin cartel, named for the Colombian city where it is
based, is believed to supply 80 percent of the cocaine in the United
States.
   Reed is charged with conspiracy to distribute five kilograms or
more of cocaine and operating a continuing criminal enterprise.
Kane, Lady and Stewart face the conspiracy count and an additional
charge of conspiracy to import cocaine. Herington is charged with
conspiracy to distribute cocaine.
   If convicted, the men could get sentences ranging from 10 years
to life.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
