<FIRST>r w AM-DisabledVets     09-13 0165</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Disabled Vets,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panel Approves Cost-of-Living Benefits Increase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House Veterans Affairs subcommittee voted
Wednesday to approve a 4.9 percent cost-of-living increase in the
benefits paid to 2.2 million veterans with service-connected
disabilities or to their survivors.
   The full committee is expected to act Wednesday on the
legislation, which would raise expenditures for fiscal 1990 to $9.34
billion instead of $8.9 billion under the current schedule,
according to committee estimates.
   The increase would become effective Dec. 1.
   The bill, approved by the subcommittee on compensation, pensions
and insurance, also raises the special monthly payment for loss or
loss of use of certain organs or portions of the body from $63 a
month to $66 a month. Further, it requires the Veterans Affairs
Department to move at least three and no more than seven VA regional
offices onto property owned by VA medical centers.
   Twenty-eight cities have medical centers and regional
administrative centers in different parts of town, according to the
committee.
</TEXT>
