<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 1958EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Books     09-13 0628</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Books,0651</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dissidents and Defectors Share Shelves With Gorbachev at Moscow Fair</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAREY GOLDBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Publisher Ilya Levkov looked proudly at books by
two Soviet defectors in his display at Moscow's International Book
Fair.
   ``I have two authors with death sentences against them,'' he
said, ``and here they are alive and well in my corner.''
   Judging by the fair that opened to the public Wednesday, the
Soviet Union is not only ready to hear the worst about itself, but
to buy it.
   Six years ago, authorities branded at least 50 Western books
intended for the fair as anti-Soviet and confiscated them.
   This year, President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's ``Perestroika''
shares shelf space with works by defectors Arkady Shevchenko and
Stanislav Levchenko, emigre Jewish dissident Natan Sharansky and
American hard-liner Zbigniew Brzezinski.
   Brzezinski's book, ``The Great Failure,'' is subtitled ``Birth
and Death of Communism in the Twentieth Century.''
   Also on display is John LeCarre's ``Russia House,'' in which a
Soviet scientist's crucial notebooks are passed to a publisher
attending the _ believe or not _ Moscow book fair.
   Levkov, who settled in New York after emigrating from the Soviet
Union 33 years ago, said the Soviet publishing company Progress
wants to acquire the rights to Brzezinski's book, and other Soviet
publishers are interested in almost all his offerings.
   At neighboring stands, Christian and Jewish publishers who once
had to endure harassment from this atheist state said they have
never had it so easy.
   Yosef Friedman, a member of the Lubavitch strain of Hasidic
Judaism, said most of his Russian-language religious books were
confiscated in the past. But this year, he said, Soviet airport
customs officers did not even examine his two cartloads of books.
   ``That's better than New York,'' he said. ``It was really
strange.''
   Soviets crammed the giant pavilions at an exhibition complex in
north Moscow where more than 2,000 publishing companies displayed
their wares, and people lined up for hours to get in.
   Moscow clerk Alexei Romantsev said that after the literary
journal Novy Mir began publishing Alexander Solzhenitsyn's ``Gulag
Archipelago'' this summer, ``there can't be any risk here, or any
real surprises.''
   Still, Romantsev said he raced to Levkov's booth as soon as the
fair opened and had been sitting there devouring the emigre press
for more than two hours.
   David Kotick of the Bantam Doubleday Dell Publishing Group Inc.,
whose booth boasted such Western best-sellers as ``Russia House''
and Frederick Forsyth's ``The Fourth Protocol,'' said he was swamped
with offers from Soviet publishers.
   ``I've been offered so many things,'' he said. ``But it's hard to
make deals because how are you going to get paid?''
   The Soviet ruble is not freely convertible into other world
currencies, which makes it difficult for Soviet companies to import
goods.
   Still, Kotick said, Soviet publishers are clearly getting good at
``Western wheeling and dealing.''
   This was the first of the biennnial fairs since new rules came
into effect allowing individual Soviet publishers to form direct
ties with foreign partners, and the fair's commercial atmosphere
brought praise from the youth newspaper Komsomolskaya Pravda.
   The event has become a real fair instead of an ``exhibit'' of
forbidden fruit, it said, and Soviet publishers have already
received orders for about 2.5 million books.
   The official news agency Tass said not a single book intended for
the fair had been confiscated. But Levkov said one book he had
planned to bring, an obscene epic poem written in the 18th century,
was vetoed by fair organizers beforehand.
   For all its changes, one tradition of the fair held true:
larceny. Vendors reported their books were disappearing at record
rates.
   But Kotick said he couldn't blame Soviet readers hungry for
literature.
   ``It's like a starving man with bread,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
