<FIRST>r i AM-Brazil-Crash     09-13 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Crash,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Paper: Pilot Set Wrong Course Before Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pilot of a domestic jetliner
noted he had set a wrong course, then began sobbing in desperation
before his aircraft crashed into the Amazon jungle, a newspaper said
Wednesday.
   The cockpit voice recorder from the Boeing 737-200 that crashed
Sept. 3 contradicts statements made later by the pilot, who insisted
he had set a proper course, the O Globo paper said.
   The Varig Airlines flight carrying 54 people crashed in a remote
eastern Amazon region, 1,100 miles from its destination of Belem.
Twelve people on board were killed.
   The newspaper said its account of the voice recorder came from an
unidentified pilot taking part in an investigation of the crash. The
contents of both the voice recorder and the flight-data recorder
have not been released.
   ``On the black box, you hear the pilot say he made a mistake with
the course, and then his desperate weeping,'' O Globo quoted the
investigating official as saying.
   Pilot Cezar Garcez, a 32-year-old Air Force veteran, said after
the crash that he had set the correct course and that his
instruments were working properly.
   The newspaper said the investigating official confirmed a report
by passenger Epaminondas Chaves, who said Garcez told him he had set
an incorrect course.
   ``When he perceived the error in his computerized plan, he could
have used his air charts, which should always be consulted, but they
were folded when the plane crashed,'' the investigating pilot told O
Globo.
   Other pilots flying in the area when the Boeing got lost said
Garcez tuned his radio to a soccer game after he took off. Garcez
denied it.
</TEXT>
