<FIRST>r i AM-Refugees-Poland     09-13 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Refugees-Poland,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>East Germans Take Refuge in West German Embassy in Poland</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Refugees, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dozens of East Germans have taken refuge in
the West German Embassy in Warsaw, state television reported
Wednesday.
   The news program Telexpress said there are about 50 East Germans
in the embassy, according to unofficial figures.
   It broadcast pictures of the refugees in the embassy courtyard,
including children at play.
   ``Not long ago this building was under a siege of Poles seeking
visas. After Budapest and Prague, East German escapees are seeking
shelter in the West German Embassy in Warsaw,'' the news program
said.
   It was referring to East Germans who this summer occupied West
German missions in Hungary and Czechoslovakia in hopes of being able
to emigrate to the West.
   Risking censure from its Warsaw Pact allies and courting praise
from the West, Hungary has opened its borders and allowed more than
10,000 East Germans to cross into Austria. Most have headed for West
Germany.
   But in Czechoslovakia, about 250 of 400 refugees holed up in the
embassy compound gave up Tuesday and left after being promised they
would not be punished and would be allowed to apply to emigrate
legally.
   Polish media have reported on the exodus, but there has been no
comment from Poland's government, the first East bloc administration
led by non-communists. Hungary also is pressing for major reforms,
but East German remains one of the most rigidly controlled states
and refuses to consider demands for change sweeping the communist
world.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890913-0167 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 2005EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Poland     09-13 0522</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0540</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Government Moves In, Gears Up For Poland's Problems</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki on
Wednesday convened the East bloc's first cabinet led by
non-Communists, and the Communist president urged support for it
from all sides.
   Mazowiecki, whose Solidarity-dominated Cabinet was approved by
parliament Tuesday, received a letter expressing support and loyalty
from 54 members of the security forces in southern Poland.
   Other offers of support came from the Communist-dominated trade
union OPZZ and Communist Party chief Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski, who
said the Communists would offer ``constructive criticism.''
   The Cabinet, known as the Council of State, met for three hours
to discuss coordinating the various economic ministries, the
government press office said. It named Labor Minister Jacek Kuron, a
veteran Solidarity activist, to handle contacts with trade unions,
the communique said.
   The Cabinet also met with Communist President Wojciech
Jaruzelski, who urged all Poles to support it.
   ``The fact that we are sitting here together may be seen by
someone as a joke of history, and by someone else as the logic of
history,'' said Jaruzelski in comments carried by television. ``Most
important today is that this experiment is successful. There are big
hopes that it will.''
   Jaruzelski imposed martial law in 1981 in an effort to quash
Solidarity. However, earlier this year, he urged the legalization of
the independent labor movement and its participation in government
to gain backing for tough economic policies.
   Rakowski, a former prime minister, later said in a TV address
that the ``party is obliged to support this government, but we
(party) will not resign from constructive criticism.''
   He called for a renewal of the party, saying Communists must
forget their former monopoly on power and ``say goodbye to ...
remnants of outdated doctrines.''
   For the first time in any Soviet bloc country, the Communists are
losing control of the vast ministerial bureaucracies and power for
political appointments.
   Solidarity has vowed personnel decisions based on competence and
commitment to reform, and no ``witch hunt.''
   A parliamentary commission overseeing the activities of the
Interior Ministry met Wednesday and agreed to review 93 cases of
alleged crimes during Communist control.
   The Communists only control four of the 24 seats on the Council
of Ministers but retain power over the police and military.
   Solidarity has 12 votes, including Mazowiecki's. The independent
foreign minister, Krzysztof Skubiszewski, likely is sympathetic to
their point of view.
   Four other posts went to the United Peasant Party and three to
the Democrats, smaller parties that ended their communist alliance
to form a parliamentary majority with Solidarity last month.
   Finance Minister Leszek Balcerowicz said it would take time
before the Cabinet could begin the radical changes it pledged in an
effort to pull Poland out of economic decline.
   Balcerowicz said Poland's triple-digit inflation must be curbed
but in such a way that ``we don't stop our (government's) activities
in the first or second week.''
   ``I don't think it is possible ... to try to make a radical
anti-inflation operation overnight. The risk of social consequences
due to the economic effects would be excessive.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890913-0168 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 1644EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Governors-Education     09-13 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Governors-Education,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governors Meet With Educators to Discuss Summit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAMARA HENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The two governors leading preparations for the
education summit insisted Wednesday that school reform is everyone's
business and politics should not enter discussions with President
Bush later this month.
   ``I really do believe this is a national security issue and
therefore I believe we should have a bipartisan national plan to
rescue the country's educational system and preserve opportunities
for American kids for the 21st century. I believe that,'' said
Arkansas Gov. Bill Clinton.
   South Carolina Gov. Carroll Campbell agreed. ``It is a national
summit, not a federal summit. This is a summit to focus on ... the
role of the federal government.''
   Campbell, a Republican, and Clinton, a Democrat who already has
begun to implement cutting-edge programs to improve education in his
state, held a day-long hearing to gather ideas and information from
educators, business leaders, government officials and others on
possible topics for the summit set for Sept. 27-28 in
Charlottesville, Va.
   Panelists generally agreed with the governors that the various
groups involved with education should devise national standards and
goals to be presented to Bush for his endorsement and support.
   However, Clinton and Campbell conceded to reporters that the
president has not agreed with the approach.
   ``We're still in negotiations and discussions with the White
House,'' said Clinton, warning against negative speculations on the
outcome of the summit. ``We are going to do this. This hasn't been
done before. We are doing our best in good faith to say what ...
issues ... ought to be raised and to let other people come in here
and say that.''
   Asked if there is fear that the president may use the summit ``as
a substitute for serious action, rather than a first step for
serious action,'' Clinton responded, ``I think it would be wrong to
have any presumptions about it one way or the other on this. I think
the fact that he's been willing to call us together will go down to
his credit.''
   However, Clinton added, ``I think that if he does try to play
politics _ and I'm not suggesting that he is _ I think that it's a
trap. I think once you pick up this ball, you pretty well got to run
with it. If you try to put it down after the summit's over, then I
think you have dashed expectations, disappointed people, a divided
country, people disoriented.
   ``I think he has made a decision that he will have to live with
and that decision is to assume some personal responsibility for the
future of the quality of education. We have to assume his good
faith,'' concluded Clinton.
   The areas in which national goals could be set, the governors
said, include reducing school dropout rates, making sure every child
is prepared to attend school, decreasing illiteracy among
working-age Americans, raising standards in science and math and
increasing high school graduation rates.
   ``I don't think that we have any magical cure but I do think that
when we finish this process of pouring all the thought and ideas
into the funnel, that at the other end we will be able to come out
with a little clearer focus of where we want to go as a nation, and
in the states,'' said Campbell.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
