<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 1645EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u p AM-DetroitMayor     09-13 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Detroit Mayor,0510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Experts: Coleman Young Well Positioned to Win Fifth Term</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Primary Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA WISNIEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Coleman Young is heavily favored to win an
unprecedented fifth term after a primary in which he vanquished his
most dangerous opponent, political experts said Wednesday.
   Young easily led a field of 13 candidates in Tuesday's
non-partisan election and will face second-place finisher Tom Barrow
in a November runoff.
   Barrow, who was badly defeated by Young in the 1985 mayor's race,
outpolled U.S. Rep. John Conyers, who was seen was a potentially
stronger candidate and had the support of the Rev. Jesse Jackson.
   Those familiar with the city's politics said Conyers, a 13-term
congressman with a national reputation, ruined his chances by
entering the race late and running a disorganized, ineffective
campaign.
   ``Conyers shot himself in the foot by making derogatory remarks
about city leaders. His campaign had no content, no issues,'' said
Wilbur Rich, an associate professor of political science at Wayne
State University and the author of a biography on Young.
   At a news conference, Conyers defended his strategy, saying,
``Campaigns by their nature are disorganized.'' However, asked what
he would have done differently, he said, ``I would have started
earlier.''
   Barrow, 40, began campaigning for this year's race soon after
losing to Young in 1985. Conyers entered a day before the filing
deadline in May.
   Most observers believe that the 71-year-old Young is a shoo-in to
win on Nov. 7 unless Barrow comes up with a secret strategy or the
mayor makes a major blunder.
   The Rev. Jim Holley, a well-known Detroit activist who remained
neutral in the primary, said Barrow has limited appeal among average
residents of the nation's sixth largest city, with most of his
support coming from white voters and ``Buppies,'' black urban
professionals.
   ``He's going to have to spend eight weeks demonstrating to the
grass-roots people he is concerned,'' Holley said.
   Rich said Barrow ``still needs to find out how government
works.'' He referred to a campaign blunder in which Barrow promised
to appoint a deputy mayor for education, apparently unaware that the
mayor doesn't have authority over the Board of Education.
   Barrow, nephew of the late prize fighter Joe Louis, hasn't paid
his dues, said Tom Turner, secretary-treasurer of AFL-CIO in Detroit
and a Democratic Party leader.
   ``Young has the kind of charisma and personality that he is able
to get a lot of industry and business people to do things in the
city of Detroit,'' Turner said. ``I'm not sure Tom Barrow is
sophisticated enough to do those kind of things.''
   Conyers may suffer next year if he seeks a 14th term in Congress,
Turner added.
   ``Once you attempt to take on someone like Coleman Young, you are
very vulnerable, and next year a lot of people will be going after
his seat,'' he said. ``Conyers never really was organized enough to
take a comprehensive program to the citizens of Detroit.''
</TEXT>
