<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 1654EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Education 1stLd-Writethru a0684 09-13 0716</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Education, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0684,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Educators Urge National Consensus on Education Goals</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 3 grafs of governors' comments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Educators urged President Bush on Wednesday to
use his upcoming education summit with governors as a springboard to
achieve a new national consensus on what children should learn.
   Bush joined Education Secretary Lauro F. Cavazos in the 45-minute
brainstorming session at the White House with leaders of 17 national
education organizations.
   Bush, who has said he wants to be ``the education president,''
has already decided not to invite them or any other education
experts to participate in his Sept. 27-28 meeting with the governors
in Charlottesville, Va.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Bush wants the
governors ``to help develop a set of realistic goals for the nation
in education.''
   ``The president believes that the nation's education system needs
more accountability in terms of student achievement. He will suggest
the need for a results-oriented education system and ask the
governors for their ideas to make education meet those goals in a
more effective manner,'' said Fitzwater.
   But Bush likely will propose the goals not at the end of the
meeting but ``at a later date,'' Fitzwater said.
   If the educators were miffed at their exclusion from the summit,
they weren't showing it as they emerged from the Roosevelt Room of
the White House.
   Keith Geiger, the new president of the National Education
Association, said, ``The major overall theme was that the president
could lead in a national role of setting (educational) goals for
this country.''
   That could include spelling out what ``youngsters need to know in
order to graduate from high school,'' said Geiger.
   Albert Shanker, his counterpart at the American Federation of
Teachers, cautioned, ``There will be a tremendous letdown if the
summmit takes place and turns out to be a mere media event and
doesn't come up with anything that's substantive.''
   Shanker said Washington doesn't need to establish a national
curriculum, but must be concerned about the percentage of high
school graduates capable of reading and writing at advanced levels.
   Cavazos noted that many governors were holding their own
pre-summit meetings to canvass experts for advice, and he emphasized
that the Charlottesville meeting was ``only a start.''
   ``It's the beginning ... of an opening dialogue, not only with
the governors, but with all of the people, with the teachers, with
the educators, with the students, parents,'' said Cavazos.
   Cavazos said the Bush administration aims to move education
``back to the forefront'' of national attention.
   The former university president said he expects the summit to
produce a ``commitment at the national level to truly restructure
the educational system in America.''
   Cavazos, who has complained that school reform has produced only
meager improvements, said, ``Everyone in that room knows what it
takes. ... The fundamental question is why hasn't it happened.''
   ``I think it is a question of leadership to be provided by the
president and the governors in turn at their states, and the
national momentum,'' the education secretary said.
   Geiger's invitation to participate in the parley with the
president was the first for an NEA chief executive since the Carter
years.
   Last month, Bush remarked that the NEA has been ``frustrated with
me for evermore.''
   ``They've opposed me every time I've ever run for office that I
can remember, and so what's new? I mean, they've got their approach
to education and I've got mine _ and I am right and they are
wrong,'' the president said Aug. 23.
   Geiger said he personally thanked Bush for the invitation.
   ``We will disagree. We will always disagree, but I think we will
be able to work with the administration,'' the union head said.
   Meanwhile, two of the governors leading the preparations for the
summit said educational excellence is too crucial to the nation's
future to let politics enter into the discussions with Bush.
   Arkansas Gov. Bill Clinton told reporters, ``I really do believe
this is a national security issue ... we should have a bipartisan
national plan to rescue the country's educational system.''
   Clinton and Gov. Carroll Campbell of South Carolina said the
summit sessions could set goals in areas such as reducing dropout
rates, cutting adult illiteracy and raising high school graduation
rates.
</TEXT>
