<FIRST>r a AM-CityDrugTests     09-13 0572</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-City Drug Tests,0590</SECOND>
<HEAD>All North Chicago Workers Tested Under New Drug Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mayor of North Chicago was the first in line
when a drug testing program for all 160 city workers got under way,
a program authorities called the first of its kind in the nation.
   Critics suspect it is unconstitutional.
   The program is aimed at creating a drug-free workforce and
setting an example for the community, said Mayor Bobby Thompson.
   President Bush ``just mentioned that government has to get
involved (in the drug war) in his speech the other day, so we were
one step ahead of him,'' Thompson said in a telephone interview.
   From office clerks to aldermen, 63 employees in North Chicago _ a
middle-class community of 18,500 about 25 miles north of Chicago _
were tested last Friday, and the remainder were to be tested
Thursday, Thompson said.
   Those who test positive for drug or alcohol use will be offered
help but not fired. Any employee who tests positive a second time
will be subject to dismissal, the mayor said.
   Employees must sign a consent form before they are tested, and
all have agreed to do so, he said.
   ``If they choose not to be tested, there's nothing you can do.
But that's grounds for suspicion,'' Thompson said ``The person is
definitely watched, because what do you have to hide?''
   North Chicago Police Chief Ernest Fisher said he thinks the city
is the first in the nation with such a testing program.
   Larry Cirignano, spokesman for U.S. drug czar William Bennett,
agreed, saying: ``I don't think anybody has it for all city
employees.''
   The program is allowed under a new ordinance that calls for
mandatory drug testing ``only where there's reasonable suspicion''
that an employee is using drugs, said Bob Long, an attorney for
North Chicago.
   ``I think most city employees have followed the lead of the mayor
and all the top administration in city government,'' he said. ``I'm
not aware of anyone who's declined.''
   But a few workers have questioned the constitutionality of the
new law and contacted the American Civil Liberties Union, which is
investigating, said ACLU attorney Alan Chen.
   The problem is not how the law is written, but rather the way
city administrators have described the tests publicly and to
employees, Chen said.
   ``The way it's been characterized by the city is that they are
mandatory,'' he said.
   ``If it were mandatory policy ... our position would be that it
was blatantly unconstitutional,'' he said.
   ``Obviously there are many reasons somebody would and could
refuse to submit voluntarily to this kind of test,'' including
privacy concerns, he said.
   If the ACLU determines that employees are being coerced into
taking the tests, ``we would seriously consider taking action
immediately'' to halt the program, Chen said.
   The idea for the program arose three years ago when North Chicago
began drug tests for all prospective city employees, Thompson said.
   ``We ran into so many people who were users at that time ... (we)
decided that maybe we'd check into this further.''
   The ordinance, passed by the City Council on Aug. 21, is based on
a contract that already governed the city's police department and
allows tests to be administered up to four times a year, the mayor
said. No decision has been made on how frequently the tests will be
given to other city workers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
