<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Azerbaijan     09-13 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Azerbaijan,0311</SECOND>
<HEAD>Azerbaijani Rally Told Legislature Will Review Their Demands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tens of thousands of people were told at a
Wednesday night rally in Baku, Azerbaijan, the communist authorities
had agreed to consider ethnic demands that touched off a widespread
strike, a witness said.
   Ali Aliev, a member of the grass-roots People's Front group who
attended the rally in the southern republic's capital, said speakers
announced that Azerbaijan's Supreme Soviet, the legislature, will
review the demands Friday.
   He said in a telephone interview the legislature will consider
pressing for an end to the special status given to the disputed
Nagorno-Karabakh region in January; adopting a law on the republic's
sovereignty; pressing for release of ``political prisoners;'' and
granting the People's Front legal status.
   The Kremlin took Nagorno-Karabakh out of Azerbaijan's control to
try to settle a dispute with Armenia over its jurisdiction.
   Azerbaijanis claim the mountainous enclave is theirs, but
Armenians say it is part of their historical homeland and want to
annex it. The region is 75 percent ethnic Armenian although it lies
in Azerbaijan.
   The dispute led to violence that killed about 100 people and
forced huundreds of thousands to flee their homes. A curfew was
imposed in Armenia and Azerbaijan to stop the unrest. Aliev said the
agreement announced Wednesday and signed by Azerbaijani party chief
Rakhman Vezirov asks the Supreme Soviet to consider lifting the
curfew.
   The accord came after three days of talks between Azerbaijani
officials and People's Front representatives, Aliev said.
   The People's Front led a strike over the issues that began Sept.
4 and silenced factories, stores and public transportation in the
mainly Moslem republic on the Caspian Sea. The Front called off the
walkout on Monday when it appeared its demand to have the Supreme
Soviet act on the dispute would be met.
</TEXT>
