<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 2036EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-Nigeria     09-13 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Nigeria,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drug Treaty Signed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh and Nigeria's
justice minister Wednesday signed a law-enforcement mutual aid
treaty that officials said would help fight drug trafficking through
that African nation.
   The agreement provides for the production of witnesses,
documents, financial records or other evidence located in one nation
that is needed in the other country for a criminal investigation.
   Both countries agreed to help each other locate suspects, make
searches and seize assets from criminal enterprises.
   The agreement is the first of its kind that Nigeria has signed
with any other nation, said Prince Bola Ajibola, the Nigerian
minister of justice. It is the 14th between the United States and
another country.
   ``Every time we sign a mutual legal assistance treaty, the world
gets smaller and more precarious for drug dealers,'' Thornburgh said
after the signing. ``With each treaty signed we make it harder for
drug dealers to high from international justice.''
   Nigeria is a major transhipment point for Middle East heroin
bound for Europe and the United States.
   Similar treaties are in force between the United States and
Switzerland, the Netherlands, Italy and Turkey. Six others are
awaiting ratification by the Senate.
   Agreements with Colombia and Morocco have been ratified by the
Senate but not yet put into force.
   Another was recently signed with Jamaica but has not been
submitted to the Senate for ratification.
   While the treaty will eliminates many legal obstacles for U.S.
prosecutors, corruption in Nigeria is still an impediment to
gathering evidence against Nigerian drug traffickers, said one U.S.
law enforcement official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
