<SECOND>AM-Leland Memorial,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chicago Merc Provides Money For Leland World Hunger Center</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The late Rep. Mickey Leland was eulogized by
Congress Wednesday for ``his quest to end world hunger,'' while the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange donated $100,000 to begin a university
center in his memory.
   ``To have known him is to have been touched by him,'' House
Speaker Tom Foley, D-Wash, said of Leland, who died on a flight to a
remote Ethiopian refugee camp last month.
   ``He never took, he only gave, and he never stopped giving: to
his nation, his state, to his friends, his family,'' Foley said.
   The $100,000 Chicago Mercantile Exchange donation will go to the
Mickey Leland Center on World Hunger, to be founded at Texas
Southern University, the congressman's alma mater, as the first
project of a newly created foundation in Leland's honor.
   Leo Melamed, chairman of the executive committee of the Chicago
Merc, and John Geldermann, chairman of the board, presented a check
for $100,000 to Texas Southern President William H. Harris during a
brief ceremony on Capitol Hill.
   Leland, the founder and chairman of the House Select Committee on
Hunger, was on his sixth trip to Ethiopia last month when his bush
plane slammed into a remote mountain on its way to a refugee camp on
the Sudanese border.
   Rep. Gary Ackerman, D-N.Y., a member of the hunger committee,
said the Leland foundation and university center would focus on the
hungry and the homeless, at home and abroad. He said he is unaware
of any similar university center dedicated to such issues in the
United States, and possibly, the world.
   ``I think it is extremely important we carry on the work and
traditions Mickey Leland cared so much about,'' said House Majority
Whip William H. Gray, D-Pa.
</TEXT>
