<FIRST>u i AM-China     09-13 0639</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China,0660</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Beijing University Head Stresses Political Education</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new president of Beijing University on
Wednesday blamed ousted Communist Party chief Zhao Ziyang and his
predecessor, Hu Yaobang, for the spring democracy movement, which
students from his school helped lead.
   Economist Wu Shuqing said the school is taking steps to prevent a
recurrence of the popular protests, which the army crushed on June
3-4.
   ``There is no place on the university campus for bourgeois
liberalism because it is a political, not an academic question,'' Wu
said in his first interview since being named president last month.
Bourgeois liberalism is a catch-phrase for Western liberal ideas.
   He said the school will hire more teachers of ideology and place
as much emphasis on educating students in Marxist-Leninist theories
as academics.
   Wu attributed student activism last spring to the failure of Zhao
and Hu ``to give enough stress to political and ideological work.''
   Hu was purged in 1987 because of pro-democracy student protests
in the winter of 1986-87. His death on April 15 precipitated the
spring democracy movement. Hundreds of posters went up at Beijing
University, mourning Hu's passing and subtly criticizing the
government.
   The school, considered China's most prestigious, has been the
hardest hit in the crackdown on dissent that began in June.
   Seniors returned to campus this summer for weeks of intensive
political study. Those who did not demonstrate that their thinking
was ideologically correct were not allowed to graduate.
   The freshman class was cut to 600 from a planned 2,100. Students
were ordered to undergo a year of military training before beginning
studies.
   Wu called the training an experiment.
   The beginning of the fall term was delayed until Oct. 14,
apparently to prevent students from disrupting the Oct. 1
celebration of the 40th anniversary of communist rule.
   Some people on campus have said another reason was that political
education among Beijing University teachers was taking longer than
planned. Many of them, particularly younger teachers, joined the
protests and showed sympathy for the students, even in the crackdown.
   However, Wu said, ``I feel the overwhelming majority of Beijing
University's teaching staff support the central authorities and
realize the harm which resulted from the anti-government riots.''
   China's official Xinhua news agency said 3,000 of the school's
12,000 students already have returned to campus.
   Wu, 57, replaced Ding Shisun, who headed the school for four
years and through two major student movements _ the spring protests
and the pro-democracy marches of the winter of 1986-87.
   Unlike other schools, Ding did nothing to stop Beijing University
students from taking the lead.
   Wu said Ding still teaches mathematics. News reports of Ding's
dismissal characterized it as non-political, saying he cited health
reasons.
   The official Beijing Daily newspaper said Wednesday that the
United States is being two-faced in criticizing the imposition of
martial law in Beijing, since America had thriving relations with
Taiwan when that Nationalist Chinese island bastion had martial law.
   ``It was precisely during the period of martial law that Taiwan's
economy and tourist industry, with the great help of the United
States, began to prosper,'' it said.
   Martial law was declared in Beijing on May 20, two weeks before
soldiers ended the student occupation of Tiananmen Square.
   Premier Li Peng said recently martial law must remain for now
because ``bad elements'' who stole military arms during the turmoil
are still at large.
   The Beijing Daily said the United States gave ``extraordinary
support'' in military and economic aid to Taiwan during the time it
was under martial law from 1949 to 1987.
   ``In the eyes of some Americans, whether a country implements
martial law or not is actually immaterial,'' the daily said. Those
who now use martial law to condemn China are ``shameless ... but
after all it is difficult to completely hide the harboring of evil
intentions.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
