<FIRST>r a AM-Elks-Blacks     09-13 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Elks-Blacks,0390</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Black Members Admitted to California Elks Lodge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOMPOC, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of an Elks Lodge voted to admit two
black men whose rejection earlier this year led the national
fraternal organization to change its voting rules.
   The 1,600 members of the lodge, a popular eating and
entertainment center here, voted late Tuesday to admit Ernie
Hutchinson, a 57-year-old Santa Barbara County housing official, and
Joe Martin, a 56-year-old real estate agent.
   Five white candidates also gained admission to the all-male
Benevolent and Protective Order of Elks. No vote tally was released.
   ``I feel very gratified and personally relieved that it's over,''
said Martin. ``Now maybe things can get back to normal and the Elks
can get on with their business of providing scholarships and
performing community service.''
   Martin and Hutchinson will be initiated on Oct. 17, lodge
Secretary Walt Cooperider said.
   Hutchinson, the first of the two blacks candidates to apply to
the lodge founded in 1963, was rejected Jan. 17, and Martin was
rejected later. The two were told that fewer than a dozen members
voted against them.
   The rejections prompted the California chapter of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People to call for a
boycott of the Elks.
   Community groups in this city of 31,000 people about 140 miles
northwest of Los Angeles, including the Lompoc school district,
severed their ties with the organization. About two dozen lodge
members resigned in protest, and the state attorney general's office
said it would investigate the lodge for civil rights violations.
   In July, delegates to the Elks' 125th annual national convention
threw out the old rule, which allowed any three members of a lodge
to reject a candidate and which some said made it difficult for
blacks to join the Elks. Under the new rule, a two-thirds majority
can approve a new member.
   For most of its history, the 1.5 million-member organization has
been all-white. In 1973, it changed its bylaws to include all men,
and blacks have joined other lodges since then.
   The Elks donate their time and money to everything from rodeos to
pancake breakfasts, and local chapters run such projects as
providing college cholarships and funding hot-lunch programs for
senior citizens. Nationally, the club raises millions of dollars for
charity.
</TEXT>
