<FIRST>u i AM-Nicaragua 1stLd-Writethru a0674 09-13 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0674,0511</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ortega Says Washington Blocking Election Contributions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS graf 3 beginning `The article' to CORRECT that article
was published Wednesday. Picks up graf 4 pvs, `The elections ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega accused the
Bush administration of blocking contributions from Europe and Latin
America to finance next year's national elections.
   ``The United States is obstructing the financing ... pressuring a
series of countries in Latin America and Europe so they won't
finance the electoral process,'' the Sandinista party newspaper
Barricada quoted Ortega as saying.
   The article Wednesday did not specify how the United States was
purportedly blocking such aid.
   The elections scheduled for Feb. 25 will cost an estimated $25
million, and foreign aid is essential to cover at least part of that
because of Nicaragua's severe economic crisis.
   Under Nicaraguan law, 50 percent of any U.S. contribution to
opposition candidates must go to the National Election Council,
which is to run the elections.
   The Bush administration wants Congress to appropriate $3 million
for the National Endowment for Democracy, a private non-profit
corporation funded largely by the U.S. government, for the campaign
of Violeta Barrios de Chamorro, the main opposition candidate.
   Ortega said if it wants to donate to Mrs. Chamorro's campaign, it
should appropriate $6 million and share it with the National
Elections Council.
   Mrs. Chamorro, publisher of the opposition newspaper La Prensa,
is running on a ticket with Virgilio Godoy of the Liberal
Independent Party for the National Opposition Union, a 14-party
coalition.
   ``The United States' problem is whether to maintain or not its
economic embargo of Nicaragua, but it can't obstruct the inflow of
funds to cover the elections,'' he added.
   Barricada did not say where Ortega made the remarks, but the
presidential press office said Ortega spoke Monday at a gathering of
farmers from cooperatives.
   Ortega also said that if U.S. congressmen want to come to
Nicaragua as election observers, they must first support a Central
American peace plan to dismantle the U.S.-supported Contra rebels by
Dec. 8.
   Ortega and the presidents of Honduras, El Salvador, Costa Rica
and Guatemala agreed Aug. 7 to a plan to dismantle the Contra force.
   In exchange, Ortega has committed his Sandinista National
Liberation Front, a leftist organization in power for the past 10
years, to hold free and fair elections.
   Rep. Mickey Edwards, R-Okla., one of four congressmen who met
Ortega on Sunday, said if the Sandinistas hold fair elections on
schedule, U.S.-Nicaraguan relations will improve regardless of who
wins.
   Otherwise, Edwards warned Nicaragua could expect more aid to the
Contras.
   The congressional delegation was joined by Janet Mullins, an
assistant secretary of state who heads the State Department's
congressional affairs office, the State Department said Wednesday.
   It was the first high-level meeting between the U.S.
administration and the Sandinistas since January 1985, when U.S.
officials accused Nicaragua of negotiating in bad faith. High level
contacts with Nicaragua were barred after that.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
