<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Adoption     09-13 0215</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Adoption,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Proposes Tax Breaks in Some Adoption Cases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush sent Congress legislation
Wednesday to provide tax breaks to parents who adopt children who
are difficult to place for reasons such as physical or mental
handicaps or age.
   ``We are here to take action to encourage more Americans to adopt
and to adopt children with physical, mental and emotional
disabilities,'' Bush said in a ceremony in the Roosevelt Room to
highlight the measures.
   Bush, who has an adopted grandchild of his own, said ``those who
adopt are giving far more than they receive.'' He said there are
30,000 ``special-needs'' children available for adoption.
   Bush first revealed his plan in his Feb. 9 address to Congress
outlining his budget proposals.
   His proposal would provide a $3,000 tax deduction to families for
costs incurred in adopting a special-needs child. Those expenses
largely are associated with legal costs, court fees, transportation
and social service reviews.
   A separate measure would provide additional benefits for federal
employees who adopt such children. During a four-year demonstration
program, federal employees would be eligible for reimbursement by
the government of up to $2,000 for expenses incurred in adopting a
special-needs child.
   As an alternative to abortion, Bush has proposed that mothers put
unwanted children up for adoption.
</TEXT>
