<FIRST>r w AM-Dole-Poland     09-13 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dole-Poland,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Labor Department to Send Advisers to Poland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Labor Secretary Elizabeth Dole said Wednesday
that her department will send a team to Poland to advise the new
government and Solidarity leadership on Western-style labor
relations and programs.
   ``We're ready as soon as they say to come,'' Mrs. Dole said after
announcing the plan in a speech to the Northeast-Midwest Leadership
Council. The visit probably will begin in a few weeks, she said.
   Mrs. Dole and her husband, Senate GOP leader Bob Dole, visited
Poland last month and met with high-ranking officials in and out of
the government, including Solidarity leader Lech Walesa.
   The Labor Department visit will cost about $4 million, which will
come from the $100 million aid package President Bush has promised
Poland, Mrs. Dole said.
   It hasn't been decided who will be on the team but members
probably will include representatives of business and organized
labor along with department officials, she said.
   They will discuss such matters as job training and referral,
unemployment insurance and collective bargaining, she said. Other
details have not been worked out.
   Mrs. Dole said Polish leaders were eager for guidance during her
visit and voiced concern about how needed changes in their economy
would affect workers _ particularly if jobs are eliminated.
   ``There's no safety net for workers in Poland, and obviously
they're going through this very tough period, from essentially a
sheltered economy to a market economy,'' she said. ``Again and again
we had that message that they're counting on us.''
</TEXT>
