<FIRST>r w AM-US-Soviet-Elections     09-13 0684</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Soviet-Elections,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Said to Be Concerned Democracy `Moving Too Fast'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet elections are hampered by vague rules
and the fear of officials that democracy ``might be moving too
fast,'' says the chairman of the Federal Election Commission, who on
Wednesday detailed help his group is giving the Soviets to develop
their voting system.
   ``The fact is that it is hard to find the procedures written down
... Procedure was kind of being developed as they went along,''
Federal Election Commission Chairman Danny L. McDonald told a news
conference.
   McDonald, who led a commission team to the Soviet Union June
4-14, said that in his discussions with Soviet officials, ``time and
time again I got the distinct impression ... that even the most
ardent critics of the general process ... were concerned that the
process might be moving too fast.''
   The FEC chairman also said the Soviets disliked some aspects of
U.S. democracy.
   ``They are astounded at the amount of money that we spend'' and
``astounded by the close scrutiny that politicians have (to undergo)
in this country,'' McDonald said.
   Commission members, releasing a report on their visit, also found
that although Soviet leaders wanted to preserve the political
monopoly of the Communist Party, many Soviet politicians and
citizens favored a Western-style system with several parties.
   Members of the Soviet Central Electoral Commission ``are not
interested in many parties, they made that very clear, that there
was the Communist Party, and that there may be divisions within it,
but they are not looking at a whole variety of political parties,''
said Lee Ann Elliott, vice chairman of the U.S. commission.
   ``Many of the candidates'' elected to the Soviet parliament last
spring do favor a multiparty system, she said. ``But the people who
are running the elections at the moment worry that with more than
one party, they would not be able to function, if that happens too
fast.''
   The report dealt largely with balloting for the Congress of
Peoples Deputies last March, in which 2,250 legislators were
elected. Some Communist Party leaders were defeated and the results
were widely interpreted as an embarrassment for old-style party
apparatchiks.
   The report left the impression that Soviet democracy is now
developing so fast that it has produced confusion on virtually every
level, a feeling that was reflected in comments by team members at
the new conference.
   Procedures are poorly understood, and varied from place to place,
said McDonald.
   Soviet officials were ``not quite clear how far they wanted to go
and what the end result might be... there is a real battle going
on'' over who should control local elections in the 15 Soviet
republics, he said.
   No date has been set for those elections, and it is not clear
whether they will be run by the Central Electoral Commission or
local officials, commissioners said. Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev announced last July that the local elections, which had
been postponed from the fall till next spring, might be held by the
end of this year.
   ``The latest word is that it might be in December,'' said
McDonald.
   ``In terms of the electoral process, they are going to have to
turn a lot over to the locals, because they simply don't have the
wherewithal at the national level,'' he said.
   The confusion was greatest outside of major population centers,
said Richard W. Soudriette, the director of the International
Foundation for Electoral Systems, a non-profit private group that
helped sponsor the study.
   Soviet officials told the team that ``they did have quite a bit
of difficulty in some of the outlying republics. ... The farther
that you got away from the metropolitan areas, Leningrad, Moscow,
Kiev ... they increasingly encountered problems,'' said Soudriette.
   U.S.-Soviet cooperation will continue, the U.S. commissioners
said, as the Americans respond to Soviet requests for copies of
federal and state laws on elections, fund-raising and advertising.
   Late Tuesday, said McDonald, Soviet Embassy officials telephoned
the American commission to relay a request for a Soviet team to
observe local elections in New Jersey and Virginia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
