<HEAD>Diplomat Suspected of Spying Says He Will Write Book</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Felix Bloch, a U.S. diplomat suspected of
spying for Moscow, said in an interview that he plans to write a
book to set the facts straight.
   The Austrian daily Die Presse in its Thursday editions quoted
Bloch as saying he will write a book about the accusations that have
dogged him for months, but the newspaper gave no details.
   Asked if it was likely he would soon prove his innocence, Bloch
was quoted as answering, ``We will see.''
   The 54-year-old Austrian-born diplomat was suspended from the
State Department on June 22. No charges have been brought against
him, but he remains under investigation and surveillance by the FBI.
   In the interview, Bloch also rejected criticism he did not do
enough to stop technology transfer to the East bloc.
   ``I did everything in my power to stop the transfer, and I
succeeded,'' the former No. 2 envoy at the U.S. Embassy in Vienna
was quoted as saying.
