<DOCNO> AP890913-0200 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 1931EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Yugoslavia     09-13 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia,0407</SECOND>
<HEAD>Announces Anti-Inflation Program; 1000s Stage Anti-Government Rallies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yugoslavia announced Wednesday it
will soon introduce a new program to battle a 900 percent annual
inflation rate, the highest in Europe.
   The federal government acted as about 11,000 workers staged
rallies in two Belgrade industrial suburbs to protest steeply
declining living standards and demand a halt in runaway inflation.
   The state news agency Tanjug said new measures will liberalize
imports of cheaper foreign goods to compete with expensive domestic
products, but will apparently not include price or wage freezes. It
did not say when the measures would begin.
   The government also foresees closing all unprofitable state
companies, which would probably lead to huge layoffs, Tanjug said.
About 30 percent of the 6.8 million Yugoslavs who now hold jobs in
state companies operating at a loss could face dismissal.
   Besides inflation, communist Yugoslavia is burdened by a $19
billion foreign debt, a 17 percent unemployment rate and an alarming
increase in labor and ethnic unrest.
   About 10,000 workers at Rakovica chanted anti-government slogans
on Wednesday and hailed Serbian authorities for their support.
Speakers demanded immediate anti-inflation action by the federal
government.
   In Zemun, about 1,000 Zmaj tractor factory workers sent a ``final
warning to the government'' to brake plummeting living standards,
now officially at the mid-1960s level, Belgrade radio reported.
   The rallies appeared to be part of a campaign by leaders of
Serbia, the largest of Yugoslavia's six republics, to unseat the
federal government and Premier Ante Markovic.
   When he became premier in March, Markovic, a Croat, said he would
resign if all six republics do not approve his radical,
market-oriented reforms.
   Economists in this capital say Serbian leaders, headed by
President Slobodan Milosevic, fear a loss of popularity if living
standards drop further and favor short-term austerity measures such
as freezing prices.
   Serbian politicians claim Markovic's economic policies favor
Yugoslavia's economically most developed regions, Slovenia and
Croatia, at the expense of poorer republics such as Serbia.
   The communist leaderships of the republics, divided between
reformers and conservatives, have been unable to agree on whether to
introduce an open, free-market economy and more political pluralism
as a way out of the crisis.
   Serbia's Communist Party went on the record Wednesday as opposing
the political pluralism adopted in the liberal northern region of
Slovenia and advocated by reformists in the remaining republics.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890913-0201 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 1931EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-EmergencyRooms 1stLd-Writethru a0663 09-13 0662</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Emergency Rooms, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0663,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Emergency Room Gridlock _ A Nightmare of Medicare Care</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS last two grafs to CORRECT attribution of last graf to Yeh,
sted report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People seeking treatment in emergency rooms in
many areas of the country are finding a medical gridlock that keeps
patients waiting hours, even days, for hospital beds, emergency
physicians said Wednesday.
   ``We are on the verge of a major crisis,'' said Dr. Stephan G.
Lynn, chairman of an American College of Emergency Physicians task
force on hospital overcrowding and director of emergency medicine at
St. Luke's-Roosevelt Hospital Center in New York City.
   The pressure on hospital emergency rooms is coming from the
growing AIDS epidemic, increased illegal drug use and an estimated
37 million Americans who have no health insurance and for whom the
emergency room is often their only entry to the health care system,
he said.
   This burden is exacerbated by medical staff shortages, financial
pressures that are leading a growing number of hospitals to close
their doors, and an inadequate number of nursing home beds, Lynn
said.
   In some cases, patients in emergency rooms in New York City have
waited for in-patient hospital beds for more than a week, Lynn said.
And though the problem is most critical in the Northeast and on the
West Coast, a survey shows emergency rooms across the country are
backed up.
   In a survey, 41 state chapters of the American College of
Emergency Physicians reported overcrowding problems in emergency
rooms in their states. Nine reported no backup problems: Idaho,
Minnesota, Nebraska, New Hampshire, New Mexico, North Dakota,
Oregon, Utah and Wyoming.
   ``This is affecting everybody, from the drug abuser to the
homeless to the business executive,'' said Dr. Charlotte S. Yeh, who
sits on the college's board and is chief of emergency medicine at
the Newton-Wellesley Hospital in Newton, Mass.
   Lynn and Yeh said it is not known whether extended emergency room
stays have led to more patient deaths, but they said the quality of
care these patients receive often is marginal.
   ``The lights never go out. The noise never turns off. Meals are
served, but on an irregular basis and rarely are as palatable or
warm as they are on the in-patient side,'' Lynn said.
   ``The patient has no access to a telephone, and access to a TV is
beyond thought,'' he said. ``The patient is lucky if they are able
to see their visitors, and they spend their entire stay lying on a
stretcher with a mattress that is two-inches thick.''
   ``That level of care is inadequate,'' he said. ``Emergency
departments were not designed and are not equipped or staffed to
provide intensive care services or in-patient services.''
   At Harbor UCLA Medical Center in Los Angeles, the emergency room
is so overcrowded it is closed to ambulance traffic 25 percent of
the time, said Dr. Robert Hockberger, chairman of the Department of
Emergency Medicine.
   ``That results in ambulances wandering around the city trying to
find emergency departments that are open,'' he said. ``This is
starting to affect not only the poor barrio gang member who got
stabbed in the midst of a crack deal, but it's also affecting the
50-year-old, quarter-million-dollar-a-year businessman.''
   Cities on the two coasts have been hit most severely by the
overcrowding problem, but the college's chapters in West Virginia,
North Carolina, Alabama and Alaska said ``overcrowding is not simply
a problem of this nation's cities,'' according to a draft report by
the task force.
   ``It is ultimately going to come down to the public at large to
decide: If you want care when you want it and where you want it,
you're going to have to put in the resources for it,'' said Yeh.
``If you don't put in the resources, you're going to have to change
your expectations and expect the wait, and expect the fact that
you're going to have limited care and limited access.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890913-0202 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 1932EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Namibia 1stLd-Writethru a0701 09-13 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0701,0662</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nujoma Returning Despite Assassination of Colleague</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with Nujoma lived chiefly in Angola.
Picks up graf 4 pvs, `Posters appeared ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HEIDI VON EGIDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of Namibia's independence
movement will end a 30-year exile and return to his homeland despite
the assassination of another nationalist leader, officials said
Wednesday.
   A Namibian newspaper on Wednesday said callers claiming to
represent a white supremacist group claimed responsibility for the
killing Tuesday of Anton Lubowski, an official of the South-West
Africa People's Organization.
   Sam Nujoma, president of the nationalist group, will return
Thursday even though there have been threats against his life, the
organization said in a statement. Nujoma has lived principally in
Angola during his self-imposed exile.
   Posters appeared in Windhoek on Wednesday with a photograph of
Nujoma and a target superimposed on his face.
   Nujoma is returning to Namibia to take charge of his group's
campaign for elections scheduled for early November, a prelude to
Namibian independence from South Africa.
   South Africa, which ruled Namibia 74 years, has agreed to
implement independence in the territory under United Nations
supervision. Independence is expected early next year.
   Lubowski, a Namibian lawyer and the nationalist group's
top-ranking white official, was shot in the head outside his home in
a Windhoek suburb.
   The 37-year-old Lubowksi was widely known abroad, and his killing
was condemned by officials from the United States, Britain, West
Germany, Norway, Sweden, amd Zambia, among others.
   Gwen Lister, editor of The Namibian, said she received two phone
calls Wednesday from men saying they belonged to the White Wolves
and that the white supremacist organization killed Lubowski.
   Ms. Lister said one of the callers also threatened her for
supporting the the South-West Africa People's Organization, the
black-dominated movement that waged a 23-year guerrilla war against
South African rule of Namibia.
   Men identifying themselves as Whites Wolves have carried out
several attacks on blacks and anti-apartheid activists in South
Africa. Police say they have not been able to prove the organization
exists.
   The South-West Africa People's Organization's election
directorate, of which Lubowski was a member, said in a statement
that ``the deliberate and well-calculated killing'' was intended to
create instability in the period prior to the elections.
   ``Such a cowardly act is part of the notorious scheme aimed at
scaring Namibian patriots from giving a hero's welcome to their
national leader (Nujoma),'' the statement said. ``It is also aimed
at frightening the white community in Namibia, which has been
increasingly joining SWAPO over the past weeks and months.''
   Fighting between nationalist guerrillas and the South African-led
security forces ended in April. Since then, there have been only
isolated violent incidents.
   Lubowski died only hours after Namibia's nine largest political
parties, including the South-West Africa People's Organization,
signed a code of conduct for the elections that prohibits violence.
   ``I wish to assure Namibians that their desire for a peaceful
transition to independence, too long delayed, cannot and will not be
frustrated by the increasingly desperate acts of a few extremists,''
said Martti Ahtisaari, head of the U.N. operation in Namibia.
   The South African-appointed administrator of Namibia, Louis
Pienaar, said authorities ``will not allow circumstances of anarchy
to develop in the run-up to the election.'' He promised tight
security for Nujoma's return.
   Pienaar said the assassination was part of a ``spiral of
violence'' that included the fatal stoning of a white police officer
during the weekend by a crowd of blacks.
   Lubowski announced in 1984 that he had joined the legal political
wing of South-West Africa People's Organization.
   Since then, right-wing newspapers often ridiculed him in stories
and cartoons critical of the leftist-oriented organization. He had
received numerous death threats.
   Police offered what they called a ``substantial'' reward for
information about the killing, but did not disclose a specific
figure.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890913-0203 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 2104EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-TugboatPageant     09-13 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tugboat Pageant,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebecca P. Crowned `Miss Tugboat'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DARLENE E. SUPERVILLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERSEY CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With former Miss America host Bert Parks
at the helm as emcee, a 105-foot, blue-and-white tugboat was crowned
the nation's most beautiful tug on Wednesday.
   As part of a day-long celebration of the resurgence of the city's
waterfront section, 13 tugboats chugged into New York Harbor for the
first Tugboat Beauty Contest.
   The nautical show coincided with this year's Miss America
Pageant, which will be televised live from Atlantic City on
Saturday. It also was used to promote the often-overlooked tugboat
industry.
   ``It's a first for me,'' said the 74-year-old Parks, who has
hosted everything from mother-daughter beauty contests to cat and
dog competitions.
   Parks hosted the Miss America Pageant for 25 years.
   ``Beauty is all in the eye of the beholder, whether it's a cat or
a tugboat or a lady,'' he said. ``You have to have a sense of humor
about it.''
   Each of the aquatic beauties sauntered down the ``aisle,'' a
channel from Jersey City leading into the harbor, as Parks, who did
not have a chance to croon the popular Miss America theme, belted
out the boat's vital statistics to more than 1,000 onlookers.
   The boats were judged by Jersey City Mayor Gerald McCann, Hudson
County Executive Robert Janiszewski and a representative from the
Port Authority of New York and New Jersey. The judges looked at
their trim, sparkle, manueverability, charm and overall appearance.
   Once in the harbor, each tugboat turned around to demonstrate her
maneuverability and then strutted her stuff back to the starting
line.
   And when it was over, the blue, white and yellow-trimmed Rebecca
P. was crowned the nation's most beautiful tugboat.
   Rebecca P., a 9-year-old tug from Poling Transportation of Staten
Island, N.Y., won a flag hailing her as the most beautiful tug and
$2,500 for her crew.
   Parks said the contestants and timing of the pageant _ just three
days before Miss America 1990 is crowned _ did not bother him.
   ``This business is so ... strange,'' he said. ``I guess that's
the fascinating part of it. You never know what's going to happen
next.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890913-0204 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 1934EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon 2ndLd-Writethru a0671 09-13 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0671,0617</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Killed in Fighting as Peace Effort Resumes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS graf 5 beginning: `The foreign ...' to UPDATE with foreign
ministers resuming peace effort. Picks up graf 6 pvs, `The envoys ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian and Christian forces battled in and
around Beirut on Wednesday, killing three people and wounding 17.
Arab mediators met in an attempt to revive their stalled peace
effort.
   Police said the casualties raised the toll from six months of
fighting to at least 850 killed and 2,545 wounded.
   A spokesman, who cannot be named under standing regulations, said
Syrians and Christians clashed with artillery, mortars and machine
guns in Beirut, north Lebanon and the mountains on the eastern edge
of the Christian heartland.
   He said residential sectors of the capital, badly hammered since
fighting erupted March 8, were spared in the sporadic clashes.
   The foreign ministers of Saudi Arabia, Morocco and Algeria met in
Saudi Arabia's Red Sea port of Jiddah for 2{ hours late Wednesday,
resuming a peace effort that ran out of steam six weeks ago.
Deliberations were to continue behind closed doors on Thursday.
   The envoys on July 31 blamed Syria for refusing to accept a
timetable for pulling its 40,000 troops from Lebanon.
   Christian leader Gen. Michel Aoun, in what appeared to be a
compromise proposal, said even a partial Syrian withdrawal would
open the way for negotiations on political reforms to end the
14-year-old civil war.
   The Syrians, who consider Lebanon vital to their strategic
defense against Israel, have refused to withdraw.
   Informed sources in Jiddah, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said the Arab mediation committee was considering a peace plan that
calls for a cease-fire and the lifting of blockades by both sides.
   Beirut's independent An-Nahar daily, the leftist As-Safir as well
as Moslem and Christian radio stations said the committee will
declare a cease-fire shortly.
   Several cease-fires called by the Arab League and others have
collapsed amid fierce artillery battles that have driven an
estimated 90 percent of Beirut's 1.5 million people from the city.
   An-Nahar said the nationalist front, a coalition of 18 leftist
and Moslem groups allied with Syria and Iran, was expected to
facilitate the committee's effort by proclaiming a cease-fire in
``the coming hours.''
   The front, formed more than a month ago in an attempt by Syria
and Iran to intensify the pressure on Aoun, generally reflects
Syrian President Hafez Assad's policy in Lebanon.
   But sources in Damascus, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
no cease-fire announcement was imminent and did not indicate any
significant shift in the Syrians' stand.
   An-Nahar said the nationalist front will also lift the maritime
blockade imposed by Syria on the 310-square-mile Christian enclave
in mid-March.
   As-Safir, which is close to Assad's government, said the Arab
foreign ministers meeting in Jiddah will discuss ``complete
stabilization'' of a cease-fire to pave the way for talks between
the warring factions.
   Aoun, a Maronite Catholic, said he was prepared to accept
``radical reforms'' to the political system that has given the
Christians the upper hand in running Lebanon since independence from
France in 1943.
   When the French pulled out, the Christians were considered the
majority. But now the Moslems comprise an estimated 55 percent of
the country's 4 million people and want equal political power.
   Aoun has declared a ``war of liberation'' against the Syrians,
whom, he views as an occupying power.
   Syria sent its troops into Lebanon in June 1976 under an Arab
League peacekeeping mandate. Aoun charges they have abrogated that
mandate by siding with the Moslems.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
