<FIRST>u w AM-Nicaragua-Visas     09-13 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-Visas,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nicaraguan Embassy Denies Visas to Election Observers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nicaragua has denied visas to members of a
privately funded delegation of Americans who wanted to monitor
prepartions for its February national elections, the embassy said
Wednesday.
   ``Our elections are not something to be manipulated by
individuals and groups interested in furthering conflict,'' charge
d'affairs Leonor Arguella de Huper said in announcing that the
Commission on Free and Fair Elections in Nicaragua would not receive
the requested visas.
   The embassy said L. Brent Bozell, president of the conservative
World Freedom Foundation, sponsor of the commission, had just
returned from a visit to Contra camps in Honduras and expressed his
support for the Contras.
   ``It is known that the World Freedom Foundation's sole objective
is to discredit our electoral process and create conditions for a
revival of the Contra war,'' Mrs. Huper said.
   Former Democratic Sen. Gaylord Nelson of Wisconsin, a co-chairman
of the commission, called Mrs. de Huper's statement ``sheer
nonsense.''
   ``This is a bipartisan commission whose sole interest was in
observing and helping to promote free and fair elections in
Nicaragua. It has no other purpose whatsoever,'' Nelson said.
   Commission director Marc Ryan said visas were sought for Nelson;
commission co-chairman Curtin Winsor Jr., a former ambassador to
Costa Rica in the Reagan administration; Sergio Bendixen, a
Democratic political consultant; Alan Keyes, a former assistant
secretary of state in the Reagan administration; and Elaine Kamarck,
a Democratic political activist.
   Ryan, who said he and Bozell also had wanted visas, said the
group might ask Mrs. de Huper to reconsider.
   ``I find it terribly disturbing that the Sandinistas are saying,
basically, you must be vocally anti-Contra to be allowed to observe
this election,'' Bozell said.
   ``As far as I am concerned, I bent over backward trying to find a
glimmer of hope in these elections, but this action by the
Sandinistas is a major nail in the coffin on that expectation.''
   The action came just days after the United States and Nicaragua
had their first high-level contact in nearly five years.
   Janet Mullins, an assistant secretary of state, joined in a
meeting with Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega. Ms. Mullins joined
a congressional delegation for the weekend meeting, which was part
of a visit to several Central American countries, the State
Department said Wednesday.
   High-level contacts were barred by President Reagan in January
1985 after officials accused Nicaragua of negotiating in bad faith
during six-month-long talks. The Bush administration has not
observed a similar policy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
