<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 2115EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-GettyArt     09-13 0205</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Getty Art,0210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Getty Museum to Aunction Gauguin, Other Paintings in London</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The J. Paul Getty Museum of Malibu, Calif., will
sell 15 paintings, mostly impressionist works, in London in late
November, and revenues from the sale are expected to surpass $18
million, Sotheby's aunction house said Wednesday.
   A number of the works hung at Sutton Place, the English Tudor
mansion once occupied by the famous oilman. He was worth $4 billion
when he died there in 1976 at age 83.
   The most important work is ``Breton Boy with a Goose'' by the
French artist Paul Gauguin, painted in 1889. It will be sold on Nov.
28, and is estimated to be worth at least $8 million.
   Other works include a standing nude by Pierre Bonnard, dancers by
Edgar Degas and a landscape by Claude Monet.
   Lori Star, press officer at the Malibu museum, said in a
telephone interview that the paintings to go on sale ``have been
overshadowed by more recent acquisitions.''
   The paintings will go on tour in Stockholm, Sweden; Tokyo; Los
Angeles; and New York before they are sold.
   Fiona James, Sotheby's spokeswoman, said most of the paintings
were purchased by Getty himself and reflect his own taste.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
