<DOCNO> AP890913-0211 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 1943EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-SriLanka     09-13 0615</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0634</SECOND>
<HEAD>Peace Conference Begins Amid Violence in Sri Lanka</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sri Lankan political parties and Tamil
rebel groups opened a conference Wednesday to seek a way to end this
land's ethnic violence that has killed more than 16,000 people.
   However, the same day, reports said 27 more people were killed
and 13 government buildings were burned in the strife.
   A government spokesman said 21 of the country's 27 recognized
political parties attended the conference in Colombo. President
Ranasinghe Premadasa said it was expected to continue through Oct.
12.
   ``I abhor violence. I believe in non-violence. I wish to make a
special appeal to all those outside the democratic process to return
to the mainstream, join the dialogue to jointly search for solutions
to the country's problems,'' Premadasa said in his opening statement
to the conference.
   The appeal was apparently aimed at Sinhalese radicals of the
People's Liberation Front, an ultranationalist guerrilla group
trying to overthrow the government.
   The front boycotted the conference organized by the
Sinhalese-dominated government. However, Bradman Weerakoon, foreign
affairs adviser to the president, said Premadasa was confident the
radicals would attend later meetings.
   More than 16,000 people have died in six years of ethnic violence
on this Indian Ocean island. At least 5,000 of them have been killed
in the two-year-old Sinhalese uprising. A revolt by minority Tamil
secessionists in the northeast has claimed the other lives.
   Delegates at Wednesday's meeting included members of five Tamil
guerrilla groups, among them the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, a
leading group that continued fighting despite a failing peace accord
in 1987.
   ``All political parties and groups who are represented at this
meeting have placed as their first priority the cessation of
violence and restoration of peace and normalcy in our country,''
Premadasa told the 69 conference delegates.
   He said he would consider proposals made by some parties to
restore peace, including formation of a provisional government,
constitutional reforms and replacement of the presidential system
with a British-style parliamentary government.
   ``I am not adverse to change if change is to bring forth desired
results. I believe that we must search for new solutions to the new
problems we face,'' he said.
   Less than an hour before the conference began, a car bomb
exploded in a parking lot in downtown Colombo, shattering some
windows but causing no casualties, police said. No one claimed
responsibility, but police blamed the front.
   A government statement said suspected front members burned 13
government buildings Wednesday in Moneragala district, 100 miles
east of Colombo.
   It said nine bodies of young Sinhalese men were found Wednesday
in Kurunegala district, 85 miles northeast of Colombo.
   Such killings have also been blamed on the Sinhalese opponents of
the government.
   Also Wednesday, four civilians were killed in central Sri Lanka;
six bodies were found near a government-owned housing complex in
Moratuwa, a Colombo suburb; and five burned bodies of Sinhalese
women were found in central Kandy district, the statement said.
   It also said Sinhalese radicals shot and killed three policemen
on a foot patrol Wednesday near Galnewa village, 100 miles north of
Colombo.
   The violence broke out in 1983 with a Tamil insurrection in the
northeast. Tamils, who make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million
people, claim the government deprives them of jobs and education.
   Sinhalese make up 75 percent of the population and control the
government and the military.
   Indian peacekeeping forces came to Sri Lanka under the 1987
accord, but they too have been caught up in the fighting. Sri Lankan
officials say the Indians have agreed to pull out their troops by
the end of the year.
</TEXT>
