<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 1953EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Congress-Drugs 2ndLd-Writethru a0734 09-13 0924</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-Drugs, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0734,900</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democrats, Republicans to Negotiate on Drug Package</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: INSERTS new grafs 6-7: ``Senate Republicans,'' with Dole comment
on negotiations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Democrats, courting a showdown with the
White House, said Wednesday that President Bush's $7.9 billion
anti-drug package was inadequate and vowed to press their own more
costly plan unless Republicans agreed to major expansions.
   The Democrats made their decision in a closed strategy session as
drug coordinator William Bennett continued his defense of the
administration's plan, saying the blueprint was ``our best
assessment'' of what is needed to combat illegal drugs.
   ``Is it impossible to spend more? No,'' Bennett told a House
committee, but added it is unclear where more money could be used
effectively. The Democrats want to up the spending by $2.2 billion.
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, said Democrats
have offered to negotiate on a compromise with the White House and
Republicans.
   ``The president's plan must be improved,'' Mitchell told
reporters. ``Its goals must be set higher. Its strategies to meet
the goals must be changed.''
   Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole of Kansas met with Mitchell and
said afterward that the two sides hoped to begin talks soon.
   ``My own view is that the Bush plan does not need any changes,
but if there are good suggestions and if we get some agreement
between the president and Congress, then obviously that is fine,''
Dole said.
   Democrats emerged from their meeting saying the proposal by Sen.
Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., to add the $2.2 billion to Bush's total by
cutting a half percent from the budgets of other programs had their
support.
   ``If we can't find that in everybody's department, we're not
serious about fighting the war on drugs,'' said Sen. John Breaux,
D-La., predicting that most Democrats would fall into line behind
Byrd's plan.
   ``I think the Democrats want to do something on drugs and they
want to do it now,'' said Sen. Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz.
   Since last week when Bush proposed his $7.9 billion plan to
combat drug abuse next year, Democrats and Republicans have sought
tactical advantages on an issue that polls show is of intense public
concern.
   The White House has signaled it is willing to try to find middle
ground, although the Office of Management and Budget issued a
statement on Tuesday saying that top administration officials would
urge a veto if Democrats passed their own plan intact.
   Elsewhere in Congress, a former worker in a Colombian drug cartel
warned that embattled South American drug dealers might lash out
with terror attacks in the United States.
   ``Some of you may be the victims of attacks and maybe the
president of the United States would be the victim of drug
traffickers,'' Diego Viafara Salinas told the Senate permanent
subcommittee on investigations in comments that paralleled remarks
made earlier in the week by an FBI official.
   He testified behiond a screen to shield his identity while
bodyguards scanned the hearing room.
   Democrats initially criticized the president for proposing new
programs without specifying where much of the money was supposed to
come from. Some said new taxes were needed for any serious anti-drug
effort.
   Byrd, the Senate Appropriations Committee chairman, surprised
Republicans on Tuesday by advancing a proposal to add $3.9 billion
to the $6.2 billion Congress had planned to spend on anti-drug
programs. He proposed raising the money by trimming defense and many
domestic programs by 0.575 percent.
   The $10.1 billion total in Byrd's package would be $2.2 billion
beyond the president's figure. His additional spending would include
$1.1 billion for treatment and prevention programs and $1 billion
for new prisons.
   Republicans, however, say the Byrd plan is too expensive and
would take an unacceptable $1.8 billion bite out of the Pentagon's
budget.
   Bennett told the House Select Committee on Narcotics Abuse and
Control Wednesday that the president's proposal represents ``our
best assessment'' of what is needed.
   The strategy seeks $925 million for treatment, a 53 percent
increase over this year's amount, and $1.2 billion for prevention
and education, a 25 percent increase.
   Bennett said some efforts don't need more money, just more
stringent policies.
   ``School policy _ clear, firm school policy _ is probably about
the most effective thing you can do, and it costs no more to have a
sound policy that to have an unsound policy,'' he said.
   Bennett also defended the way Bush's plan distributes money: 70
percent for law enforcement and 30 percent for education and
treatment. Byrd's plan would be split 53-47 respectively.
   ``It is a function of what we think needs to be done, what needs
to be done now, and what needs to be done by the federal
government,'' Bennett said.
   Meanwhile, Viafara Salinas, a one-time Colombian cartel health
officer who is a federally protected witness, warned senators that
South American drug dealers could spread terror within the United
States and possibly attack officials here if the crackdown
intensifies.
   Another witness testifying from behind a screen, David Wheeler,
the Washington-born son of a U.S. Foreign Service officer, said
wealthy Bolivians have a cocaine cartel that rivals those of
Colombia.
   He said he gained the confidence of cocaine dealers after living
20 years in Mexico, growing marijuana and shipping it to the United
States.
   The cocaine cartels, seeking new ways to smuggle the drug into
this country, are considering buying surplus diesel submarines,
Wheeler testified. He said they are buying land on both sides of the
Southwest border with an eye to tunneling and piping in narcotics.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
