<SECOND>AM-Victim Arrest, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0747,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teenager Risks Arrest to Save Siblings</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 8-10, `Pettway, 35...,' to raise first reference
to Rodman.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVE EPSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-ager called police Wednesday to rescue five
younger siblings from a house containing cocaine and guns even
though he was a fugitive from a New Jersey youth detention center,
police said.
   Police arrested the 16-year-old from Newark but released him
later when New Jersey officials declined to seek his return.
   ``He must have been scared to death,'' said Jill Reilly, a Boston
police spokeswoman.
   The youth called police at about 1 a.m. after he allegedly was
robbed at gunpoint near the home where the children were staying in
Dorchester, a section of Boston where drug-related violence is
common.
   When police arrived, the juvenile told them he was afraid the
children, ages one through 12, were in danger, Reilly said.
   The teen-ager said Jimmy Lee Pettway, 35, who lived in the house,
threatened him with a .22-caliber pistol and grabbed his watch,
Reilly said. Pettway told police he was babysitting the children.
   ``The officers believed the children were in danger,'' Reilly
said, and they entered the house. They found eight grams of cocaine,
scales and ``lots and lots'' of other drug paraphernalia, as well as
several rifles in plain view in a closet, she said.
   Pettway, 35, was charged with armed robbery, carrying a firearm
and possession with intent to distribute drugs, said David Rodman, a
spokesman for the Suffolk County district attorney's office.
   Another man at the scene, James Young, 43, was also charged with
assault with a dangerous weapon, possession of a firearm and
possession with intent to distribute, Rodman said. And a woman at
the scene, Theresa Clark, 22, also known as Claude, the mother of a
2-year-old who was a sixth child in the house, was charged with
possession with intent to distribute and conspiracy to violate drug
laws.
   All three pleaded innocent to the charges and were released on
personal recognizance, Rodman said.
   Police also arrested the 16-year-old who called them, but Rodman
said he was released later Wednesday when New Jersey authorities
declined to seek his return to the state on a robbery charge.
   ``New Jersey said they don't want him, so we let him go,'' Rodman
said. ``He didn't do anything wrong.''
   Officials in the Essex County sheriff's office in New Jersey
would not comment on the case because it involves a juvenile. Newark
police did not return telephone messages.
   Boston police brought in Gladys Williams, the mother of the
juvenile and the other five children, for questioning when she
arrived at the house later in the morning. Williams, whose age was
not available, told police she originally was from New Jersey but
had been living in the Dorchester house for about two months.
   The state Department of Social Services was granted temporary
custody of the six children, and they will be placed in foster care,
said department spokesman Joseph Landolfi.
</TEXT>
