<FIRST>r w AM-AbandonedMines     09-13 0415</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abandoned Mines,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Panel Says Western States Should Pay For Eastern Mine Reclamation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHERINE RIZZO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Interior Committee decided Thursday
that coal mines all over the country should pay for cleaning up
abandoned strip mines, rejecting arguments of Western states that it
was unfair to tax them for eastern cleanups.
   On a 27-11 vote, the panel sent to the full House a bill
providing a 15-year extension of the mine reclamation tax, with
special provisions that may let western states pay at a reduced rate.
   Western coal producers want an end to the tax because all their
abandoned coal mine projects are on track for completion by the end
of 1992, when coal mining's version of Superfund is scheduled to
expire.
   Rep. Larry Craig, R-Idaho, argued that the federal program has
served its purpose and further reclamation should fall to the states.
   He said it's unfair to ask one segment of the mining industry to
take care of another segment's problems. Western coal interests
would end up subsidizing Eastern projects, he argued.
   The Office of Surface Mining estimates another $4 billion in
high-priority problems will remain in the East after 1992.
   Lawmakers from Eastern coal states argued that the nation as a
whole benefited from the coal mined in Appalachia and is responsible
for damage left behind.
   ``This is the coal that fueled the Industrial Revolution,'' said
Rep. Nick Rahall, D-W.Va.
   Saying open shafts, contaminated water and burning refuse piles
are local or regional concerns is like arguing that a state without
Superfund sites should be exempted from paying into the toxic
cleanup-fund, he said.
   ``Just as we have declared a war on drugs, so must we protect
coalfield citizens from the health, safety and environmental hazards
they face on a daily basis,'' said Rahall, who came up with a
compromise that cuts in half the tax paid by coal producers
operating in states where abandoned mine projects have been
completed.
   The legislation ready for House consideration includes that 50
percent cut.
   The tax currrently is uniform nationwide: 35 cents per ton of
surface-mined coal, 15 cents per ton of deep-mined coal, 10 cents
per ton of lignite.
   The legislation would let companies in states certified to have
finished all mine reclamation work pay 18 cents per ton of
surface-mined coal, 8 cents per ton of deep-mined coal and 5 cents
per ton of lignite.
   The tax had collected $2.2 billion through last Sept. 30.
</TEXT>
