<HEAD>Senate Votes on FSX Veto Override</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 4th graf: ``The vote,'' To spell out that Japan may
now proceed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate failed by a single vote Wednesday to
override President Bush's veto of congressional restrictions on the
coproduction of a jet fighter with Japan.
   The 66-34 vote, one vote short of the required two-thirds
majority, came after a debate in which both the White House and
Congress were accused of trying to monopolize the power to regulate
the nation's international trade.
   In the debate, Bush supporters said the legislation represented a
serious erosion of the powers of the presidency and would force
renegotiation of the terms of the FSX production contract between
the two nations.
   The vote means Japan can go ahead with the fighter, an updated
version of the General Dynamics Corp. F-16, under the deal
negotiated with the Bush administration.
   Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole of Kansas pleaded with
colleagues not to aggravate the president and to sustain Bush's veto
of legislation Dole called ``meddling, micromanagement and not
constructive.''
   Senate Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., the principal sponsor of the FSX
resolution, told the Senate that the FSX resolution is ``too
important to have a turf battle over,'' declaring that it improves
the terms of the deal for the United States.
   Senators seeking to overturn the veto said it represented a White
House power grab in the international trade arena and a direct
threat to the constitutional power of Congress to regulate trade.
   Sen. John C. Danforth, R-Mo., said the FSX legislation does not
derail the coproduction deal, which he said is ``in place and cannot
be undone.''
   ``This debate is about the drawing of lines between the president
and the Congress on international trade issues,'' Danforth said.
``If the president is correct in his view, then he has succeeded in
dramatically shifting the line from where it has been.
   ``If we agree (with the veto) then there has been a very
substantial rollback in the authority of the Congress of the United
States on issues related to international trade,'' he said. ``This
is trying to muscle the other fellow off the beach.''
   But Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind., contended that in passing the FSX
resolution on a 72-27 roll call, the Senate ``overreached'' and
moved to usurp the president's proper authority under the
Constitution.
   ``The president of the United States has not attempted to strip
the Congress of any constitutional power whatsoever,'' Lugar said. '
   He said the president is contending that ``the executive branch
retains the right to negotiate agreements with other nations and
that the Senate has the right to approve or reject them.''
   He appealed to the Senate to let the agreement with Japan go
forward on grounds it is in the U.S. national interest and not to
``foul it up with mischief legislation.''
   Bush vetoed the FSX resolution on July 31, saying, ``I cannot
accept binding provisions ... that would tie my hands in the
exercise of my constitutional responsibilities.''
   He said the legislation would inject the General Accounting
Office, an agency of the legislative branch, into the administration
of the jet program ``in a highly intrusive manner,'' trespassing on
the constitutional powers of the president.
   ``To reopen discussions now for additional and needless changes
can only damage the prospects for a successful agreement,'' the
president said.
   ``If this occurs, substantial injury to the U.S.-Japan security
relationship is likely and the considerable strategic and commercial
benefits to the United States will be lost.''
   The agreement, negotiated earlier this year by Bush
administration officials with officials of the Japanese government,
calls for development by General Dynamics and Mitsubishi Heavy
Industries of an advanced version of the F-16 fighter, named FSX, to
be deployed by Japan in the 1990s. The deal envisions a $6 billion
price tag.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
