<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 2159EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-TroubledMayor 1stLd-Writethru a0744 09-13 0680</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Troubled Mayor, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0744,0699</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mayor Walked `Grey Area of Law,' City Attorney Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `Bradley did ...,' with 4 grafs to UPDATE with
Bradley speech; picks up 6th graf, `Although Hahn ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE V. BIGELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Tom Bradley walked a ``gray area of the
law'' as a paid consultant to two savings banks doing business with
the city, but evidence is insufficient to prosecute him, the city
attorney said Wednesday.
   Bradley instead faces a civil lawsuit that alleges six violations
of failing to report investments, two of them in excess of $100,000.
   City Attorney James Hahn filed the lawsuit in Los Angeles
Superior Court at about the same time as he released a 1,613-page
report on the mayor's conduct. The report was based on a five-month
investigation by Hahn's office into Bradley's relationship with Far
East National Bank and Valley Federal Savings and Loan Association.
   ``No vindication of the mayor's conduct is intended, implied or
should in any way be inferred,'' Hahn wrote in the report. ``The
mayor clearly stepped into that gray area of the law between factual
innocence and a chargeable offense.''
   The mayor said the report confirmed his earlier statements that
he broke no conflict-of-interest laws.
   ``I would never do anything to harm Los Angeles,'' he said in a
locally televised afternoon speech. ``I will not let you down.''
   In the lengthy speech, Bradley said that he saw no connection
between accepting consulting fees from a bank and the city
treasurer's decisions to deposit city money in the bank.
   ``The two have nothing to do with one another,'' he said.
   Although Hahn described his five-month investigation as
``exhaustive'' and ``unprecedented in scope and purpose,'' it was
limited to a narrow range of questions about the mayor's outside
financial dealings.
   Still unresolved are questions about possible illegalities
involving a city-funded task force for Africa, Bradley's ties to the
investment banking firm of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. and an
alleged cover-up by the city treasurer's office.
   Hahn said it was apparent that a March 22 telephone call from
Bradley to City Treasurer Leonard Rittenberg influenced Rittenberg
to deposit $2 million in city funds with Far East National Bank.
   Bradley was paid $18,000 as a consultant to Far East.
   It was also obvious, Hahn said, that someone altered financial
bid sheets following a reporter's inquiry about the Far East
deposit. A section of the bid sheets that contained the words ``per
the mayor'' had been blotted out.
   ``There's no question in my mind that there was a cover-up, but
we could find no evidence linking that to the mayor,'' the city
attorney said.
   Hahn noted, however, that a criminal investigation into the
treasurer's activities is continuing.
   While much of the report dealt with the mayor's relationship with
Far East, he also received at least $89,000 in consulting fees from
Valley Federal since 1979.
   The mayor was a consultant for Valley Federal while it had a $2.7
million tax dispute with the city, and while developments backed by
Valley Federal sought zoning changes from the city.
   Bradley has resigned from consulting positions with both banks.
   The 11-page lawsuit, alleging violations of the state Government
Code, does not specify the penalties sought by the city attorney.
However, Hahn and Bradley were expected to negotiate over about $2.2
million in possible fines.
   The suit alleges that Bradley intentionally or negligently failed
to report personal financial interests totaling more than $200,000.
   In some instances, the mayor's investments were made through the
local office of Drexel, and Hahn referred that aspect of the
investigation to the federal Securities and Exchange Commission.
   The report also noted serious concerns about the mayor's
relationship to the Task Force for Africa-Los Angeles, and said
police are continuing their investigation into the city agency. But
Hahn said he found no misconduct by Bradley in his dealings with the
agency.
   Juanita St. John, head of the task force, has been ordered by the
City Controller's office to account for missing city funds granted
to the trade group.
</TEXT>
