<FIRST>r i AM-Brazil-Storms     09-13 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Storms,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>12 Dead, 1000s Homeless in Brazilian Storms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three days of pounding rain and
high winds left 12 people dead and drove thousands from their homes
in southern Brazil, civil defense officials said Wednesday.
   Three people drowned and a fourth was killed by lightning in
Curitiba, capital of Parana state, 500 miles southwest of Rio,
Carlos Daher of the civil defense said in a telephone interview.
Among the dead was a 16-year-old boy, swept away by a flooded river
in the slum neighborhood of Vila Sofia.
   ``The river rose so high that parts of the city looked like a
lake,'' Daher said of the flooding. ``But the rain has stopped now,
and people who were driven from their homes are going back to clean
up.''
   Six people died in western Parana when winds of up to 65 mph
knocked down buildings and blew off roofs, leaving 4,000 homeless,
Daher said.
   Worst hit was rural Pato Branco, where winds destroyed the homes
of 2,500 people, he said.
   The homeless were being sheltered in churches, schools and public
buildings, Daher said.
   In Santa Catarina state, heavy rains caused a gold mine in the
city of Lages to collapse Tuesday, trapping and killing two men,
officials said.
   Heavy rain also left 2,000 people homeless in Rio Grande do Sul,
Brazil's southernmost state.
</TEXT>
