<FIRST>r a AM-Yeltsin     09-13 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yeltsin,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Maverick Visits Liberty Bell</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boris N. Yeltsin, the maverick Soviet
legislator, on Wednesday toured the birthplace of U.S. democracy,
visiting Independence Hall and touching the Liberty Bell.
   ``The same kind of crack which I see in this bell should not
arise in the free countries of the world as a result of the
emergence of liberty,'' Yeltsin said.
   After sightseeing, the 58-year-old Yeltsin addressed more than
800 people at a World Affairs Council luncheon for a fee of $25,000,
which he said will go to charity.
   Yeltsin, who met briefly with President Bush during his weeklong
speaking tour of the United States, also arranged for a meeting
Thursday with former President Reagan, recovering from brain surgery
at a hospital in Rochester, Minn., Reagan spokesman Mark Weinberg
said.
   Yeltsin, a sharp critic of what he called Mikhail Gorbachev's
``compromising and half measures,'' said he hoped the Soviet Union
would improve economic relations with the United States.
   ``We have to change some of our laws on land holdings and
property to make this possible,'' he said through an interpreter.
``If foreigners could purchase land, they would make investments.
   ``I would like to see someone build 1 million apartments and sell
them because Soviet citizens have money available and they would
bring a good price if they were good.''
   Yeltsin, ousted as Moscow's Communist Party chief in 1987 but
later overwhelmingly elected to parliament, said he did not expect
any retaliation for his frank criticism about developments in his
country.
   ``I'm no less straightforward about what I say back there as I
say here,'' Yeltsin said. ``I'm trying to practice the diplomacy of
truth. I think we should get away from the old-fashioned diplomacy
of people trying to outwit each other.
   ``If we can be truthful it will increase the level of confidence
between countries and people.''
   He said he did not expect any kind of effort to oust Gorbachev,
calling it ``extremely unlikely since I have been on the inside for
2{ years and I know it can't happen.''
   On the thousands of East Germans fleeing through Hungary to the
West, he said, ``People should have the right to leave their country
and go someplace else. This is part of an international agreement.''
   Yeltsin was asked about a report that the KGB, the Soviet secret
police, had offered the United States help in its drug war.
   ``All I can say is that the KGB has its hands full dealing with
drugs in the USSR,'' he answered. ``They have to take care of their
own domestic problems before they start trying to help someone
else.''
</TEXT>
