<FIRST>r i AM-India-Attack     09-13 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Attack,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Officer's Son Killed, Sikh Extremists Suspected</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEEPAK SHARMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Suspected Sikh extremists Wednesday shot
to death the son of a senior police official and wounded his friend
as they returned from college on a motorcycle in northern Punjab
state, authorities said.
   Press Trust of India news agency said the extremists also killed
three people elsewhere in the state Wednesday, bringing to 1,206 the
number of people killed in the secessionist violence this year.
   Rajan Ram, 18, was shot in the head and chest by unidentified men
in a car in Jallandhar, a senior police officer said in that city 45
miles south of Amritsar.
   Ram and a friend, Pradeep Kumar, were returning from college when
they were attacked on a busy road in the town's center, Suresh
Arora, the senior police superintendent of Jallandhar, said in a
telephone interview.
   He said Kumar was seriously injured, and the attackers sped away
in the car.
   Arora quoted Kumar as saying that before opening fire, the men
asked Rajan Ram if he was the son of Gobind Ram, a senior
superintendent of police in the Punjab Armed Police.
   He was transferred to the post Sept. 1. Earlier, he served as
senior superintendent of police of neighboring Batala district,
where he had led a crackdown on Sikh extremists fighting to set up
an independent nation.
   Rajan Ram was the fourth son of a senior police officer to have
been killed by suspected Sikh extremists. Police officials said the
extremists have killed at least 20 relatives of police officers.
   Sikh militants began their secessionist campaign in 1982,
charging discrimination by the Hindu-dominated government.
   Sikhs make up 2 percent of India's 880 million people, but they
are in a slight majority in Punjab. Hindus make up 88 percent of the
population.
</TEXT>
