<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--PuertoRico     09-13 0154</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Puerto Rico,0158</SECOND>
<HEAD>Separatist Leader Proposes United Pro-Independence Rally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Independence leader Juan Mari Bras
proposed Wednesday that all Puerto Rican pro-independence groups
unite at one big rally on Sept. 23 to commemorate this Caribbean
island's 1868 revolt against Spain.
   He said the groups, which often differ over ideology, should
cancel separate events planned to commemorate the revolt.
   Mari Bras, founder of the Puerto Rican Socialist Party and
veteran independence leader, suggested the main speakers be
Independence Party leader Ruben Berrios, Socialist Party leader
Carlos Gallisa and Macheteros founder Filiberto Ojeda Rios.
   Ojeda Rios is on bail pending trial in Hartford, Conn., in
connection with the 1983 robbery of $7 million from a Wells Fargo
depot.
   Nationalists in the mountain town of Lares in 1868 called for a
revolt against Spain. Their rebellion failed. Spain later lost
Puerto Rico to the United States in the 1898 Spanish-American War.
