<FIRST>r a AM-MissAmerica-Preliminaries     09-13 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Miss America-Preliminaries,0498</SECOND>
<HEAD>Miss Louisiana, Miss Oklahoma Win Preliminary Miss America Competitions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Miss Oklahoma won the talent division
and Miss Louisiana won the swimsuit contest Wednesday in the second
night of preliminary competitions for the Miss America Pageant.
   Tamara Denise Toshiko Marler, a 26-year-old from Tulsa, Okla.,
performed a haunting, romantic rendition of ``Since I Fell For You.''
   For her performance, she wore a full-length navy silk gown beaded
with Mediterranean blue bugle beads and featuring a sweetheart
neckline.
   Miss Marler, who is half-Japanese, is a recent marketing graduate
of the University of Tulsa. She hopes to someday become a lawyer.
   Miss Marler, who has auburn hair and chestnut eyes, said her hero
is Barbra Streisand.
   ``She is so talented,'' she said. ``She's a great singer,
producer, director and writer, and she's straightforward and
honest.''
   The winner of Wednesday's swimsuit competition was Miss Louisiana
Stacy King, a green-eyed blonde. At 5-foot-5 and 105 pounds, she
wore a white swimsuit with spaghetti straps at the shoulders.
   To stay in shape, she plays softball, dances, bicycles and trains
with weights ``every day.'' To prepare for the pageant, Miss King
said she gave up chocolate chip cookies.
   ``I gave them up right after I won the state pageant on June 18 _
that's 2 1-2 months,'' she said. ``If I lose in Atlantic City, I'll
eat a lot of them.''
   Miss King, a 23-year-old from Slidell, La., has a degree in
fashion merchandising from Louisiana Tech University and plans to
obtain a degree in dental hygiene. Eventually, she said she hopes to
combine both degrees to design more fashionable uniforms.
   Wednesday's competition was the second of three nights of
swimsuit, talent and evening gown rounds. The winners of the
preliminary evening gown competitions are kept secret to heighten
the suspense for the finals.
   The three nights of preliminary competitions for the 51
contestants are the first steps to the live nationally televised
Miss America Pageant on Saturday. On Friday night, the contestants
participate in the famous, colorful Miss America Parade on the
resort's Boardwalk.
   The 10 women who have accumulated the most points in preliminary
competitions and interviews with the judges will become the top 10
finalists. Those 10 will start with a clean slate Saturday night,
competing to succeed Miss America 1989 Gretchen Elizabeth Carlson.
   The judging has been revised this year, with talent counting for
40 percent, the interview for 30 percent, and the evening gown and
swimsuit divisions counting for 15 percent each.
   At Tuesday night's preliminary competition, Miss Missouri Debbye
Turner wore a canary yellow swimsuit to win that contest.
   Miss Ohio Kristin Huffman won the talent division with a
classical vocal piece titled ``Csardas.''
   The 63rd annual pageant will air on NBC-TV at 10 p.m. EDT
Saturday. Gary Collins and Miss America 1971 Phyllis George Brown
will host.
</TEXT>
