<FIRST>u i AM-Britain-Rushdie 1stLd-Writethru a0815 09-13 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Rushdie, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0815,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bookstore Owned By Rushdie Publisher is Bombed, Other Bomb Found</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with six grafs to UPDATE with other bomb found and defused;
pickup graf 5 pvs `He said...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YORK, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A homemade bomb exploded Wednesday outside a
bookstore owned by the British publisher of Salman Rushdie's novel,
``The Satanic Verses,'' and a second bomb was defused at another of
its stores, police said.
   There were no injuries.
   However, the bomb that exploded caused minor damage to the York
bookstore owned by the Viking Penguin group, police said. The store
was closed for the night.
   The other bomb was found Wednesday night outside the group's
bookstore in Guildford, 30 miles southwest of London, police said.
It was safely defused by army experts, they said.
   No group claimed responsibility for planting either bomb, but
suspicion fell on Moslem hard-liners opposed to the publication and
sale of the book, which many Moslems say blasphemes their religion.
   Inspector Ron Johnson of York police said the bomb there was
spotted about a half-hour before it went off. Police cleared the
area, which was crowded with tourists.
   He said the attackers gave no warning.
   Moslem militants in Britain ignited worldwide demonstrations
against the book when they burned copies in Bradford, 30 miles
southwest of the northern city of York, following its publication in
September 1988.
   Rushdie, an Indian-born naturalized British citizen, has been in
hiding since Feb. 14, when the late Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini,
Iran's spiritual leader, called on Moslems to kill him and his
publishers.
   On Aug. 3, a bomb killed a man in a London hotel, and a
previously unknown Islamic group claimed he was preparing to use the
device against Rushdie.
   In addition, two California bookstores were firebombed on March
1, and five stores in London were bombed between April 9 and Sept.
3. Authorities said those attacks may have been connected to ``The
Satanic Verses.''
</TEXT>
