<FIRST>u i AM-Brazil-Drugs     09-13 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Drugs,0352</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Arrest Cocaine Kingpin With Alleged Ties to Medellin Cartel</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Colombia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police stormed an outlying slum and
captured the city's top drug kingpin Wednesday. He is believed to
have direct ties to Colombia's Medellin drug cartel, an official
said.
   Darcy da Silva Filho allegedly smuggled large amounts of cocaine
from the Medellin cartel to Brazil as well as neighboring Bolivia,
state police Col. Emir Campos Laranjeira said.
   ``Filho had direct contacts with drug bosses in Medellin and
Bolivia,'' Laranjeira said. ``He went there personally on several
occasions to buy. He smuggled cocaine in shipments as large as 800
pounds.''
   He said Filho, 37, sold an average of 130 pounds of cocaine in
Rio each week. That represents about 60 percent of the city's drug
trafficking operations, he said.
   ``This is perhaps the biggest drug arrest in Rio in recent
times,'' said Laranjeira. ``The repercussions of this arrest will be
far felt.''
   Early Wednesday, 120 policemen with machine guns, shotguns and
aided by helicopters began the day-long raid. They discovered the
drug traffickers in a lavishly furnished apartment at noon,
Laranjeira said.
   After an intense gunbattle, Filho's bodyguards fled and police
arrested the drug baron, his chauffeur and nephew, said Laranjeira.
   Police seized 13 pounds of cocaine paste, valued at $200,000, but
found no weapons, he said.
   The drug leader has been charged on three counts of drug
trafficking and faces up to 40 years in prison, Laranjeira said.
   Brazil traditionally has played a relatively minor role in the
South American drug trade, which is dominated by Colombia, Peru and
Bolivia. Colombia's Medellin and Cali cocaine cartels produce an
estimated 80 percent of cocaine for U.S. markets.
   But in recent years, South America's largest nation has emerged
as a key player in international trafficking, with a role in every
stage of the drug chain, from production to consumption.
   Seizures of cocaine have risen from about 200 pounds in 1981 to
more than 15 times that amount last year, according to police
figures.
</TEXT>
