<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 2311EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-US-Burma     09-13 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Burma,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Officials Describe Mass Torture, Voice Doubt Over Free Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. officials said Wednesday they have
trustworthy reports that Burma's military government routinely
tortures political prisoners, and it has become questionable whether
the country's election next spring will be free.
   Electric shocks, cigarette burnings, beatings and other forms of
torture were described at the State Department's daily news
briefing, and later by department witnesses who told a congressional
hearing that the Burmese junta has killed and arrested thousands in
a continuing wave of repression that began one year ago.
   Congress also heard testimony about forced labor and ``death
marches'' in Burma in which members of ethnic minorities were
rounded up, put on starvation rations and used as human minesweepers
for army units.
   Two House Foreign Affairs subcommittees unanimously approved a
resolution demanding that Burma release everyone ``imprisoned for
the peaceful expression of their views,'' investigate and punish
those accused of torture and uphold its commitment to free and fair
elections by next May.
   The legislation also urged all countries to follow the U.S. lead
in withholding foreign aid from Burma. It was sent to the full
committee and sponsors said a final floor vote would be sought this
month. The Senate last month passed a similar resolution, with
backing of the Bush administration.
   From Burma, ``we now have credible, first-hand reports that
instances of torture, beatings and mistreatment are commonplace and
that deaths have resulted,'' State Department spokeswoman Margaret
Tutwiler told reporters.
   She and Richard Schifter, assistant secretary of state for human
rights, who testified in Congress, made similar statements
describing cigarette burnings, beatings causing severe eye and ear
injuries, electrical shocks to the genitals and immersion in water
during questioning.
   Such mistreatment along with forced loss of sleep ``appear to be
routine methods of questioning'' of thousands of detainees in Burma,
Schifter told a joint hearing of the subcommittees on human rights
and Asian and Pacific affairs.
   ``The number of Burmese killed by the government the past year is
in the thousands,'' he said. ``It may well be that the number of
Burmese killed is indeed higher'' than the count of those massacred
in China's current crackdown on its democracy movement, he said in
answer to a question.
   Burma's military government headed by General Saw Maung seized
power Sept. 18, 1988, ousting a month-old moderate civilian regime
that took over after the resignation of General Ne Win whose
18-year-rule, Schifter said, had reduced Burma ``to a state of
poverty.''
   Recent developments in Burma ``call into question the military
government's pledge that it will hold free and fair elections and
turn over power to a civilian government,'' said David F.
Lambertson, deputy assistant secretary of state for East Asian and
Pacific Affairs.
   ``Recent measures ... appear designed to engineer an electoral
victory by the leading pro-government party,'' he said. Thousands of
backers of the National League for Democracy and other leading
opposition groups have been arrested since July 20, and NLD leaders
Aung San Suu Kyi and Tin Oo are under house arrest ``virtually cut
off from the rest of the world,'' Lambertson testified.
   Schifter said the United States has not given up hope for a fair
election, ``but the situation is going to have to change, leaders of
the opposition are going to have to be given freedom ... recent
performance does not give much reason for optimism.''
   The government might well step up its ``resort to lethal force if
political opponents mounted mass public protests anew,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
