<FIRST>r a AM-InsuranceReferendum     09-13 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Insurance Referendum,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court OKs Auto Insurance Referendum for New Jersey</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS MARTELLO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An appeals court Wednesday cleared the way
for a citizens group to put a referendum on state ballots calling
for a 20 percent cut in auto insurance rates.
   In a 2-1 decision, an Appellate Division panel of Superior Court
ruled that the referendum, sponsored by Citizens Auto Revolt, is
legal. Representatives of the insurance industry said they would
appeal to the state Supreme Court.
   The non-binding referendum is to be placed on the November ballot
in each of New Jersey's 21 counties. It urges state lawmakers to
trim auto insurance rates by 20 percent and enact several reforms of
the state insurance system.
   Lawyers for the insurance industry had argued that the
referendum's sponors acted improperly by trying to place the
initiative on each county's ballot, rather than on a statewide basis.
   But two of three judges on the panel agreed with the group's
contention that it could initiate a statewide referendum through the
counties.
   ``This is a very exciting and important decision,'' said Jay
Angoff, executive director of the reform group. ``It shows that a
citizens group can fight back against an industry as powerful as the
insurance industry by going directly to the people.''
   Michael Herbert, an attorney representing the insurance industry,
said the referendum would confuse voters and ``create turmoil.''
   In addition to the rollback in auto insurance costs, the
referendum urges state lawmakers to initiate reforms that include
the scrapping of the Joint Underwriting Association pool for high
risk drivers and the elimination of the insurance industry's
exemption to the anti-trust laws governing price-fixing.
</TEXT>
