<FIRST>a i PM-Salvador-Linemen Adv19   09-13 0821</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador-Linemen, Adv 19,0845</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv19</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tues PMs Sept. 19 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>El Salvador's High-Tension Linemen Are War's Unsung Heroes</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR VOLCANO, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Almost every day in El
Salvador's guerrilla war, khaki-clad commandos of an unsung assault
force have descended on war zones armed only with ratchets, pulleys
and shovels.
   They are the intrepid electric-power linemen who replace towers
toppled by guerrilla sabotage, raise tons of downed cable and keep
the country's lights on in the midst of civil war.
   They have seen companions killed and maimed by mines or in cross
fires and now they are delighted with the announcement by the
anti-government guerrillas of an indefinite end to sabotage as of
Sept. 10.
   The linemen, however, have plenty to keep them busy for months
without new damage to the network of high-tension cables
criss-crossing El Salvador, a nation about the size of Massachusetts.
   ``Halting the sabotage is good, because everybody is favored by
it,'' said lineman Roberto Segovia. ``But let's see what the
government offers in exchange, to show it is really interested in
peace and ending the war for good.''
   He was one of 30 linemen working to replace six poles bombed
recently along a major transmission line traversing a high flank of
the volcano looming northwest of San Salvador, the capital city.
   Segovia was wounded in the face by shrapnel in 1986 when a
soldier near him stepped on a mine at a sabotaged site.
   Although mines have killed one lineman and wounded seven since
1981, the linemen don't speak harshly of the Marxist-led guerrillas
who have been fighting the government for nearly a decade.
   Antonio Ramirez, a lineman whose left arm was partly disabled by
shrapnel in 1981, said guerrillas sometimes visit the workers at job
sites and the meetings are cordial.
   Describing an encounter late last year, he said: ``We talked
about things in general. Then all gave each other Christmas embraces
before they went off.''
   Almost all of the linemen are members of a militant union,
veterans of labor battles that have given their views a tone similar
to that of many positions expressed by the Farabundo Marti National
Liberation Front, the guerrilla organization.
   The front said in its announcement Sept. 7 that its suspension of
sabotage and the use of mines was for ``a sufficiently prudent time
for the government and armed forces to carry out reciprocal gestures
that contribute to a serious climate of negotiation.''
   The government's immediate response was that the suspension would
permit the guerrillas to evacuate their wounded.
   A subsequent broadcast on the guerrillas' clandestine radio said,
``Sabotage has played a strategic role in the war, preventing the
regime from spending all its money on arms. Sabotage has undermined
the war economy, and its effectiveness has been undeniable.''
   Sabotage of the electric-power system has cost the country more
than $100 million since the war began, and it has been getting
steadily worse. Last year was the worst to date with 539 bombings of
major lines. Through August of this year, 451 bombings of such lines
were recorded _ a rate that would easily have surpassed 1988 had
sabotage continued.
   However, the United States, through the Agency for International
Development (AID), pays virtually all the repairs to damaged power
lines. It has provided more than $3.5 billion in military and
economic aid this decade in an effort to prevent a rebel victory,
making El Salvador by far the hemisphere's biggest recipient of U.S.
assistance.
   ``Without AID, we couldn't survive,'' said Mauricio Arevalo,
superintendent of line maintainance, who oversees the 90 linemen,
five engineers and five foremen who keep the power flowing
nationwide.
   AID provided the two Bell 212 helicopters that transport the
workers and carry, dangling from a cable, the 40-foot pine poles,
also donated by AID, that hold the lines.
   The steel towers used originally now lie twisted and rusting
along transmission routes.
   ``Between 75 and 80 percent of our metal structures have been
destroyed,'' said Arevalo, on the volcano with his men. ``We replace
them with poles because it's much cheaper and they are much more
mobile.''
   A lineman with 20 years experience earns the equivalent of about
$280 a month, including the 35-percent raise that was the result of
a bitter 21-day strike last year, plus $7,000 life insurance
policies. El Salvador's minimum wage is $100 a month but $280 a
month is about what a teacher or factory worker would earn. The
linemen maintain that their wages and compensation are inadequate.
   Raul Mendez, who lost his right leg below the knee to a mine in
1986, said he received $3,500 in compensation and continues working
with a prosthesis.
   Asked if he resented the guerrillas who planted the mine, he
said: ``Not at all. It's the kind of thing that happens in this line
of work.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Tues PMs Sept. 19</NOTE>
