<FIRST>r f PM-Aspen-Sugarman     09-13 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Aspen-Sugarman,0194</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sugarman's Group to Acquire Aspen Airways</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investor Burt Sugarman said he has
agreed to buy Aspen Airways, a 35-year-old privately-owned airline
serving Colorado's ski resorts for an undisclosed price.
   ``As a part-time resident of Aspen for 22 years, I've flown on it
many times over the years, and I've enjoyed the service,'' said
Sugarman in announcing the purchase Monday.
   Donald W. Ringsby, chairman of the family-owned carrier, said the
airline could not afford on its own to replace its turbo-prop
airplanes, which are about 25 years old.
   It could cost between $8 million and $10 million to replace the
10 Convair 580 commuter planes, Ringsby said. Aspen, which serves 16
cities in the western United States and Canada, also operates four
British Aerospace-146 jet planes.
   In March, Sugarman sold his controlling interest in Barris
Industries Inc., producers of the television programs ``The Gong
Show'' and ``The Newlywed Game,'' to the owners of an Australian
television network for $34.5 million.
   He is acquiring Aspen through Giant Group Ltd., his Beverly
Hills, Calif.-based holding company that also owns cement plants.
</TEXT>
