<FIRST>r f PM-Neiman'sCatalog 1stLd-Writethru f0009 09-13 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Neiman's Catalog, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0009,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>From Cowpokes to Cattle Drives, Neiman-Marcus Goes Western</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Eliminates hyphen from Neiman Marcus throughout. Also moving
on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHIP BROWN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Neiman Marcus, seller of sumptuous fantasies for 81
years, is inviting its well-heeled clientele to put on a pair of
spurs and recapture the Wild West.
   The Dallas-based retailer began delivery Tuesday of its Christmas
catalog, the annual wishbook of the wealthy. For one cowpoke with
$108,000, Neiman's will sell a hand-tooled saddle by Edward H.
Bohlin Co., lavishly furnished with sterling silver and 18-karat
gold.
   A cowboy ain't a cowboy without a horse, so for $4,000 and up
Neiman Marcus is offering a selection of champion bloodline painted
horses from the Real Ranch in Kerrville. Buyers can choose from 1989
weanlings and up _ from black to bay.
   Those wishing to relive the great cattle drives of the Old West
can reserve a pony to chase herd for a weekend at the Y.O. Ranch,
also near Kerrville. There is room for 150 people to attend the
ranch's 110th anniversary in April 1990.
   ``I do not recommend this for pussyfooters,'' said Jan Roberts, a
Neiman Marcus spokeswoman.
   To give prospective ropers across the country an equal shot at
the event, Neiman Marcus has set 11 a.m. CDT Oct. 18 as the time it
will begin taking reservations. The weekend costs $627 for a double
occupancy room.
   ``Texas is really in right now,'' Ms. Roberts said. ``From the
president to Lonesome Dove, Texas and the West are in vogue. And
because Neiman Marcus is from Texas, we thought we should get back
to our roots and pay tribute to our heritage.''
   The catalog includes more whimsical gifts with a Western flavor,
including teepee-shaped salt and pepper shakers and a replica of the
badge deputized lawmen once fashioned.
   In recent years, Neiman Marcus, which has stores across the
country, has offered a spangled cat, his-and-her mummy cases and
giant hot air balloons.
   The catalog always contains several pages of furs. A coat of
Russian lynx bellies sells for $150,000 this year.
   For fisherman who can't wait to see what they are reeling in, an
8-foot glass-bottom boat is available for $1,800.
   The catalog does not leave out the pet or pet lover. In a section
titled ``From Santa Paws,'' the catalog features townhouses for
tomcats and beds for bulldogs along with a cat collar lined with
fish-shaped pearls.
   But the 130-page gift book does not only cater to the rich, Ms.
Roberts said.
   ``This year we have six pages dedicated to gifts for $26 or
less,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890913-0261 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 0242EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Campeau Bjt   09-13 0689</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Campeau, Bjt,0714</SECOND>
<HEAD>Campeau Board Approves Sale of Bloomingdale's, Loan From Developer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Directors of troubled Campeau Corp. have approved
a plan to sell its crown jewel, the Bloomingdale's department store
chain, and to accept a loan from a real estate firm as part of a
restructuring of the Toronto-based retailer.
   Meanwhile Tuesday, shopping mall developer Crown American Corp.
confirmed its interest in acquiring Bloomingdale's.
   ``We are still in the process of gathering information,'' said
Frank Pasquerilla, Crown American's chairman and chief executive
officer.
   ``At this point, we are interested in keeping the 16-store chain
and its operations intact,'' he said in a statement released by
Crown American's headquarters in Johnstown, Pa. He added that any
bid ``probably would be in excess of $1 billion.''
   Campeau board members, meeting privately in Toronto, agreed to
put Bloomingdale's on the block and approved a proposal aimed at
coping with a cash crunch.
   Campeau stock fell 25 cents to close at 16.87{ Canadian dollars
in Toronto Stock Exchange trading Tuesday. The announcement of the
board's decisions was made after the market closed.
   Campeau management unveiled the restructuring plan Friday, saying
it was designed to reduce debt and address a need for working
capital. The sale of Bloomingdale's would be a key element of the
overhaul.
   As one of the best-known names in retailing, New York-based
Bloomingdale's was expected to attract significant interest among
potential buyers.
   Crown American, a privately held company founded by Pasquerilla,
is one of the country's biggest shopping mall developers. It owns 30
enclosed malls and nine community shopping centers plus 19 hotels
and five office buildings. Its hotels include Comfort Inns, Hotel
Ibis and Compri Hotels.
   In 1979, Crown American bought Hess's Department Stores of
Allentown, Pa. Hess's now has 72 stores, up from 17 a decade ago.
   The only other potential rival for Bloomingdale's to come forward
so far is the department store chain's chairman and chief executive,
Marvin S. Traub, who last week said he was in the early stages of
putting together a buyout proposal.
   Traub, in an interview Friday, wouldn't say what price he might
offer for Bloomingdale's or comment on where he might obtain
financing. He said he was still contacting lawyers and investment
bankers.
   Traub said he has been interested in taking control of the
retailer he has headed for 11 years since the time when Campeau
became embroiled in a bidding battle for Bloomingdale's parent
Federated Department Stores Inc. with rival R.H. Macy &amp; Co. Inc.
   The takeover of Federated, completed about a year and a half ago,
cost Campeau $6.7 billion and contributed to the Canadian company's
precarious financial condition.
   Campeau, which bought Allied Stores Corp. in 1986 for $3.4
billion, is struggling with a debt burden approaching $10 billion.
   A sale of Bloomingdale's could raise $1 billion to $2 billion,
Wall Street analysts say, and chop an estimated $200 million off
Campeau's annual $1 billion in interest payments.
   A pressing concern for Campeau this week is a loan of about $400
million left over from acquiring Federated. Unless refinanced, the
loan converts into notes and warrants of Federated stock this week.
   Among elements of the restructuring plan approved in principle
Tuesday by Campeau's board was a $250 million loan from
Toronto-based Olympia &amp; York Developments Ltd., which has an 11.8
percent stake in Campeau.
   The funds from Olympia &amp; York, which analysts speculated might be
given in exchange for a larger stake in Campeau, were expected to
allow Campeau to cover its immediate cash needs.
   Retail analysts said an intense bidding battle could develop for
Bloomingdale's, a high-profile retailer usually considered to be on
the cutting edge of fashion merchandising.
   ``It's going to be similar to the Federated feud,'' said analyst
Linda R. Morris, of PNC Financial Corp. in Pittsburgh.
   Rumors that possibly as many as a dozen retailers and real estate
holding companies were considering making offers circulated in the
stock market. Among the names cited were Limited Inc., a leading
specialty apparel retailer. A spokeswoman at the chain's Columbus,
Ohio, headquarters said the company had no comment.
</TEXT>
