<DOCNO> AP890913-0262 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 0241EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AutoOrders Bjt   09-13 0640</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto Orders, Bjt,0659</SECOND>
<HEAD>Orders Dropping for 90 Cars As Dealers Face Slump</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Houston auto dealer Alan Helfman will be scaling
back his orders for 1990 model cars and trucks, even though he has
just five 1989 models left on his lot.
   Helfman, general manager of River Oaks Chrysler-Plymouth in that
Texas city, isn't alone. Other dealers nationwide say they too will
trim their orders for the next model year's vehicles, due out next
month, mainly because of pressure from their own inventories and
sagging sales.
   ``I'm probably going to cut them back a touch,'' Helfman said
Tuesday. ``I think we will be a little more conservative this year.
When you look at everything, you've got to really forecast and
you've got to be conservative.''
   After a few strong sales periods recently, year-to-date car and
light truck sales through the end of last month were running 3.7
percent behind last year's pace.
   While that's better than at the end of March, when sales were
down 8.9 percent compared with that time last year, industry experts
expect the market to contract in the early 1990s.
   Sales figures for the first 10 days of September from the major
automakers are due today.
   ``There's a trend (among dealers) to get to a lower inventory,''
said Jake Kelderman, executive director of industry affairs for the
National Automobile Dealers Association in McLean, Va.
   He estimated that dealers would aim for a 45- to 60-day supply of
cars on their lots in the coming year. A 60-day supply used to be
the norm, he said.
   Each of the automakers has predicted 1989 model-year sales well
below the previous year's 15.8 million. The 1990 model year could be
worse yet, although no recession is forecast.
   Interest rates, which determine how much dealers pay to buy cars
on credit from the manufacturers, have been relatively steady
recently, but it still costs money to keep cars on the lot.
   Perhaps the biggest uncertainty is whether automakers will stay
in the incentive war they have been waging since early spring.
Dealers often carry more stock during heavy incentive periods than
during other times.
   ``You've got to really watch it now,'' Helfman said. ``There have
been a lot of negative (economic) articles and it's kind of getting
dealers scared.
   ``Manufacturers are cutting and slicing and dicing. They're
expecting very, very hard times,'' he said. ``It scares me that if
that's going to be the case, you've got some blood ready to be
spilled.''
   Helfman said he planned well and has just five 1989 cars on his
lot. But he's going to trim his upcoming orders to a 45-day target,
down slightly from previous years, and rely more on swapping cars
with other dealers as orders come in.
   ``I think I'd rather give up a little profit and find the car for
those people who want a special kind of car and deal out of other
people's inventory,'' he said.
   The Big Three _ General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler
Corp. _ trotted out enhanced incentive plans in late March and early
April, and during the last several months, manufacturers have
offered rebates to dealers, too, giving them the option of using
that money for advertising or to cut the price of 1989 cars.
   For automakers, that's a gamble with potentially high stakes as
the model year draws to a close, which for bookkeeping purposes
happens at the end of this month.
   ``I just hope that it works,'' said Herb Adcox, owner of Adcox
Chevrolet in Chattanooga, Tenn., a longtime General Motors dealer.
``If it doesn't, you've got a lot of dealers who are not going to
order (as many) 1990 models.
   ``Sometimes they call it `Generous Motors,''' he said. ``We're
going to find out just how generous they are.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
