<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 0311EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-BATBattle-Senate     09-13 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BAT Battle-Senate,0463</SECOND>
<HEAD>Packwood Urges Hands Off Policy in BAT Takeover Battle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The international tug of war over the British
conglomerate BAT Industries PLC lurched back to Capitol Hill with a
top Senate Republican urging the Bush administration to stay out of
the takeover fight.
   Sen. Bob Packwood of Oregon, in a letter to Secretary of State
James A. Baker disclosed Tuesday, said the U.S. government should
``take no action'' to avoid the appearance of ``unreasonable
government interference.''
   Packwood, ranking minority member of the Senate Finance
Committee, sent similar letters to Treasury Secretary Nicholas
Brady, U.S. Trade Representative Carla Hills and Securities and
Exchange Commission Chairman David S. Ruder.
   Ruder has already informed several congressmen that the SEC does
not believe it has the authority to do more than monitor the
takeover bid for BAT, which owns several major U.S. companies.
   The Packwood letter was the latest development in an
international legal and public relations tug of war since Hoylake
Investments Ltd., a consortium headed by Anglo-French financier Sir
James Goldsmith, launched a $21 billion bid for BAT, the world's
largest tobacco company, in late July.
   BAT, whose U.S. holdings include Brown &amp; Williamson Tobacco
Corp., the Saks Fifth Avenue and Marshall Field department stores
and Farmers Insurance Group, has vowed to fight the unsought
takeover.
   Packwood's Sept. 6 letter was in sharp contrast to a letter sent
to Baker last month, co-signed by more than 200 members of the House
and Senate, asking him to express their concern to the British
government about the multinational leveraged buyout.
   Senate aides, who spoke on condition that they not be identified,
said Packwood wrote the letter on his own and it did not reflect the
views of other Republicans on the committee.
   Because Goldsmith has a reputation for taking over companies and
then breaking them up and selling off the pieces, labor unions in
this country have condemned the takeover as a potential threat to
about 55,000 U.S. workers.
   And 209 members of Congress, both Democrats and Republicans,
wrote Baker about their concern the deal eventually would
``dismantle a company that is important to hundreds of U.S.
communities.''
   ``Although I am sympathetic to my colleagues' concerns about the
uncertainties new ownership of business entities in their
communities might raise, I frankly cannot see a proper role for the
federal government under U.S. law or the United States open
investment policy in this transaction,'' Packwood's letter said in
part.
   ``I would appreciate your assurances that the administration will
remain true to its open investment policy by taking no action in
this transaction that might be construed as unreasonable government
interference,'' he wrote.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
