<FIRST>r f PM-AMR-Airbus     09-13 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AMR-Airbus,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Airline Expected to Place Plane Orders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Airlines Inc. this fall will
place orders and options for 12 European-built Airbus airliners in a
transaction valued at nearly $850 million, a newspaper reported
today.
   Industry sources familiar with the negotiations told The Dallas
Morning News that the Fort Worth-based airline plans to place firm
orders for six Airbus A300-600R aircraft and get options for another
six.
   The sources told the newspaper an announcement for the order
could come within the next two months.
   However, officials at AMR Corp., the parent of American, and
Airbus Industries, based in Toulouse, France, would not comment on
whether a deal is near.
   American's vice president and treasurer, Michael Durham,
confirmed the airline has been looking at several aircraft,
including the Airbus, in search of a plane that could be used on
overwater routes to destinations in Europe and the Caribbean.
   Fulfilling that priority is the carrier's top priority in the
realm of aircraft acquisition, said Durham.
   The airline was the launch customer for the A300-600R and has
taken delivery of 25 copies of the model, officials said. The
airline uses the planes on its route system in the Caribbean, where
it has a hub at San Juan, Puerto Rico.
   The A300-600R is a newer, longer-range version of Airbus' A300
and has a price tag of $71 million, officials said.
</TEXT>
