<FIRST>r f PM-SEC-CoxResigns     09-13 0415</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SEC-Cox Resigns,0428</SECOND>
<HEAD>Economist Charles Cox Stepping Down From SEC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charles C. Cox, the first economist to be
appointed a member of the Securities and Exchange Commission, is
leaving the federal regulatory agency at the end of the month to
join a consulting firm.
   Cox, an SEC commissioner since 1983 and a former chief economist
of the agency, said in a brief letter to President Bush that his
resignation would take effect September 30, unless his numerical
replacement, Richard Breeden, assumes office before that date.
   The resignation of Cox had been expected because his term
technically had expired, but the announcement Tuesday marked the
first time Cox disclosed a departure date and post-SEC plans.
   Cox, 44, is joining Lexecon Inc., a Chicago-based economic
consulting concern, where he will be senior vice president in its
securities and finance group, responsible for directing studies in
securities, securities fraud and commodity futures trading.
   ``We are delighted that Charles Cox is joining Lexecon and
bringing his unique experience as an SEC commissioner and former
chief economist of the SEC to our firm,'' Lexecon President Andrew
Rosenfield said in a statement.
   The statement quoted Cox as saying ``I'm excited to be joining
Lexecon because it affords me the opportunity to do research in the
areas I've been dealing with at the SEC every day, issues like
securities fraud, insider trading, tender offers and the structure
of financial markets.''
   Lexecon analyzes many areas of business, including antitrust,
corporate reorganizations, securities regulation, health, safety and
environmental regulations, transportation and tax matters.
   A native of Missoula, Mont., Cox served as the SEC's chief
economist for a year before he was nominated as a commissioner by
then-President Reagan.
   Before joining the SEC staff, Cox served from 1980 to 1982 as a
professor of management at Texas A&amp;M University from 1972 to 1980 as
a professor of economics at Ohio State University.
   A 1967 University of Washington graduate, Cox has masters and
doctoral degrees in economics from the University of Chicago.
   Breeden, a Bush aide who played a leading White House role on the
savings and loan bailout legislation, was nominated Aug. 14 to
become an SEC commissioner. The administration has said that once
Breeden is confirmed by the Senate, Bush will designate him as
chairman.
   The Senate Banking Committee was to begin confirmation hearings
Thursday for Breeden.
   Current SEC Chairman David S. Ruder previously announced that he
also would step down Sept. 30.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890913-0268 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 0816EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-PartnersBarred     09-13 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Partners Barred,0501</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Accounting Partners Barred for 5 Years From SEC Work</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two partners in the accounting giant Coopers &amp;
Lybrand say they will appeal an order barring them from practicing
before the Securities and Exchange Commission for the next five
years.
   An administrative judge, in a ruling announced Tuesday, found
David J. Checkosky and Norman A. Aldrich had engaged in ``blatant,
serious'' unprofessional conduct.
   Following 30 days of hearings, 13 witnesses and 350 exhibits, the
administrative judge ruled in favor of the SEC, which claimed
Checkosky and Aldrich violated generally accepted standards of
auditing and principles of accounting in audits their firm did for
Savin Corp., which markets copy machines.
   Financial information provided in the audits ``portrayed the
company as a far more successful business enterprise than it was,''
according to the judge's ruling.
   ``It's fair to characterize the judge's decision as outrageous,''
said Geoffrey F. Aronow, an attorney for both men, who worked in
Coopers &amp; Lybrand's Stamford, Conn. headquarters.
   Aronow accused the Administrative Judge Brenda P. Murray of of
ignoring ``large portions of the evidence in the record'' and said
she ``has misapplied the applicable auditing principles and
misconstrued the underlying regulatory legal standards that apply
here.''
   He said his clients ``intend to appeal to the commission and
believe the propriety of their actions will ultimately be
vindicated.''
   There were no allegations of wrongdoing against Savin in the SEC
action, but several investors lawsuits are pending in Connecticut.
   A spokesman for Coopers &amp; Lybrand was not available for comment.
   Savin has been a client of Coopers &amp; Lybrand, one of the nation's
largest accounting firms, since the mid-1960s.
   The judge noted that annual billings from Savin totaled about
$340,000.
   ``For professional reasons, it was important to both men that the
client be pleased with their efforts. Unfortunately, pleasing the
client became their paramount consideration,'' she wrote in a
68-page opinion.
   Checkosky and Aldrich were the senior people assigned to the
Savin audits in question, for fiscal years 1981 through 1984.
Savin's fiscal year ran from May 1 to April 30.
   The SEC charged, among other things, that the two partners did
not adequately plan the audits; did not ``exercise due care'' in
examining Savin financial statements and did not obtain sufficient
credible evidence to back up the opinions they submitted in SEC
documents.
   According to the judge's finding, the partners wrongly claimed it
was proper to defer as start-up costs the costs Savin incurred in
developing a new copier.
   She found the SEC's evidence persuasive that during the time
covered by the audits, Savin should have listed its costs as
research and development expenses.
   By deferring rather than expensing, Savin kept these costs from
increasing its net operating loss during the period in question.
Instead these costs were included as assets on Savin's balance sheet
and increased owners' equity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890913-0269 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 0822EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Steel-Inland-Nippon     09-13 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Steel-Inland-Nippon,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Steel Giants Plan to Expand Joint Venture with $450 Million Facility</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLIFF EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Executives of Inland Steel Industries Inc. and
Nippon Steel Corp. say customers are already lining up to purchase
coated steel from a soon-to-be-built $450 million facility in
Indiana.
   The two steel-coating lines, called I-N Kote, should strengthen
Inland's position as a supplier to the appliance and auto
industries, primary markets for corrosion-resistant coated steel
products, said Frank Luerssen, chairman and chief executive officer
of the company.
   The move will ``measureably strengthen our joint commitment to
meet the needs for differentiated steel products in the American
market,'' Luerssen said at a news conference Tuesday. ``We now see
customers lining up to get their share of the materials.''
   The two production lines will have an annual capacity of 900
finished tons and will be constructed next to a nearly completed New
Carlisle, Ind., plant, where Inland and Nippon are finishing work on
a continuous cold-rolling mill called I-N Tek.
   I-N Tek and Inland Steel's Indiana Harbor Works in East Chicago,
Ind., will provide all the sheet steel for I-N Kote.
   The $900 million complex being built at New Carlisle, Ind., by
Chicago-based Inland and Tokyo-based Nippon is believed to represent
the largest spending program so far for an American-Japanese joint
venture in the United States.
   The new coating lines will take the cold-rolled steel produced at
the plant and coat it, using an electrogalvanizing process or a
hot-dip line.
   Automakers use galvanized steel's higher-grade sheets on exposed
car panels and hot-dipped sheets for such things as panels for light
truck beds.
   Inland, the sixth-largest steel company in the nation, supplies
the three major U.S. carmakers and major Japanese auto manufacturers.
   Nippon is the largest steel maker in the world, exporting about 8
million tons a year.
   Hiroshi Saito, president of Nippon, said the venture with Inland
represented a joint commitment to Japanese carmakers who have built
U.S. plants and to American companies with a demand for the
materials.
   Saito said the new plant will be entirely operational in 1991,
with I-N Tek beginning operations next year.
   Such ventures, he said, work to ease tensions about the trade
imbalance between the United States and Japan.
   ``I am confident that this undertaking will play a major symbolic
role as a constructive attempt to resolve issues between the two
economies through mutual understanding and cooperation,'' Saito said
in a prepared statement.
   Nippon and Inland will contribute $150 million each to I-N Kote,
with the rest sponsored by debt-financing. Inland is assuming 60
percent of the construction costs for I-N Tek, also a joint venture.
   Inland this year has experienced three consecutive quarterly
earnings declines, blamed partly on seasonal softness in orders, but
Luerssen predicted a small gain for the company's fourth quarter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
