<FIRST>r f BC-Japan-NTTStock     09-13 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Japan-NTT Stock,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Drops Plans for New Sale of NTT Stock</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Finance Ministry said Wednesday it has dropped
plans to sell 1.95 million shares of Nippon Telegraph and Telephone
Corp. stock this year.
   Finance Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto told a news conference the
decision was based on various factors, including the slump in NTT
share prices.
   The government had planned to sell 1.95 million NTT shares in
fiscal 1989, which ends next March 31, after Parliament approved the
sale to finance public works and the redemption of outstanding
government bonds, said a Finance Ministry official, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   Since NTT, the former government monopoly in telecommunications,
was turned into a private firm on April 1, 1985, the government has
sold 5.4 million shares, 35 percent of the shares it owned.
   In April 1987, two months after the stock was first offered, a
single share of NTT stock was worth 3.18 million yen, or about
$21,600. NTT stock closed at 1.51 million yen, or about $10,272,
Wednesday.
   NTT posted a 14.3 percent decline in unconsolidated pretax
profits for the fiscal year that ended March 31.
   Officials attributed the decline to lower long-distance revenues
caused by competition from new entrants in the market, and to a
slump in revenue from data communications services.
   The company's chairman, Hisashi Shinto, resigned last December
after being implicated in the Recruit scandal, and was arrested in
March on bribery charges.
   The Recruit Co., an information services conglomerate, has been
accused of using cut-price stock sales and political donations to
try to buy influence with a wide range of politicians, bureaucrats
and businessmen. Although NTT now is a private firm, its employees
are treated the same as public officials under laws covering bribery.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
