<DOCNO> AP890913-0272 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 0914EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Jaguar     09-13 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Jaguar,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Luxury Auto Maker Posts Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Luxury auto maker Jaguar PLC on Wednesday posted an
after-tax loss of $1.7 million for the first half of the year,
citing a decline in U.S. sales, adverse currency factors, and a
large depreciaton charge.
   These negative factors were partly offset by improvements in cost
efficiency, the company said.
   The loss for the six months ended June 30 compared with an
after-tax profit of $21 million, or 11 cents a share, in the same
period a year earlier.
   The company said its pre-tax profit sank to $2.2 million from $35
million, a year ago.
   Sales climbed 3 percent to $869 million, from $832 million.
   The depreciation charge for plant and equipment came to $55
million, up from $42 million in the year-earlier period.
   Jaguar said sales in its key U.S. market deteriorated sharply
during the second-quarter, and that they were well below
expectations. U.S. sales rose 14 percent to $399 million in the
period.
   The company said that fiercer competition forced it to raise its
marketing expenditure in the region. Jaguar is forecasting U.S.
sales of around 20,000 cars in the current year, compared with
20,700 in 1988.
   Jaguar said half-year sales in Britain were on a par with year
earlier levels, but that there was ``some uncertainly about overall
demand'' due to the country's high interest rates.
   Jaguar said it hoped ``to maintain good sales progress'' in
continental Europe, where sales declined 17 percent to $109 million.
   Overall, Jaguar said it didn't envisage any improvement in its
underlying trading conditions during the rest of the year. However,
the company said the introduction of new models was expected to
enhance demand.
   Jaguar did not produce quarterly results. It isn't required to
under British law.
</TEXT>
