<SECOND>PM-Sears Tower, 1st Ld-Writehtur, f0044,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sale of Sears Tower Hits Snag: Report</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf pvs, A Sears ..., with one graf to UPDATE with
Sears having on comment. Picks up 4th graf pvs, The retailing ...</UNK>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sears, Roebuck and Co.'s plans to sell the Sears
Tower in Chicago, the world's tallest building, to Canadian
developer Olympia &amp; York Developments Ltd. have hit a snag, the Wall
Street Journal reported today.
   The two sides had prepared to sign a deal on Tuesday but couldn't
decide on who would bear tax costs of a reappraisal expected to
follow the sale, the newspaper said, quoting unidentified
individuals close to the negotiations.
   Sears spokesman Douglas Fairweather said the company would have
no comment on the report.
   The retailing giant had announced last October that it would sell
the downtown Chicago landmark as part of a corporate restructuring,
and it reportedly began serious talks with Olympia &amp; York earlier
this summer.
   Toronto-based Olympia &amp; York, according to media reports, had
agreed to pay around $1 billion for the 110-story building and was
considering signing British-based publisher Maxwell Communications
Corp. as its anchor tenant. Sears' Merchandise Group is currently
the tower's anchor tenant.
   Sears had agreed to continue to pay rent for six years on the
space it was planning to vacate but it said it was unwilling to
shoulder any increased taxes, according to the Journal.
</TEXT>
