<FIRST>u f PM-PetroleumReport     09-13 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Petroleum Report,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Monthly Figures Show Sharp Decline in Domestic Production, Rise in
Imports</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Domestic crude oil production dropped 6.6 percent in August
compared with a year earlier, falling to the lowest daily output
level in more than 25 years, the American Petroleum Institute
reported today.
   The trade group's monthly breakdown of supply and demand in the
United States also said August imports of oil and petroleum products
rose 16.3 percent over a year earlier and supplied nearly half of
American requirements for the second straight month.
   The API report reflected both falling domestic production and a
rising American dependence on foreign energy sources, trends that
have resurrected fears in Washington of an excessive reliance on
imports.
   The report said year-to-date domestic oil production has been
falling at an average annual rate of 5 percent to 6 percent compared
with 1988, nearly double the decline of 3.2 percent for the previous
three years.
   The report said it was clear that production in all oil-producing
states has been declining rapidly, even after adjusting for
temporary production curtailments in Alaska caused by the March 24
Exxon oil spill.
   U.S. crude production averaged 7.545 million barrels a day in
August, vs. 8.079 million barrels a day in August 1988, the report
said. The last full year in which average daily domestic crude
production dipped as low was in 1963.
   Imports of crude oil and petroleum products in August totaled
8.559 million barrels a day compared with 7.361 million barrels a
day in August 1988. The import level nearly matched the July level
of 8.6 million barrels a day, keeping total imports' share of
domestic deliveries near the 50 percent mark. Among other key
statistics in the report:
   _ Domestic demand for oil and petroleum products declined
slightly in August, to 17.438 million barrels a day from 17.482
million in August 1988.
   _ Domestic refineries operated at 90.3 percent of capacity in
August, compared with 87.4 percent a year earlier.
   The API, based in Washington, represents 200 corporations in the
petroleum and related products industries, including producers,
refiners, marketers and transporters of crude oil, lubricating oil,
gasoline and natural gas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
