<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   09-13 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grain Futures Retreat Following Bearish Crop Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices retreated
slightly this morning on the Chicago Board of Trade following a
government crop report construed as neutral to slightly bearish.
   The Agriculture Department report released late Tuesday projected
slightly larger 1989 corn and wheat harvests than traders had
expected _ 7.32 billion bushels of corn and 2.06 billion bushels of
wheat.
   The USDA's soybean crop estimate of 1.89 billion bushels was in
line with expectations.
   ``There's really not a whole lot in these reports that's going to
impact these markets,'' said Walter Spilka, a grain analyst in New
York with Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co.
   He said the markets were focusing instead on slack foreign demand
for U.S. grains and speculation that the USDA will take action soon
to increase wheat acreage.
   In early trading, wheat futures were \ cent to 2\ cents lower
with the contract for delivery in September at $3.92} a bushel; corn
was } cent to 1{ cents lower with September at $2.35{ a bushel; oats
were unchanged to 1{ cents lower with September at $1.36 a bushel;
soybeans were 2\ cents lower to 1 cent higher with September at
$6.01 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were higher while pork futures were mixed in early
trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .05 cent to .32 cent higher with October at
72.47 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .08 cent to .58 cent higher
with September at 83.20 cents a pound; hog futures were .15 cent
lower to .30 cent higher with October at 39.50 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were .02 cent to .83 cent lower with February at 46
cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled higher on Tuesday while pork futures were
mixed.
</TEXT>
