<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 1310EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-CurrencyTrading     09-13 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Currency Trading,0292</SECOND>
<HEAD>Currency Trading in U.S. Doubles to $129 Billion a Day</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Currency trading in the United States has more
than doubled in the last three years to about $129 billion a day,
the Federal Reserve Bank of New York said today.
   Growth in trading volume has far outpaced the growth in the U.S.
economy and the expansion of world trade, said Gretchen Greene, a
senior vice president at the central bank.
   U.S. businesses need to trade currencies in order to turn their
earnings from overseas sales or investments back into dollars, or to
obtain foreign currencies for spending in foreign countries.
   But the vast majority of the volume of currency trading is simple
speculation, in which banks and other traders buy currencies they
expect to rise and sell ones they expect to fall.
   By taking on extra risk in the hope of profit, the speculators
allow companies that actually need foreign currencies to lay off
risk by hedging.
   Although there are no precise estimates of the amount of
speculation that goes on, Ms. Greene said banks did only 12 percent
of their trading volume with parties that were not themselves
involved in wholesale currency trading, such as industrial companies.
   Based on a monthlong survey in April, the average daily volume of
currency trading in the United States was $128.9 billion, up 120
percent from $58.5 billion in March 1986, the last time the survey
was conducted.
   The survey covered trading done by 127 banks and 14 non-bank
financial institutions, which are believed to be almost all the ones
actively involved in currency trading.
   The West German mark remained the most actively traded foreign
currency.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
