<FIRST>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     09-13 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower, Gold Little Changed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: A version for AMs is planned by 5:30 p.m. EDT.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar drifted lower Wednesday as traders
marked time until the release of the next batch of U.S. economic
data.
   Gold prices were little changed in thin trading.
   The market has been waiting all week for fresh economic news to
give the dollar direction. The most important figures are the U.S.
trade data for July, due out on Friday. There is also the potential
for some market movement on Thursday when Washington releases the
August retail sales data.
   ``There is a rally waiting to happen,'' said William Simpson, an
economist at Barclays Bank.
   In Tokyo, the dollar fell to 146.70 Japanese yen from 146.73 yen
at Tuesday's close. Later, in London, it traded at 146.90 yen.
   In London, the British pound rose to $.5530 from $1.5470 late
Tuesday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late rates
Tuesday, included: 1.9800 West German marks, down from 1.9880;
1.7095 Swiss francs, down from 1.7160; 6.6805 French francs, down
from 6.6950; 2.2300 Dutch guilders, down from 2.2330; 1,419.00
Italian lire, down from 1,421.75 and 1.1855 Canadian dollars, down
from 1.1892.
   Gold traded at $358.50 per troy ounce in London late Wednesday,
down from $358.75 bid late Tuesday. In Zurich, gold fell to $358.25
an ounce from $358.55 late Tuesday.
   In Hong Kong, gold closed at a bid of $359.93 an ounce, unchanged
from Tuesday's closing bid price.
   Silver bullion traded in London at a bid of $5.08 a troy ounce,
unchanged from late Tuesday.
