<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 1344EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-SmokingBan 1stLd-Writethru f0077 09-13 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Smoking Ban, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0077,0411</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tobacco State Lawmakers Moving Against Airline Smoking Ban</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 3 grafs new with vote set for Thursday; picks up 2nd graf
pvs, We're willing ... Also moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate supporters of a proposed smoking ban on
all airline flights today scheduled a Thursday vote aimed at
stopping tobacco state lawmakers from blocking the legislation.
   The vote was scheduled by Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell,
D-Maine, after opponents of the ban threatened to hold up unrelated
spending bills unless a compromise was reached.
   Tobacco state senators had said earlier that rather than the
stronger restrictions, they would accept a permanent ban on smoking
aboard airline flights of two hours or less.
   ``We're willing to make that permanent,'' Sen. Wendell Ford,
D-Ky., said of the current smoking ban on two-hour flights, which is
due to expire next April.
   But he said he would continue opposing a provision permanently
extending the ban to all flights, language that is part of a bill
providing $11.9 billion for next year's federal transportation
programs.
   ``This one will take basically a week to get through,'' Ford said
of the transportation bill. That would delay approval of other
spending legislation awaiting Senate approval, he said.
   Congressional leaders want to complete work on the transportation
measure, and 12 other spending bills, by the Oct. 1 start of fiscal
1990.
   But the author of the permanent smoking prohibition on all
flights, Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J., continued to defend his
measure and called on opponents of the ban to let work on the bill
proceed.
   ``If they have a case to make they ought to make it and let us
vote on it,'' Lautenberg said.
   The House voted Aug. 3 to make the ban on two-hour flights
permanent. Tobacco industry supporters have said they are willing to
accept that if Lautenberg will drop his insistence on the broader
restrictions.
   Lautenberg, supported by health groups and airline unions, argues
that non-smoking passengers risk cancer and other diseases because
of the cigarette smoke they breathe in airline cabins.
   The tobacco industry has argued that there is no convincing
evidence that such smoke is dangerous and that there are other
chemicals besides cigarette fumes in the recirculated air of
airliner cabins.
   Tobacco supporters in Congress have also said the restrictions
would hurt tobacco growers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
