<DOCNO> AP890913-0288 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 1352EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-NII-Noranda     09-13 0178</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-NII-Noranda,0187</SECOND>
<HEAD>National Intergroup Sells Aluminum Unit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National Intergroup Inc. said Wednesday it will
sell the rolling division of its National Aluminum Corp. subsidiary
to Norandal USA Inc., a subsidiary of Noranda Inc. of Toronto, for
$117.7 million.
   National Aluminum's unit employs about 500 workers in Caldwell,
Ohio; Salisbury, N.C.; and Newport, Ark.
   National Intergroup said the rolling division contributed about
$15.2 million in profit on sales of $204.6 million to National
Aluminum in fiscal 1989.
   ``The proposed sale...is in keeping with our previously stated
strategy to divest our metals businesses and to focus on our
long-term strategy of being a leader in wholesale distribution,''
said National Intergroup Chairman Howard M. Love.
   He said selling off National Aluminum by divisions was better
than selling it whole.
   Love said National Intergroup is ``continuing to explore its
options'' for National Aluminum's extrusion division in Anniston,
Ala., and its 55 percent-owned primary smelter in Hawesville, Ky.
   Love said the sale is expected to result in a non-recurring,
third-quarter gain of about $30 million after taxes and expenses.
</TEXT>
