<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 1517EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-MGM-UA 1stLd-Writethru f0115 09-13 0571</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-MGM-UA, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0115,0587</SECOND>
<HEAD>MGM-UA Gets $1.35 Billion Buyout Bid 2 Weeks Before Qintex Deal Set
to Close</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout, CORRECTS Qintex bid to $1.2 billion to account
for preferred stock and changes Qintex Entertainment to Qintex Australia;
including new details and analyst comment.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By E. SCOTT RECKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   MGM-UA Communications Co. said today
that it had received a $1.35 billion buyout offer from an
unidentified bidder that would apparently compete with an Australian
company's offer of $1.2 billion.
   MGM-UA identified the prospective buyer only as a New York Stock
Exchange-listed company who it said had offered $23.16 per share of
MGM-UA common stock and $18 per share of preferred stock.
   The proposal values the stock at aout $1.35 billion, or about
$150 million more than the bid for the same stock that Qintex
Australia Ltd. has made through an affiliate.
   Andrew Wallach, an analyst who follows MGM-UA for Drexel Burnham
Lambert, said speculation on the buyer focused on media giants who
have shown interest in MGM-UA in the past.
   They include 20th Century Fox, owned by Rupert Murdoch's News
Corp., Sony Corp., The Walt Disney Co. and MCA Inc.
   Qintex Australia owns 43 percent of Qintex Entertainment Inc., a
TV company that financed part of the CBS miniseries ``Lonesome
Dove'' and bills itself as Australia's largest TV production and
distribution company.
   When assumption of debt and other factors are considered, the
Qintex bid totals about $1.35 billion, according to Qintex
Entertainment Executive Vice President John Lloyd. If the same
factors applied on the new offer _ details in MGM-UA's announcement
were sketchy _ it would total $1.5 billion, Lloyd said.
   He said Qintex was waiting to learn details about the new offer
and would have no immediate comment about it.
   The Qintex deal was to have closed by the end of this month. In
essence, it would split the present MGM-UA Communications Co., and
leave majority shareholder Kirk Kerkorian in control of the MGM
portion of the business.
   By the time Kerkorian bought back the MGM businesses, Qintex
would have paid about $600 million for United Artists.
   MGM-UA spokeswoman Mary Hardy said the company's board will meet
Thursday to consider the latest offer. MGM-UA shareholders were
scheduled to vote on the Qintex offer at a meeting Sept. 23. MGM-UA
has agreed to pay Qintex $18 million if it accepts another offer.
   Ms. Hardy declined to say whether the latest offer had been
expected by the board or Kerkorian, the Los Angeles billionaire who
owns 82 percent of MGM-UA's 50.6 million common shares of stock and
all but a tiny fraction of MGM-UA's 10.1 million shares of preferred
stock.
   MGM-UA said nothing about the financing involved in the latest
offer.
   Qintex has assembled a group of 10 Asian and European investors
to help finance its deal. The investors would buy stock worth $500
million, while Qintex Group would buy shares worth $100 million.
   The renamed United Artists Corp. would be the first big American
motion picture studio to pass into foreign hands.
   United Artists, one of the five dominant U.S. movie studios,
holds the rights to 4,000 movies, including the ``The Pink Panther''
and James Bond series and Rocky films.
   Kerkorian's ``new'' MGM that he would buy back from Qintex would
include movie and TV production assets and a library of 34 recent
films, including ``Moonstruck'' and ``A Fish Called Wanda.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
