<HEAD>Dollar Down, Gold Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Precedes LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar declined Wednesday against all key
foreign currencies in quiet trading.
   Gold prices rose slightly after falling overseas.
   On the New York Commodity Exchange, gold bullion for current
delivery settled at $359.90 a troy ounce, up 40 cents from Tuesday.
Republic National Bank quoted a late bid for gold of $358.70 an
ounce, up 20 cents.
   Linda McLaughlin, a currency trader for Chemical New York Capital
Markets Group, attributed the dollar's decline largely to renewed
concerns that West Germany and Japan might soon raise their interest
rates, and that would help strengthen the currencies in those
countries.
   But she said Wednesday's trading was relatively light as many
dealers preferred to keep a low profile in anticipation of a spate
of upcoming economic data.
   The government is scheduled to release its report on August
retail sales on Thursday. Reports due out Friday include August
producer prices and industrial production and July merchandise trade.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell to 146.70 Japanese yen from 146.73 yen Tuesday. It
traded at 146.90 yen in London, and at 146.40 yen in New York, down
from 146.905.
   The dollar lost ground against the British pound. In London, the
pound rose to $1.5530 from $1.5470 late Tuesday. Sterling fetched
$1.5585 in New York, up from $1.5485.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Tuesday's
quotes, included: 1.9725 West German marks, down from 1.9865; 1.6990
Swiss francs, down from 1.7140; 6.6525 French francs, down from
6.6915; 1.18405 Canadian dollars, down from 1.18725; and 1,415.00
Italian lire, down from 1,422.125.
   Late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late rates Tuesday,
included: 1.9800 West German marks, down from 1.9880; 1.7095 Swiss
francs, down from 1.7160; 6.6805 French francs, down from 6.6950;
2.2300 Dutch guilders, down from 2.2330; 1.1855 Canadian dollars,
down from 1.1892; and 1,419.00 Italian lire, down from 1,421.75.
   Gold traded at $358.50 an ounce in London late Wednesday, down
from $358.75 bid Tuesday. In Zurich, gold fell to $358.25 an ounce
from $358.55.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold closed at a bid of $359.93 an ounce,
unchanged from Tuesday.
   Silver prices were little changed. On New York's Comex, silver
bullion for current delivery fell to $5.067 from $5.069 Tuesday.
Silver closed in London at $5.08 an ounce, unchanged.
