<SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market yielded to a late-afternoon
barrage of selling Wednesday, sending the Dow Jones industrial
average below 2,700 for the first time in three weeks.
   Brokers attributed the selloff partly to rumors, which were
quickly denied, that a major brokerage firm was facing large losses
from a position in high-yield ``junk'' bonds.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell 27.74 points to
2,679.52, closing below 2,700 for the first time since it stood at
2,678.11 on Aug. 23.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 5 to 3 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
555 up, 912 down and 526 unchanged.
   The market's drop in the last hour of trading came as rumors
spread that Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. was sustaining losses from holdings
in bonds of a unit of Campeau Corp., which is undergoing a financial
restructuring that includes plans to sell its Bloomingdale's
department store chain.
   Merrill Lynch denied that it faced any losses in the junk bond
sector, and said it owned no bonds related to Campeau. But Merrill
stock dropped 1] to 32~.
   Otherwise, analysts said traders were hoping for some positive
news later in the week to serve as a market stimulus.
   For instance, the monthly data on the producer price index of
finished goods, due out Friday, is expected to show no change or a
modest decline in that measure of inflationary pressures.
   But some observers said it may take something more surprising to
stir stocks out of their recent torpor.
   And with prices still not far below the record highs they reached
a couple of weeks ago, talk persisted on Wall Street that the market
might be heading for a ``correction,'' or period of retrenchment.
   Among actively traded blue chips, American Telephone &amp; Telegraph
dropped { to 40; International Business Machines 1{ to 115]; Exxon ~
to 44{, and General Electric 1] to 55{.
   MGM-UA Communications climbed 1{ to 21\. The company said it
received a takeover bid from another NYSE-listed concern it didn't
identify.
   Circle K Corp. was the day's biggest percentage loser among NYSE
issues, down 1} at 7}. The company said it had ended efforts to
solicit takeover proposals without attracting a bidder, and
suspended its dividend.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 175.33 million
shares, up from 142.14 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in those
stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter market,
totaled 208.69 million shares.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market lost $23.08 billion, or 0.67
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks fell
1.59 to 192.29.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index dropped 3.86 to 395.38, and
S&amp;P's 500-stock composite index was down 3.24 at 345.46.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market dipped
.03 to 471.83. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index closed at 383.77, down .77.
