<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     09-13 0718</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0745</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cotton Futures Skyrocket On Dwindling World Supply Outlook</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Cotton futures prices skyrocketed Wednesday on the New York
Cotton Exchange, climbing as much as 2 cents a pound, the permitted
daily limit, on fresh signs of shrinking world supplies.
   On other markets, grain and soybean futures fell steeply; most
energy futures advanced and precious metals, livestock and meat
futures were mixed.
   Cotton futures settled 1.13 cents to 2 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in October at 73.77 cents a pound.
   The rally was rooted partly in Tuesday's Agriculture Department
crop report, which painted an ultimately bullish scenario for
cotton, although it was not apparent at first blush.
   For starters, the USDA estimated the 1989 cotton crop at 12.28
million bales, which represents a 20 percent decline from the 1988
harvest but an increase of 450,000 bales from the agency's August
estimate.
   The estimate was higher than expected, which would have been a
bearish signal _ except that the USDA also reduced by 400,000 bales
its estimate of the U.S. cotton stockpile as of last July 31,
offsetting the increased harvest projection.
   The bullish news came in the USDA's new projection for world
cotton stocks as of next July 1: 25.2 million bales, 1 million less
than the agency had predicted a month earlier.
   World supplies are dwindling, analysts said, because of poor
growing weather both in the United States and abroad.
   ``The foreign crops are not doing well, especially in China and
the Soviet Union,'' said Ernest Simon, cotton specialist in New York
with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   The U.S. crop, which was punished earlier this year by too much
rain in the Southeast and too little in Texas, has been taking
another beating this week due to cold, wet weather in the high
plains of Texas.
   Prospects for at least another day of harsh weather contributed
to cotton's rally.
   Grain and soybean futures fell sharply on the Chicago Board of
Trade in selling sparked by a higher 1989 wheat crop estimate and
expectations for an increase in 1990 wheat acreage.
   The USDA raised its projection for the 1989 wheat harvest to 2.06
billion bushels from 2.04 billion, surprising traders who had
expected little change in the number.
   Further selling was linked to persistent rumors that the
Agriculture Department is preparing to revise its 1990 wheat program
to allow farmers to increase spring wheat planting, which is already
underway, by as much as 10 million acres.
   Walter Spilka, an analyst in New York with Smith Barney, Harris
Upham &amp; Co., said that despite the improved 1989 harvest outlook,
U.S. wheat stocks are relatively low.
   He said USDA leaders are worried the United States may have to
reduce its wheat exports unless it can ensure an increase in
supplies.
   Wheat futures settled 8 cents to 14 cents lower with September at
$3.85 a bushel; corn was 2{ cents to 5{ cents lower with September
at $2.33} a bushel; oats were 2{ cents to 4 cents lower with
September at $1.34 a bushel; soybeans were 5 cents to 15{ cents
lower with September at $5.86{ a bushel.
   Crude-oil futures traded above $20 a barrel on the New York
Mercantile Exchange but closed below that level as the technically
inspired rally ran out of gas.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 1 cent to 16 cents
higher with October at $19.86 a barrel; heating oil was .10 cent
lower to .25 cent higher with October at 55.46 cents a gallon;
unleaded gasoline was .21 cent to .86 cent higher with October at
57.75 cents a gallon.
   Gold futures rose slightly while silver inched lower on New
York's Commodity Exchange.
   Gold settled 20 cents higher across the board with October at
$361.30 a troy ounce; silver was 0.2 cent to .06 cent lower with
September at $5.067 a troy ounce.
   On the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, live cattle futures settled
.20 cent lower to .15 cent higher with October at 72.02 cents a
pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent to .38 cent higher with September
at 83 cents a pound; hogs were .03 cent lower to .55 cent higher
with October at 39.75 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .20
cent to .32 cent lower with February at 46.25 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
