<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     09-13 0188</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0196</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Futures Rise on Increased Demand</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Demand for gasoline and heating oil boosted
energy futures higher in brisk trading Wednesday.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the October contract for
wholesale unleaded gasoline rose 0.86 cent to close at 57.75 cents a
gallon while heating oil for October delivery picked up 0.09 cent to
settle at 55.46 cents a gallon.
   On Tuesday, gasoline fell 0.18 cent while heating oil slipped
0.73 cent.
   Prices for refined products moved higher as demand stepped up in
several markets across the country, said Andrew Lebow, an energy
futures analyst with E.D.&amp;F. Man International Futures Inc.
   The strength carried over to the crude oil market, Lebow said.
When demand for gas and heating oil goes up, demand for crude _ from
which the products are refined _ also increases.
   The October contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude oil, rose 16 cents to $19.86 a 42-gallon barrel.
The contract fell 6 cents on Tuesday.
   Lebow said prices were also supported by reports of production
problems at a new refinery in Norway.
</TEXT>
