<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 2045EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-TexasInstruments-HDTV     09-13 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Texas Instruments-HDTV,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>TI Signs Agreement To Acquire Japanese HDTV Technology</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's public broadcasting organization, NHK, will
sell some of its high-definition television technology to Texas
Instruments Inc. so the company can design chips for advanced
televisions, the companies said Wednesday.
   Terms of the agreement were not disclosed, except TI's statement
that it will pay NHK for the transfer of its decoder technology. The
chips from Texas Instruments' Japanese arm will be sold to Japanese
television manufacturers.
   ``This agreement with NHK gives TI the system knowledge needed to
design integrated circuits for advanced televisions,'' said Akira
Ishikawa, TI's semiconductor group senior vice president and
president of TI Japan.
   ``TI will take this resulting technology and work with customers
in Japan, Europe and America.''
   TI said the agreement is part of an ``overall strategy to focus
and penetrate the advanced vision systems segment of the
semiconductor consumer market.''
   Meanwhile, TI also announced it plans to take a $10 million
charge in the third quarter because of severance pay and overhead
costs involved in last month's voluntary reduction plan.
   The Dallas-based company also said it expects capital spending to
exceed the $800 million previously announced. In addition, research
and development, including some funded by customers, should reach $1
billion this year.
   The formal name of NHK is Nihon Hoso Kyokai.
</TEXT>
