<DOCNO> AP890913-0306 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 2047EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Philippines-Westinghouse     09-13 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-Westinghouse,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Refuses to Dismiss Remaining Claims by Aquino Against Westinghouse</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge refused Wednesday to dismiss
civil charges that Westinghouse Electric Corp. and a New Jersey
engineering firm bribed former Philippines President Ferdinand E.
Marcos in order to win a nuclear power plant contract.
   The ruling by U.S. District Judge Dickinson R. Debevoise keeps
alive a major claim in a broad lawsuit by the present Philippine
government.
   Debevoise in May shifted 13 of 15 counts of the suit, filed six
months before, to arbitration. The International Chamber of Commerce
will consider breach of contract, negligence, fraud, antitrust and
other claims.
   The suit said massive corruption surrounded the project, a $2.3
billion, 600-megawatt plant on the Bataan peninsula begun in 1976
but that has yet to open.
   The Philippine government is seeking recovery of its investment,
damages and the alleged bribes, which the Philippines say were
passed to Marcos through ``consultants'' linked to him.
   Pittsburgh-based Westinghouse, the nation's leading nuclear power
plant producer, in turn is seeking $30 million in fees through the
chamber's arbitration court. The other defendant is Burns &amp; Roe
Enterprises Inc. of Oradell.
   Both companies have denied that consultant fees were bribes.
   At Wednesday's hearing, Westinghouse attorney David Boies argued
that because Marcos was the Philippines' absolute power at the time,
a U.S. federal court was not the place to determine whether the
payments caused him to violate his duty to the nation.
   ``Marcos was Marcos; whatever he was doing he was doing with
absolute impunity long before Westinghouse came on the scene,''
Boies said.
   Mark Augenblick, an attorney for the Philippines, argued that the
scope of the deposed dictator's power at the time was not important.
   Marcos's wrongdoing ``does not mean that the Philippine
constitution and the laws of the Philippines do not apply,'' said
Augenblick.
   To throw out the remaining two bribe-related counts ``would send
a message that one can with impunity bribe the president of a
foreign country and avoid civil penalties in the United States,'' he
said.
   Debevoise called the defendants' arguments a ``semantic
exercise,'' ruling that the legality or illegality of a regime is
not the issue. What is important, he said, is whether such payments
were acceptable under applicable law.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
