<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 2052EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-AlleghenyInternational     09-13 0171</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Allegheny International,0178</SECOND>
<HEAD>Company Predicts Continued Losses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allegheny International Inc. likely will lose
money for another two years after emerging from protection under
Chapter 11 of federal bankruptcy laws, the company said Wednesday.
   Company officials filed the projection, which they termed
speculative and highly conditional, with the U.S. Bankruptcy Court
as exhibits to its latest reorganization proposal.
   Officials said the company will return to profitability in 1992
with a profit of $6.3 million on sales of $983 million.
   Meanwhile, management said, it expected the company to lose $32.9
million on sales of $879 million in fiscal 1990 and to lose $5.9
million on sales of $930 million in fiscal 1991.
   The Pittsburgh-based firm, best known for manufacturing Sunbeam
and Oster small appliances, has not made an annual profit since
1984. It has reported aggregate losses of more than $600 million
since.
   The company has filed six reorganization plans with the
bankruptcy court, but the first five failed to win approval. The
sixth is pending before the court.
</TEXT>
