<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 2228EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-MGM-UA 1stLd-Writethru f0283 09-13 0814</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-MGM-UA, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0283,0833</SECOND>
<HEAD>MGM-UA Gets $1.35 Billion Buyout Bid 2 Weeks Before Qintex Deal to
Close</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with confirmation that Murdoch
made the bid. Picks up 10th graf pvs, `MGM-UA's most ...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By E. SCOTT RECKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rupert Murdoch entered the bidding
for MGM-UA Communication Co. on Wednesday with an offer that values
the company at $1.8 billion, topping a rival $1.64 billion bid by an
Australian entertainment group.
   The bid was made by the media magnate's News Corp. Ltd. and its
20th Century Fox Film Corp. subsidiary.
   Analysts said Murdoch apparently wants MGM-UA's huge film
library, which he could use for his Fox TV network here and Sky
Television satellite operation in Europe.
   MGM-UA had agreed to sell its United Artists assets to an
affiliate of Qintex Australia Ltd. by the end of this month in a
deal that valued MGM-UA's stock at about $1.24 billion, $160 million
less than the new offer of $1.4 billion, according to MGM-UA
spokeswoman Mary Hardy.
   She said the buyer would also assume about $400 million in debt.
   MGM-UA said Fox and News Corp. had offered $23.16 for each of the
approximately 53 million shares of MGM-UA common stock and $18 per
share for the more than 10 million shares of preferred stock. Qintex
had offered $20 for each common share and $18 per preferred share.
   Shares of MGM-UA common stock closed Tuesday at $19.75 on the New
York Stock Exchange, a high for the year, then surged to $21.125 per
share by the close of trading Wednesday. Qintex plunged $2 to close
at $6 per share Wednesday in over-the-counter trading.
   Confirmation of a rumor earlier Wednesday that Murdoch was the
bidder did not come until after the market closed.
   News Corp.'s American Depositary Shares are traded on the NYSE,
and slipped 12{ cents to $25 a share Wednesday. Each News Corp. ADS
is equivalent to two shares of the Australian company's common
shares.
   Fox spokesman Dennis Petroskey confirmed the offer, but refused
to discuss how it would be financed or other issues, saying only,
``We are in discussions with MGM-UA. We will have no further comment
until the discussions are concluded.''
   Ms. Hardy said MGM-UA's board will meet Thursday to consider the
latest offer. MGM-UA shareholders were scheduled to vote on the
Qintex offer at a meeting Sept. 23. MGM-UA has agreed to pay Qintex
$18 million if it accepts another offer.
   MGM-UA's most attractive assets are its film libraries. United
Artists has nearly 1,000 films, including ``Rain Man,''
``Betrayed,'' ``The Living Daylights,'' ``Baby Boom'' and the
``Rocky'' pictures. Foreign home video distribution rights to the
3,000-film MGM library are also up for grabs; cable TV magnate Ted
Turner already owns the other rights to those movies.
   ``The libraries throw off $90 to $100 million (a year) in cash
flow,'' said Andrew Wallach, an analyst who follows MGM-UA for
Drexel Burnham Lambert. ``If you're paying $1.4 billion for it,
that's about 14 times operating cash flow, aside from any other
assets.''
   He said that would make MGM-UA an attractive target for an
aggressive bidder such as Murdoch, who needs programming for his Fox
TV network here and for his British Sky Channel, the four-channel
satellite service into which he already has sunk $120 million in its
first five months.
   The Australian-born Murdoch, now a U.S. citizen, is just one of
many entertainment industry giants actively acquiring programming
for the booming overseas market.
   The programming demand will be fueled by the coming deregulation
of European television and new satellite technologies. Overseas
audiences have demonstrated such an insatiable taste for U.S. films
and TV shows that European regulators are considering limiting how
many American productions can be shown after 1992, when European
trade barriers come down.
   According to proxy material mailed to MGM-UA shareholders
recently, Qintex and Fox were the final two suitors of a host of
companies that expressed interest in MGM-UA after it acknowledged in
April 1988 that it had received sale inquiries.
   Other companies that have been mentioned as being interested in
all or part of MGM-UA include Sony Corp., The Walt Disney Co., MCA
Inc., Polygram NV, The Cannon Group, Weintraub Entertainment Group,
former and present MGM-UA directors Alan Ladd Jr. and David Gerber.
   Qintex Australia owns 43 percent of Qintex Entertainment Inc., a
TV company that financed part of the CBS miniseries ``Lonesome
Dove'' and bills itself as Australia's largest TV production and
distribution company.
   The Qintex deal in essence would split MGM-UA, leaving MGM under
the control of Los Angeles billionaire Kirk Kerkorian, who owns 82
percent of MGM-UA's common stock and all but a tiny fraction of the
preferred stock. By the time Kerkorian bought back the MGM
businesses, Qintex would have paid about $600 million for United
Artists, plus assumed $400 million in debt.
</TEXT>
