<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 2343EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-DrugSuit     09-13 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Drug Suit,0230</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Cyanamid Sues Generic Drug Maker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WAYNE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Cyanamid Co. filed suit Wednesday
against Vitarine Pharmaceuticals Inc., claiming Vitarine misled the
federal government to obtain permits to produce generic drugs that
compete with American Cyanamid products.
   The lawsuit, filed in U.S. District Court in Newark, accuses
Vitarine of submitting false statements to the federal Food and Drug
Administration to win approval to manufacture several generic
versions of brand-name pharmaceuticals.
   The lawsuit contains charges similar to those recently leveled
against Vitarine and 10 other generic drug makers by FDA, which is
investigating fraud in the generic drug industry.
   The Vitarine drugs include a version of Maxzide, known
generically as triamterene-hydrochlorothiazide, a hypertension drug
exclusively distributed by Lederle Laboratories, a division of
American Cyanamid.
   The complaint accuses Vitarine, based in Springfield Gardens,
N.Y., of injurious interference with prospective economic advantage,
unfair competition and violations of the Racketeer Influenced and
Corrupt Organizations act, American Cyanamid said in a statement
from its headquarters here.
   The lawsuit seeks unspecified damages and an injuction against
Vitarine's using illegal means to obtain permits to manufacture
drugs produced or distributed by American Cyanamid.
   The FDA told Vitarine two weeks ago that it planned to revoke the
company's permits to manufacture 25 generic drugs because of untrue
statements in Vitarine applications, American Cyanamid said.
</TEXT>
