<FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 2359EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writethru f0298 09-13 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0298,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Edges Down, Share Prices Rise</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with morning Nikkei, comments.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar edged down against the Japanese yen
Thursday morning, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange
inched up.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues regained 30.59
points, or 0.09 percent, ending morning trading at 34,317.53. The
index had shed 45.94 points the previous day.
   The dollar ended morning trading at 145.75 yen. It started
trading at 146.05 yen, down 0.65 yen from Wednesday's 146.70-yen
close, and moved in a range of 145.50 to 146.43 yen.
   Currency dealers attributed the dollar's lower opening to its
overnight downswing, mainly against major European currencies, on
overseas markets.
   ``The dollar started falling against the yen as foreign investors
sold it against the West German mark,'' said a Bank of Tokyo trader,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The currency fell further as the Bank of Japan conducted a
dollar-selling intervention to halt the dollar's excessive rise when
some investors attempted to buy it back, he said.
   The Bank of Japan reportedly sold some $300 million. The central
bank does not comment on its monetary actions.
   Other traders said many market players were sitting on the
sidelines as the market awaited a spate of major U.S. economic
figures this week.
   Among major data to be released by the U.S. government were the
nation's August retail sales, due out later Thursday in Washington,
and the July merchandise trade figures, due Friday.
   On the stock exchange, the market's key index rose as market
players were reassured by the yen's recovery against the dollar,
said Kazuyuki Suzuki, a Daiwa Securities dealer.
   ``The yen's rebound pushed down the short-term interest rate
here, which also reassured participants and encouraged them to buy
stocks,'' he said.
   But trading was light ahead of a three-day weekend starting
Friday, Respect for the Aged Day, a national holiday, Suzuki said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
